1. e4
{ Hello chess-lover,  A warm welcome to my course: Attacking repertoire for club players: 1.e4. I am thrilled to share all the variations with you. My name is Midas Ratsma from the Netherlands. I am a FIDE-Master, full-time chess coach, and content developer. Also, I am the founder of the website @@LinkStart@@www.thechesscommunity.com@@LinkEnd@@, a place where chess players can connect for lessons from professional and passionate coaches and friendly training games. Thank you very much for buying the course. It’s exciting that you are about to learn 200 variations you must know to win with 1.e4. This is my first course for Chessable. I am also developing the complementary course for the Black pieces with the same concept, which will most likely be published around June/July. Combined, the courses provide a complete opening repertoire for everyone from beginner up to 1800-level.  During the work, I discovered the popularity of opening variations is totally different at the 1600-level compared to the high-amateur and top-level chess. This inspired me to discover the best way to get winning positions against 1600-level players in the opening. Based on a database I used with more than 50-million rapid and classical games at the 1600-level, the course should give you an over 80% chance to get a winning position against a 1600-level player. Looking forward to sharing the countless tricks that the typical 1600-rated opponent will fall for.     Studying 1600-level games, I discovered that the games almost never reach 15 moves of theory. So not to occupy your memory, we will never go beyond 15 moves of theory. The density of each chapter is based on how frequently it is played at the 1600-level. We start with the replies that you will face the most starting with 1…e5 and finishing with all the sidelines.   The video explanations sometimes go deeper than the trainable lines. This is designed not to overburden your memory with variations. The course is to the point and teaches you the 200 variations you must know to win with 1.e4. This knowledge should be sufficient for everyone under 1800-level, and it’s much more important to refresh and repeat the lines than to go deeper into the theory. And don’t forget that understanding all the ideas is much more essential than memorizing the moves, so try to either watch the videos or read everything thoroughly for the best learning experience.  “Chess is 99% tactics” is a famous quote by Richard Teichmann. Although 99% is a bit too much, tactics are indeed incredibly important, and tactical mistakes decide most games. Therefore, the course has tactics chapters to test your tactical knowledge directly after the theoretical chapters. In the Themed Based Tactics chapter, in the end, you can do a final tactic test repeating all tactics combinations in the course.  I did my utter best to explain all the moves and variations as clearly as possible. Surely it could be that you have questions, and you can place all your comments on Chessable by clicking on the moves of variations you have a question about. Every Monday, I will take the time to reply to all comments and update the course if necessary.      A few study tips. The Quickerstarter guide will teach you the 20 most important variations you must know to start playing the openings. Repeat the Quickerstarterguide until you master it before moving on with the next chapters. I would recommend studying the chapter in the order it is made and practicing the tactics chapter before moving on to the next theoretical chapter. The most convenient way to use the move trainer is to click on the learn next button, and after each variation, you can click on next or the space bar to study the next one. You can use the Browse Repertoire Tree option to quickly check the move recommendation after a tournament or online game. I recommend the Chessable default settings to study the variations.     Let’s not wait any longer and jump into the variations. I can’t wait to share the sneaky tricks and attacking variations which hopefully will bring you countless enjoyable victories. }
