1. e4 e5
{ 1.e4 e5 is called the Open Game or the Double King's Pawn Opening. This is by far the most popular reply at the 1600-level. We will immediately dive into the most important variations. Within the Open Game, we will most likely end up playing The Scotch Gambit covered in the first chapters. Alternatively, we could face the Petrov Defense, the Philidor Defense or the Latvian and Elephant Gambits. }
2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Gambit has similarities to the Italian opening. Instead of playing the Italian with  3.Bc4  we first play the @@StartBracket@@usually@@EndBracket@@ temporary pawn sacrifice  3.d4  and only after  3...exd4  do we go for  4.Bc4  . }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started. We play 4.Bc4 instead of  4.Nxd4  because we are going for quick development and castling.  Our bishop is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle; however, Black still needs to develop the knight and the bishop on the kingside to prepare to castle. }
4... Nf6
{ The best and most popular move. We now immediately put more pressure on our opponent by chasing away this knight. }
5. e5
{ Going for the knight-hunt. It will be a signature move in our repertoire to hunt knights placed on f6 or c6. The f6- and c6-squares are usually the best squares for Black's knights but we will attack them mercilessly. }
5... Qe7
{ This is a poor move. Black pins our e5-pawn, so we cannot capture the knight. As a rule of thumb, we will castle and play Re1 when Black tries to win our e5-pawn. }
6. O-O
{ After  6...Nxe5  7.Nxe5  Qxe5  8.Re1  pins the queen. White has a winning position. The most convincing way to beat Black is explained in theScotch Gambit chapter. }
