[Black "Scotch Gambit with 4...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ 1.e4 e5 is called the Open Game or the Double King's Pawn Opening. This is by far the most popular reply at the 1600-level. We will immediately dive into the most important variations. Within the Open Game, we will most likely end up playing The Scotch Gambit covered in the first chapters. Alternatively, we could face the Petrov Defense, the Philidor Defense or the Latvian and Elephant Gambits. }
2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Gambit has similarities to the Italian opening. Instead of playing the Italian with  3.Bc4  we first play the @@StartBracket@@usually@@EndBracket@@ temporary pawn sacrifice  3.d4  and only after  3...exd4  do we go for  4.Bc4  . }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started, we play  4.Bc4  instead of  4.Nxd4  because we are going for quick development and castling.  Our light-squared bishop on c4 is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle; however, Black still needs to develop the knight on g8 and the bishop on f8 to prepare to castle. }
4... Bc5
{ The second most popular move both at the top level as well as at the 1600-level. Black is defending the pawn on d4 and also preparing to castle. }
5. Ng5
{ It's time to give your opponent a heart attack! We don't allow Black to castle in this game. We are going for the f7-pawn and once we capture it with the knight, we fork the queen and the rook. The pressure on your opponent is huge and they only have one good move!   It's nice to know that Ng5 is only the third most popular move in the position, so probably your opponent won't be prepared. We only go for the Ng5 plan when Black plays ...Bc5 because this allows us a tactic with a fork on the king and the bishop. }
5... Nh6
{ The only good move for Black, defending the f7-pawn!  Against the frequently played  5...Ne5  at the 1600-level, we play  6.Nxf7  and White is already winning.   At the 1600-level  5...d5  is also often played when after  6.Bxd5  we gained a pawn and keep the threat of Nxf7. }
6. Nxf7
{ We shouldn't let your opponent recover from the big shock that we just gave them! We continue with our plan, even though Black just defended the pawn. }
6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+
{ Forking the king and bishop to gain back the piece. } 8... g6 9. Qxc5
{ So after 4...Bc5 we can force our opponent into this position where Black's king is exposed. By this time your opponent will be shocked and scared to death! We know that things are only going to get worse for them. All the details are explained elaborately in theScotch Gambit chapter. }
