[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ 1.e4 e5 is called the Open Game or the Double King's Pawn Opening. This is by far the most popular reply at the 1600-level. We will immediately dive into the most important variations. Within the Open Game, we will most likely end up playing The Scotch Gambit covered in the first chapters. Alternatively, we could face the Petrov Defense, the Philidor Defense or the Latvian and Elephant Gambits. }
2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Gambit has similarities to the Italian opening. Instead of playing the Italian with  3.Bc4  we first play the @@StartBracket@@usually@@EndBracket@@ temporary pawn sacrifice  3.d4  and only after  3...exd4  do we go for  4.Bc4  . }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started, we play  4.Bc4  instead of  4.Nxd4  because we are going for quick development and castling.  Our light-squared bishop on c4 is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle; however, Black still needs to develop the knight on g8 and the bishop on f8 to prepare to castle. }
4... h6
{ The most popular move in the 1600-rating database! At the 1600-level  4...h6  ,  4...Bc5  , and  4...Nf6  are all about equally popular. The move h6 shows that Black is struggling under the pressure of the Scotch Gambit and plays a prophylactic move to  prevent Ng5. h6 is a significant mistake since Black is ignoring their development! The f7-square is never fully safeguarded until Black has managed to castle.   The most popular move for White is  5.Nxd4  which gives White an advantage. This is very logical as now we have a normal Scotch Opening where we played an extra development move with Bc4, while Black wasted time with h6. I suggest castling instead, which leads to a massive lead in development! }
5. O-O
{ After  5...Bc5  we play  6.c3  forcing Black to play  6...dxc3  when we strike with  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  and regain the piece with  8.Qd5+  forking the king and the bishop.   After  5...Nf6  we play our standard knight-hunting attacking move  6.e5  . In both cases, we have a much better version of the main line since Black wasted time on playing ...h6.  You'll find the possible continuations starting from here. }
