1. e4 e5
{ 1.e4 e5 is called the Open Game or the Double King's Pawn Opening. This is by far the most popular reply at the 1600-level. We will immediately dive into the most important variations. Within the Open Game, we will most likely end up playing The Scotch Gambit covered in the first chapters. Alternatively, we could face the Petrov Defense, the Philidor Defense or the Latvian and Elephant Gambits. }
2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nf6
{ The Petrov Defense is on the board. This is usually a solid opening for Black. The Petrov has recently gained more popularity since Ian Nepomniatchi used it as the main repertoire in the 2021 World Championship Match against Magnus Carlsen. Also, Fabiano Caruana played the Petrov against Carlsen twice in the World Championship Match in 2018. }
3. d4
{ We play in a similar style as in the Scotch Gambit and start the fight in the center directly! I like this move a lot because it is putting pressure on Black and they have to make an important decision right away. }
3... exd4
{ As we already learned from playing the Scotch Gambit, we don't have to recapture the d4-pawn immediately. Instead, we go for our signature knight-hunting move. }
4. e5
{ Our signature move, hunting Black's knight.   If  4...Nd5  or  4...Ne4  we continue the knight hunt by playing  5.Qxd4  .   After  4...Ng4  we continue attacking the knight with  5.h3   After  4...Qe7  pinning the e5-pawn, we reinforce the threat on the knight with  5.Be2  .  You will find the possible continuations starting from here. }
