1. e4 e5
{ 1.e4 e5 is called the Open Game or the Double King's Pawn Opening. This is by far the most popular reply at the 1600-level. We will immediately dive into the most important variations. Within the Open Game, we will most likely end up playing The Scotch Gambit covered in the first chapters. Alternatively, we could face the Petrov Defense, the Philidor Defense or the Latvian and Elephant Gambits. }
2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense. This is the second most popular move at the 1600-level. This move is not so popular at the top level since Black blocks in their dark-squared bishop. }
3. d4
{ We open the center! Against Black's three main responses @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nc6  ,  2...Nf6  , and  2...d6  we always play  3.d4  . }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4
{ Our typical Scotch Gambit move  4.Bc4  makes less sense now. Black can continue with  4...Nf6  and our typical attacking idea with  5.e5  isn't possible anymore since Black plays  5...dxe5 }
4... Nf6 { Developing and attacking the pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ Developing and defending the pawn. We plan to play Bf4, Qd2, and O-O-O, when our rook will be strong on the semi-open d-file. In the Philidor Defense chapter these variations have been covered in detail. }
