1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian opening 1.e4 c5 is the second most popular choice at the 1600-level and is covered in several chapters, starting in this one. }
2. c3
{ The Alapin variation starts. We prepare to play d4 next and make it possible to recapture with the pawn to create a strong center. It's our goal to get our pawns on e4 and d4! }
2... Nc6
{ At the 1600-level the three most popular moves are  2...Nc6  ,  2...d6  , and  2...e6  , whereas  2...Nf6  and  2...d5  are the most popular at the top and high amateur levels. These differences show that Black has difficulties facing the Alapin at the 1600-level. }
3. d4
{ We continue our Alapin idea and get a strong center with pawns on e4 and d4. Also, we prepare to play d5 and immediately punish our opponent for placing the knight on c6. }
3... cxd4 4. cxd4
{ We managed to get both our pawns in the center. This makes it easy to develop and castle since we opened the diagonals for the bishops and the queen. Furthermore, our pawns in the center prevent our opponent from developing, castling, and getting their pawn in the center! Rule of thumb: Next move, we play d5 kicking the knight, regardless of what Black plays. }
4... e6
{ The most popular at the 1600-level. Let's punish it immediately. After  4...d5  5.exd5  Qxd5  6.Nf3  We transpose to the Barmen's defense, which will be covered here in the quickstarterguide. }
5. d5
{ We kick away the knight from its comfortable square.  You will find out more about this variation starting from here. }
