[Black "Alapin Sicilian with 2...d5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian opening 1.e4 c5 is the second most popular choice at the 1600-level and is covered in several chapters, starting in this one. }
2. c3
{ The Alapin variation starts. We prepare to play d4 next and make it possible to recapture with the pawn to create a strong center. It's our goal to get our pawns on e4 and d4! }
2... d5
{ This is one of the main variations for Black, called the Barmen Defense. Black aims to strike back in the center immediately. }
3. exd5
{ We want to capture in the center, forcing our opponent to bring the queen out. }
3... Qxd5 4. d4
{ This position is a perfect illustration of why the Alapin is my recommendation. Both bishops and the queen are entirely free to develop quickly. We have set up an excellent base for our future development by throwing the center pawns forward. If Black just makes one mistake, we will make sure that all our pieces are crushing through the opponent's position with lightning-fast development. }
4... cxd4
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level. This move is extremely dangerous for Black since our knight can develop with tempo after the trade of pawns, attacking the queen. }
5. cxd4 Nc6 6. Nf3
{ Developing and defending our d4-pawn. We plan to play Nc3 developing with tempo and after the queen moves, we want to go for the knight-hunt with d5!    This is covered in the Barmen Defense. }
