1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian opening 1.e4 c5 is the second most popular choice at the 1600-level and is covered in several chapters, starting in this one. }
2. c3
{ The Alapin variation starts. We prepare to play d4 next and make it possible to recapture with the pawn to create a strong center. It's our goal to get our pawns on e4 and d4! }
2... Nf6
{ Black attacks in the center which temporarily stops us from playing d4. } 3.
e5 { We counterattack the knight, forcing it to move again! } 3... Nd5 4. d4
{ We set up a perfect basis to be able to develop all the pieces. Both our bishops and queen are free to develop. }
4... cxd4 5. Nf3
{ We don't recapture the pawn yet and kindly invite Black to capture on c3. Like in the Scotch Gambit, we plan to play for Bc4 next, developing and putting pressure on the knight. Study more about this variation here.   After  5...dxc3  6.Qxd5  wins the knight! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction & Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "French Defense "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French 1.e4 e6 is the third most popular move at the 1600-level and is covered here. }
2. d4
{ Just like in the Alapin, we love to get our pawn on e4 and d4. With both pawns in the center, we can develop the bishops and the queen whenever we want, as well as go for our knight-hunting ideas. }
2... d5 { The idea of the French opening is to strike back in the center. } 3.
e5
{ We go for the Advance Variation in the French. When we play e5, Black's light-squared bishop is locked in by Black's pawn chain. Also, Black's knight can no longer develop to the most natural f6-square. }
3... c5
{ Black wants to attack and exchange the d4-pawn. If that happens, our e5-pawn would become weak. That's why we should defend this pawn. }
4. c3 { Supporting our d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6 5. Nf3
{ Developing and providing more protection to the d4-pawn. } 5... Qb6 6. Bd3
{ Setting up a trick for our opponent. After  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  Nxd4  8.Nxd4  Qxd4  9.Bb5+  wins the queen.   After  6...Bd7  we have a more subtle trick when after  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.O-O  by far the most popular move at the 1600-level blunders the bishop  8...Nge7  after  9.b4!   All these variations are discussed in much more detail in the chapter about the French opening. }
