[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction & Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Caro-Kann #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann is closely related to the French opening, and Black prepares to strike back in the center on the second move by playing d5.  You can find here the variations for the Caro-Kann. }
2. d4
{ We love to get our pawns on e4 and d4 when Black doesn't prevent us from doing so. }
2... d5 3. e5
{ Just like in the French Defense, we are going for the Advance Variation. The idea is to prevent Black from developing freely and with e5 we take away the natural f6-square for Black's knight. }
3... Bf5
{ Black's main idea of playing the Caro-Kann compared to the French is to make sure that the light-squared bishop can develop. In the French Advance Variation after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  we saw that the light-squared bishop was stuck behind the e6-pawn. }
4. h4
{ This move requires some explanation. Why do we push a pawn instead of playing a standard developing move like  4.Nf3?  The idea behind this move is prophylactic. It is just as essential to prevent our opponent from developing as it is for us to develop our pieces.  4.h4  prevents Black from playing  4...e6  and developing the dark-squared bishop, since after  5.g4  Be4  6.f3  Bg6  7.h5  the bishop is trapped.  You will find other continuations starting from here. }
