[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction & Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Scandinavian #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ In the Scandinavian opening Black immediately attacks our e4-pawn. The Scandinavian is covered here. }
2. exd5 { We capture the pawn, forcing Black's queen to recapture. } 2... Qxd5
3. d4
{ This move is not so popular. Nevertheless, it is in my opinion the most tricky way to play against the Scandinavian.  After the main move  3.Nc3  we develop with tempo, however, the downside is that Black's queen moves to a safer square.  With 3.d4 we are putting our pawn in the center and wait for the perfect moment to target Black's queen. }
3... Nc6
{ Black's main move and the most logical one. Black is targetting our d4-pawn. We are happy to see the knight on c6 because, as we have already learned in the Alapin, we can go knight-hunting and play d5 after chasing away Black's queen on d5. First, we should simply develop and defend the d4-pawn. }
4. Nf3
{ We develop and defend in the center. We are ready for our knight-hunting plan: attack the queen with either c4 or Nc3 and then play d5, attacking the knight. At this point, Black is in a tough spot, and they have to play multiple very strong moves to get a playable position. }
4... Bg4 { Developing and counter-attacking by pinning our knight. } 5. Nc3
{ Developing and attacking the queen. Black is in a tough spot now.  5...Qh5  is Black's only good move which is the sixth most popular move at the 1600-level. All the variations are extensively covered in the chapter on the Scandinavian. They start here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Scotch Gambit: Main Line with 4...Nf6"]
[Black "Chapter Summary Scotch gambit 4...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ 1.e4 e5 is called the Open Game or the Double King's Pawn Opening. This is by far the most popular reply at the 1600-level. We will immediately dive into the most important variations. Within the Open Game, we will most likely end up playing The Scotch Gambit covered in the first chapters. Alternatively, we could face the Petrov Defense, the Philidor Defense or the Latvian and Elephant Gambits. }
2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Gambit has similarities to the Italian opening. Instead of playing the Italian with  3.Bc4  we first play the usually temporary pawn sacrifise  3.d4  and only after  3...exd4  we go for  4.Bc4  . }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started, we play  4.Bc4  instead of  4.Nxd4  because we are going for quick development and castling. Our light-squared bishop on c4 is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle; however, Black still needs to develop the knight and the bishop on the kingside to prepare castling. }
4... Nf6
{ The best and most popular move, we immediately put more pressure on our opponent by chasing away this knight. }
5. e5
{ Going for the knight-hunt. This will be a signature move in our repertoire to hunt knights placed on f6 or c6. These squares are usually the best squares for Black's knights, and we will attack these knights mercilessly. }
5... d5
{ A difficult move for Black, since they didn't move their knight, which was under attack.   5...Qe7  This is a poor move from Black. As a rule of thumb, we will castle and play Re1 when Black tries to win our e5-pawn.  6.O-O  Nxe5  A big mistake, Black soon will be pinned on the e-file. First, we capture the knight.  7.Nxe5  Qxe5  8.Re1  Pinning the queen, Black must block the e-file with the knight.  8...Ne4  9.f4   The idea is that we want to eliminate the queen from defending the knight!  9.f3  attacking the pinned knight would also be winning; however, this move is less convincing since after  9...d5  Black is counterattacking on our bishop.  9...Qe7   9...Qf5  10.g4  This move looks risky! But who will attack our king?? Look at all Black's pieces on the back rank. Our move g4 attacks the queen and ensures that we will win the knight and crush our opponent mercilessly!  10...Qg6  The queen is still defending the knight, let's attack again.  11.f5  We keep on attacking the queen, we want to make it impossible for Black to keep defending the knight.  11...Qc6  And still the queen is defending! Now we will play a cunning move.  12.Qd3   A lovely move. We win the knight, and we play Rxe4 next move. Also, we set up a new trap when Black would defend by playing ...d5. Please don't play  12.Qxd4  when after  12...Bc5  Black is pinning and winning our queen.  12...d5  13.Bb5  Winning the queen and the game!  10.Nd2   Attacking the pinned knight!  10.Qd4  would also be crushing; this is even better.  10...f5  11.Nxe4  fxe4  12.Qxd4  Next move Rxe4 is coming, surely Black's king and queen won't be happy about this. White is winning.   5...Ng4  A logical move, Black is attacking the e5-pawn twice now, and we only have one defender.  6.O-O  We use the rule of thumb and castle since the e5-pawn gets attacked. This indirectly protects the e5-pawn because we have the idea to create a pin along the e-file.  6...Ngxe5   6...Be7  Black is reinforcing the threat to capture with ...Nxe5.  7.Re1  Defending the e5-pawn.  7...O-O  This logical move is a big strategical blunder.  8.h3  The knight is short of squares, so we attack it.  8...Nh6  9.Bxh6  Destroying the king's safety from Black!  9...gxh6  10.Nxd4  White wins back the pawn and has a much better position. Black has a weak pawn structure and an unsafe king.  7.Nxe5   It is crucial not to play  7.Re1  immediately, since after  7...d6  , Black defends the knight. If we play  8.Nxe5  now Black plays  8...dxe5  and has no problems.   7.Re1  d6  8.Nxe5  dxe5  7...Nxe5  8.Re1  Pinning the knight.  8...d6  9.f4   Winning the knight! The knight is pinned and cannot run away. A game of one of my chess students continued with  9...Bg4  attacking the queen. My student gladly played  10.Qxg4  since the knight is pinned. Black decided to resign immediately!   5...Ne4  This best square for the knight, that's why we attack the knight immediately.  6.Qe2  Nc5   After  6...d5  , we can use the rule of en passant and play  7.exd6  gaining a pawn and keeping the attack on the knight.   6...Bb4+  7.Kd1  This looks strange but is an important move that gives White an advantage. The idea is that the Black's knight is short of squares, and we don't want to trade it by placing a piece on d2.  7...Nc5  A big blunder  8.a3  We are winning a piece now!  8...Ba5  9.Bg5   9.b4  was also winning, but this is even stronger, developing with tempo to attack the queen.  9...Ne7  10.b4  Forking the bishop and the knight to win a piece.  7.O-O  Be7  8.Rd1  Planning to regain the d4-pawn.  8...O-O  9.Nxd4  Nxd4  10.Rxd4  White has more control in the center and a slight advantage! It's time to wake up all our sleeping pieces on the queenside. }
6. Bb5
{ A nice move to save our bishop and create a pin on the knight, we will soon regain the d4-pawn and are ready to castle quickly. }
6... Ne4 7. Nxd4
{ We recapture the pawn and increase the pressure on the pinned knight. } 7...
Bd7
{ 7...Bc5   A tricky and strong move from Black,  8.Nxc6  is dangerous because  8...Bxf2+  is possible.  8.Be3  We develop and both defend on d4 and f2.  8...O-O   8...Bd7  9.Bxc6  We need to eliminate the knight to prevent Black from capturing on d4, we give Black doubled pawns.  9...bxc6  10.O-O  White maintains nice attacking chances in this position! The attacking ideas are similar, as we will discuss in the mainline later in this chapter.  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.Bxc5  Nxc5  11.Bxc6  Rb8  12.Qxd5  White is doing fine here since we are two pawns up! With precise play, Black can regain the pawns and hold the balance. When we castle quickly with White, we can never be in danger. }
8. Bxc6
{ We have to capture the knight with our bishop After  8.O-O?  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd7+  Qxd7  10.Qxd4  Bc5  Black gains a tempo and attacks our queen.   If we would play  8.Nxc6  the problem is that after  8...bxc6  gains a tempo for Black by attacking our bishop. }
8... bxc6 9. O-O
{ It's always a nice feeling to castle much faster than your opponent. } 9...
Bc5 10. f3
{ It's our attacking plan to play f3-f4-f5! Depending on Black's play, we can choose later if we want to attack with f6 or e6. Note that we shouldn't play  10.f4  immediately since  10.f3  kicks Black's knight from its beautiful square on e4. }
10... Ng5 11. f4
{ Again attacking the knight, and now we make sure that the f4-pawn protects the e5-pawn. }
11... Ne4
{ 11...Ne6  12.c3  An important move to defend our knight!  12...O-O  The most popular move in the 1600rating database, and now White is winning.  13.f5  We continue our attacking plan with another tempo on the knight.  13...Nxd4  14.cxd4  Gaining another tempo.  14...Be7  15.Qf3   15.f6  would have been premature since after  15...gxf6  we lose the pawn. With Qf3 we prepared to play f6; if Black allows that, we will give mate by bringing the queen to  g7!   After  15...f6  we play  16.e6!  securing a strong protected past pawn on the 6th rank! Also, we can still go for Qg4, Bh6 and Qg7#, mate. White has a winning position the computer gives  +3. }
12. Be3
{ This is a nice development move that breaks the pin on the knight. If Black plays  12...Bb6  13.Nd2  c5  14.N4f3  Nxd2  15.Qxd2  d4  16.Bf2  We can play c3 at some point to exchange the d4-pawn; also, we should activate our rook on a1 to d1 or e1.   After  12...Qb8  , we go  13.b3  to prevent Black from capturing the b2-pawn. }
12... O-O 13. Nd2
{ Black's knight on e4 was strong. We cannot attack the knight with a pawn since we don't have a d-pawn and the f-pawn is already on f4. That's why we would love to exchange this knight. }
13... Nxd2 14. Qxd2
{ This develops the queen and makes space for the rook on a1 to come to the center. }
14... Bb6 { Black prepares an attack with ...c5 and ...d4. } 15. Nb3
{ A beautiful strategical move. We make sure that we control the c5-square with our knight and bishop, stopping Black's central pawns from advancing. I like this position for White. Black's light-squared bishop pair is not powerful since it is stuck behind the c6-pawn. We have a true master plan. Our idea is to bring our last rook into the game to e1, supporting the center. Then we like to play f5 and f6. The last step is to bring the queen to g7 with mate!! The computer indicates that Black's only good move is  15...f6  White has many ways to play, but I like  16.Bd4  fxe5  17.fxe5  Qe7  18.Qe3!  Preventing Black from playing ...c5. }
