1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Gambit has similarities to the Italian opening. Instead of playing the Italian with  3.Bc4  we first play the @@StartBracket@@usually@@EndBracket@@ temporary pawn sacrifice  3.d4  and only after  3...exd4  do we go for  4.Bc4  . }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started. We play  4.Bc4  instead of  4.Nxd4  because we are going for quick development and castling.  Our bishop is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle; however, Black still needs to develop the knight and the bishop on the kingside to prepare to castle. }
4... Nf6
{ The best and most popular move. We now immediately put more pressure on our opponent by chasing away this knight. }
5. e5
{ Going for the knight hunt. It will be a signature move in our repertoire to hunt knights placed on f6 or c6. These squares are usually the best squares for Black's knights, and we will attack these knights mercilessly. }
5... Qe7
{ This is a poor move from Black. As a rule of thumb, we will castle and bring the rook to e1 when Black tries to win our e5-pawn. }
6. O-O Nxe5
{ A big mistake, as Black will soon be pinned on the e-file. First, we capture the knight. }
7. Nxe5 Qxe5 8. Re1
{ Pinning the queen, so Black must block the e-file with the knight. } 8... Ne4
9. f4
{ The idea is that we want to eliminate the queen from defending the knight!  9.f3  attacking the pinned knight would also be winning; however, this move is less convincing since after  9...d5  Black is counterattacking our bishop. }
9... Qf5 10. g4
{ This move looks risky! But who will attack our king?? Look at all of Black's pieces on the back rank. Our move attacks the queen and ensures that we will win the knight and crush our opponent mercilessly! }
10... Qg6 { The queen is still defending the knight, let's attack again. } 11.
f5
{ We keep on attacking the queen. We want to make it impossible for Black to keep defending the knight. }
11... Qc6
{ And still, the queen is defending! Now we will play a cunning move. } 12. Qd3
{ A lovely move. We win the knight and we play Rxe4 next. Also, we set up a new trap in case Black defends by playing d5.   Please don't play  12.Qxd4  when  12...Bc5  pins and wins our queen. }
12... d5 13. Bb5 { Winning the queen and the game! } *

