1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Gambit has similarities to the Italian opening. Instead of playing the Italian with  3.Bc4  we first play the @@StartBracket@@usually@@EndBracket@@ temporary pawn sacrifice  3.d4  and only after  3...exd4  do we go for  4.Bc4  . }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started. We play  4.Bc4  instead of  4.Nxd4  because we are going for quick development and castling.  Our bishop is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle; however, Black still needs to develop the knight and the bishop on the kingside to prepare to castle. }
4... Nf6
{ The best and most popular move. We now immediately put more pressure on our opponent by chasing away this knight. }
5. e5
{ Going for the knight hunt. It will be a signature move in our repertoire to hunt knights placed on f6 or c6. These squares are usually the best squares for Black's knights, and we will attack these knights mercilessly. }
5... d5
{ A difficult move to find for Black since they didn't move their knight, which was under attack. }
6. Bb5
{ A nice move to save our bishop pin the knight. We will soon regain the d4-pawn and are ready to castle quickly. }
6... Ne4 7. Nxd4
{ We recapture the pawn and increase the pressure on the pinned knight. } 7...
Bd7 { The main move in this position. } 8. Bxc6
{ We have to capture the knight with our bishop. After  8.O-O?  Nxd4  9.Bxd7+  Qxd7  10.Qxd4  Bc5  Black gains a tempo and attacks our queen.   If we play  8.Nxc6  the problem is that  8...bxc6  gains a tempo for Black by attacking our bishop. }
8... bxc6 9. O-O
{ It's always a nice feeling to castle much faster than your opponent. } 9...
Bc5 10. f3
{ Our attacking plan is to play f3, f4, f5! Depending on Black's play, we can choose later if we want to attack with f6 or e6. Note that we shouldn't play  10.f4  immediately since 10.f3 kicks Black's knight from its beautiful e4-square. }
10... Ng5 11. f4 { Marching the pawn forward and attacking the knight again. }
11... Ne6 12. c3 { An important move to defend our knight! } 12... O-O
{ The most popular move in the 1600-rating database, and now White is already winning. After  12...f5  we play  13.Na3!  We want to bring the knight to c2 supporting the d4-knight. The trade after  13...Bxa3  14.bxa3  is  good for White since Black lost their powerful dark-squared bishop and remains with a bad bishop. }
13. f5 { We continue our attacking plan with another tempo on the knight. }
13... Nxd4 14. cxd4 { Gaining another tempo. } 14... Be7 15. Qf3
{ 15.f6  would have been premature since after  15...gxf6  we lose the pawn.  With Qf3 we prepared to play f6. If Black allows that, we will give mate by bringing the queen to g7!   After  15...f6  we play  16.e6!  securing a strong protected past pawn on the 6th rank!  Also, we can still go for Qg4, Bh6, and Qg7 mate. White has a winning position, and the computer gives +3. }
