[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Scotch Gambit: Main Line with 4...Nf6 Tactics "]
[Black "Exercise 6: Scotch Gambit 4...Nf6 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n5/4P3/1bBpn3/5N2/PPP1QPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What would you play here? } 1. Kd1 f5
{ This is the best move for Black since  1...Nc5  doesn't work, as shown in the previous tactic. }
2. exf6
{ We should make use of the en-passant rule! Now we are attacking the knight and the g7-pawn.  The game could continue with  2...d5  3.fxg7  Rg8  4.Nbd2  dxc4  5.Qxe4  with a large opening advantage for White.   In case of @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n5/4P3/1bBpn3/5N2/PPP1QPPP/RNBK3R b kq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  we should also capture en-passant with  2.exd6  winning the pawn and reinforcing the threat on the knight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Scotch Gambit: 4...Bc5"]
[Black "Chapter Summary: Scotch Gambit 4...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Bc5
{ The second most popular move both at the top-level and at the 1600-level. Black is defending the d4-pawn and also preparing to castle. }
5. Ng5
{ It's time to give your opponent a heart attack! We don't allow Black to castle in this game. We are going for the f7-pawn, and once we capture the knight, we fork the queen and the rook. The pressure on your opponent is huge, and they only have one good move! It's nice to know that Ng5 is only the third most popular move in the position, so probably your opponent won't be prepared. We only go for the Ng5 plan when Black plays ...Bc5, because this allows us a tactic with a fork on the king and bishop. }
5... Nh6
{ The only good move for Black defending the f7-pawn!   5...d5  This doesn't help Black either as we capture the pawn and keep the same threat.  6.Bxd5  f7 is again under attack.  6...Be6  The most played move in the 1600 rating database and we will reach a winning position very quickly.  7.Nxe6  We capture the bishop.  7...fxe6  8.Bxc6+  After we trade the bishop for the knight, we have a nice trick coming up.  8...bxc6  9.Qh5+  Forking the king and bishop!!  9...g6  10.Qxc5  White has an excellent position and is a full piece up.   5...Ne5  A very logical move for Black, attacking the bishop and defending the f7-pawn. Still, this move is a blunder from Black!  6.Nxf7  We shouldn't let your opponent recover from the big shock we gave them! We continue with our plan, even though Black just defended the pawn!  6...Nxf7  7.Bxf7+  Kxf7  8.Qh5+  Our tactical justification, we fork the king and the bishop and win back the piece. White is in a much better position because Black's king is in a lot of trouble.  8...g6  9.Qd5+  Before taking the bishop, we give one more check to force the king to a worse square.  9...Kg7  10.Qxc5  White is ready to go Qxd4+ next move and has a great position! This position is a much better version than we will get in the mainline, where we will have a similar position, but in that case, Black's knight is on c6 instead of g8! }
6. Nxf7
{ We shouldn't let your opponent recover from the big shock we gave them! We continue with our plan, even though Black just defended the pawn! }
6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+
{ The same tactic! Forking the king and bishop to gain back the piece. } 8...
g6
{ 8...Kg8  9.Qd5+  A nice intermediate move! We want to make sure that we capture the bishop with a check.  9...Kf8  10.Qxc5+  The same variation could be reached if Black played ...Kf8 immediately.  10...d6  11.Qb5  Again attacking the b7-pawn to prevent the bishop from developing. }
9. Qxc5
{ We forced our opponent into this position where the Black's king is exposed. By this time, your opponent will be shocked and scared to death! We know that things are only going to get worse for them. Note that this is the only moment we don't give the intermediate check before capturing the bishop because after  9.Qd5+  Kg7  10.Qxc5  we would improve the position of Black's king! In the sideline, where the position was exactly similar with the only difference that the knight is on g8 instead of c6, it would be good to chase the king to g7 because then Qxd4+ is a threat! }
9... d6
{ The main move at the 1600-level. Black is attacking the queen and preparing to develop the bishop!   9...Re8  A very logical move by Black, attacking the e4-pawn! This is the second most popular move in the 1600rating-database! However, this is a mistake; let's crush our opponent.  10.Qd5+  We start with this useful check to support our e4-pawn, defending against Black's idea of Rxe4+.  10...Re6   10...Kf8  This square for the king isn't any better.  11.Bh6+  Ke7  12.Bg5+  Again winning the queen and the game.   10...Kg7  11.Bg5  We kindly ask our opponent how they want to defend the queen. In the 1600rating-database almost everyone blocks with the knight.  11...Rxe4+  This is Black's best move sacrificing the rook!   11...Ne7  12.Qxd4+  Grabbing the pawn with check, we are crushing our opponent!  12...Kg8  13.Nc3   13.Bh6  with the threat of Qg7# mate would have been a bit premature, since after  13...Nf5  Black forks the queen and bishop and defends the mate. The computer claims that even in that case, White is winning. This is much stronger! Black's knight is pinned, the king is weak. We will play Nd5 and Nf6+ next. The computer gives +8 it's time to resign for Black.  12.Qxe4  Qxg5  Black is threatening Qc1+  13.O-O  d5  Developing with tempo  14.Qf3  White has a huge advantage. We want to trick our opponent into making another mistake.  14...Bg4  Very logical developing with tempo and attacking the queen.  15.Qg3  Pinning the bishop! We threaten to play h3 and win the bishop. Also, we threaten to capture the c7-pawn with a check and subsequently capture the b7-pawn! Black wants to cry and cannot defend against all the threats. White is winning, and the computer gives +5.  11.O-O  Black's rook is pinned, the king is still weak! White has a huge advantage. We like to play c3 and get our knight into the game after a trade! }
10. Qc4+
{ Usually, we always reply with Qb5! The idea was to attack the b7-pawn and restrict the bishop from developing. In this case, we don't play  10.Qb5  because after  10...Re8  11.O-O  Rxe4  Black wins the e4-pawn. }
10... Be6 11. Qe2
{ Why did we give Black time to develop the bishop and subsequently go backward with the queen, this doesn't look smart! Our reason is that Black planned to play ...Re8 and attack the e4-pawn. This is no longer possible since their bishop is blocking the e-file. }
11... Rf8 12. O-O
{ White plans to play f3 to stabilize the center. Also, c3 to exchange Black's central pawn and develop our knight to c3. Our bishop can come to h6 attacking the rook! When we wake up our sleeping army on the queenside, then eventually White will get a great position because our king is much safer than Black's king! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Scotch Gambit: 4...Bc5"]
[Black "Scotch Gambit: 4...Bc5 with 5...Qf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Gambit has similarities to the Italian opening. Instead of playing the Italian with  3.Bc4  we first play the @@StartBracket@@usually@@EndBracket@@ temporary pawn sacrifice  3.d4  and only after  3...exd4  do we go for  4.Bc4  . }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started. We play  4.Bc4  instead of  4.Nxd4  because we are going for quick development and castling.  Our bishop is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle; however, Black still needs to develop the knight and the bishop on the kingside to prepare to castle. }
4... Bc5
{ The second most popular move both at the top level as well as at the 1600-level. Black is defending the pawn on d4 and also preparing to castle. }
5. Ng5
{ It's time to give your opponent a heart attack! We don't allow Black to castle in this game. We are going for the f7-pawn and once we capture it with the knight, we fork the queen and the rook. The pressure on your opponent is huge and they only have one good move!   It's nice to know that Ng5 is only the third most popular move in the position, so probably your opponent won't be prepared. We only go for the Ng5 plan when Black plays …Bc5 because this allows us a tactic with a fork on the king and the bishop. }
5... Qf6 { This move is bad! Black is just playing for one cheap trick. } 6.
Nxf7 { Winning the pawn and trapping the rook in the corner. } 6... d3
{ Black is preparing the cheap trick Qxf2 mate. } 7. O-O
{ We defend against the mate and kindly remind Black that we can still capture the rook in the corner on the next move because it cannot run away! The computer gives +7. It is time to resign for Black. }
