{ The Scotch Gambit has similarities to the Italian opening. Instead of playing the Italian with  3.Bc4  we first play the @@StartBracket@@usually@@EndBracket@@ temporary pawn sacrifice  3.d4  and only after  3...exd4  do we go for  4.Bc4  . }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started. We play  4.Bc4  instead of  4.Nxd4  because we are going for quick development and castling.  Our bishop is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle; however, Black still needs to develop the knight and the bishop on the kingside to prepare to castle. }
4... Bc5
{ The second most popular move both at the top level as well as at the 1600-level. Black is defending the pawn on d4 and also preparing to castle. }
5. Ng5
{ It's time to give your opponent a heart attack! We don't allow Black to castle in this game. We are going for the f7-pawn and once we capture it with the knight, we fork the queen and the rook. The pressure on your opponent is huge and they only have one good move!   It's nice to know that Ng5 is only the third most popular move in the position, so probably your opponent won't be prepared. We only go for the Ng5 plan when Black plays …Bc5 because this allows us a tactic with a fork on the king and the bishop. }
5... Nh6 { The only good move for Black, defending the f7-pawn. } 6. Nxf7
{ We shouldn't let your opponent recover from the big shock that we just gave them! We continue with our plan, even though Black just defended the pawn. }
6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+
{ The same tactic! Forking the king and bishop to gain back the piece. } 8...
g6 9. Qxc5
{ So after 4.Bc5 we can force our opponent into this position where Black's king is exposed. By this time, your opponent will be shocked and scared to death! We know that things are only going to get worse for them.   Note that this is the only moment where we didn't give the intermediate check before capturing the bishop, because after  9.Qd5+  Kg7  10.Qxc5  we would improve the position of Black's king!  In a sideline,  in which the position is almost the same, with the only difference that the knight is on g8 instead of c6, it is good to chase the king to g7, because then Qxd4+ is a threat. }
9... Re8
{ A very logical move by Black, attacking the e4-pawn! This is the second most popular move in the 1600- rating database! However, this is a mistake, so let's crush our opponent. }
10. Qd5+
{ We start with this very useful check to support our e4-pawn, defending against Black's idea of Rxe4. }
10... Kg7 11. Bg5
{ We kindly ask our opponent how they want to defend the queen. In the 1600-rating database, almost everyone blocks with the knight. }
11... Ne7 12. Qxd4+
{ Grabbing the pawn with check. We are crushing our opponent! } 12... Kg8 13.
Nc3
{ 13.Bh6  with the threat of Qg7 mate would have been a bit premature, since after  13...Nf5  Black forks the queen and bishop and defends the mate. The computer claims that even in that case, White is winning.  The text move is much stronger! Black's knight is pinned and the king is weak. We threaten Nd5 increasing the pressure on the pinned knight. The computer gives +8 and it's time to resign for Black. My student Tom won his model game from this position. }
