{ So after 4.Bc5 we can force our opponent into this position where Black's king is exposed. By this time, your opponent will be shocked and scared to death! We know that things are only going to get worse for them.   Note that this is the only moment where we didn't give the intermediate check before capturing the bishop, because after  9.Qd5+  Kg7  10.Qxc5  we would improve the position of Black's king!  In a sideline,  in which the position is almost the same, with the only difference that the knight is on g8 instead of c6, it is good to chase the king to g7, because then Qxd4+ is a threat. }
9... d6
{ The main move at the 1600-level. Black is attacking the queen and preparing to develop the bishop. }
10. Qc4+
{ Usually, we always reply with Qb5! The idea is to attack the b7-pawn and restrict the bishop from developing. In this case, we don't play  10.Qb5  because after  10...Re8  11.O-O  Rxe4  Black wins the e4-pawn. }
10... Be6 11. Qe2
{ Why did we give Black time to develop the bishop and subsequently go backward with the queen? This doesn't look smart, does it? Our reason is that Black planned to play Re8 and attack the e4-pawn. Now, this is no longer possible since their bishop on e6 is blocking the e-file. }
11... Rf8 12. O-O
{ White plans to play f3 to stabilize the center. Also, c3 to exchange Black's central pawn and develop our knight to c3. Our bishop can come to h6, attacking the rook. When we wake up our sleeping army on the queenside, we will eventually get a great position because our king is much safer than Black's! }
