[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scotch Gambit: Sidelines"]
[Black "Chapter Summary: Scotch Gambit Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4
{ 3...d6  The second most popular move in the 1600rating-database. Black immediately gets into trouble.  4.dxe5  dxe5   After  4...Nxe5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Black lost its right to castle  7.Bc4  develops and attacks the f7-pawn.  5.Qxd8+  Black can choose either to give up their right to castle or give us the pawn.  5...Kxd8   5...Nxd8  This doesn't make sense for Black  6.Nxe5  White is a clean pawn up and has a significant advantage!  6.Bc4  Let's develop and attack.  6...Ke8  7.O-O  There is no need to explain why White is better.   3...Nxd4  It's not so strong for Black to capture with the knight!  4.Nxd4  We are happy to trade the knights.  4...exd4  5.Qxd4   White is better since the queen on d4 is strong and can not easily be attacked. Our queen is attacking the g7-pawn, preventing Black's bishop from developing.  5...Nf6  is not possible either because it runs again into  6.e5!   5...c5  would be a horrible move from a strategic point of view because after  6.Qd3  Black has given up all control over the d5-square, which is an excellent outpost for our knight. The computer already gives  +2. }
4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started, we play Bc4 instead of Nxd4 because we are going for quick development and castling. Our bishop is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle, however, Black still needs to develop the knight and the bishop on the kingside to prepare castling. }
4... h6
{ The most popular move in the 1600rating-database! On the 1600-level  4...h6  ,  4...Bc5  , and  4...Nf6  are all about equally popular. The move ...h6 shows that Black is struggling under the pressure of the Scotch Gambit and plays a prophylactic move to prevent Ng5. ...h6 is a significant mistake since Black is ignoring its development! The f7-square is never fully safeguarded until Black has managed to castle.   The most popular move for White is  5.Nxd4  gives White an advantage; this is very logical as now we have a normal Scotch Opening where we played an extra development move with Bc4 while Black wasted time with ...h6. I suggest castling instead, gaining a massive lead in development!   4...Bb4+  Objectively the best sideline for Black! Black is developing and immediately giving a check.  5.c3  We counterattack directly on the bishop, not giving our opponent any time to stabilize.  5...dxc3  6.O-O  We know the importance of lightning-fast development  6...cxb2  7.Bxb2   Our bishops are monsters aiming at the f7 and g7-squares! Our queen can join on b3 to put extra pressure on f7. After Black plays  7...Nf6  , we still have our typical attacking reply  8.e5!  7...Nf6  8.e5  Ne4  9.a3   9.Qd5  would also have been crushing. Before we play that, we first want to chase the bishop to a worse square.  9...Ba5  10.Qd5   Threatening Qxf7 mate as well as to capture the knight. If Black plays  10...Ng5  , we play  11.Nxg5  White has a winning position.   4...Be7  Black is trying to play it safe, developing the bishop and also preventing Ng5. We will make sure Black's position will be anything but safe.  5.c3  A very sneaky move, opening up the position to attack with all our pieces.  5...dxc3  6.Nxc3   The super attractive move  6.Qd5  threatening mate on f7 looks more promising than it is. After  6...Nh6  7.Bxh6  O-O  Black suddenly threatens to capture the b2-pawn, trapping the rook and capturing the bishop on h6. After  6.Nxc3  , our point is that Black still has difficulties developing the knight and isn't able to castle yet.  6...Nf6   6...d6  7.Qb3   When Black plays  7...Be6  , we play  8.Bxe6  fxe6  we play  9.Qxb7!!  Black's position is collapsing.  7.e5  We play our signature knight-hunting move.  7...Ng4  8.Qd5  Threatening Qxf7 mate.  8...O-O  Even though Black has castled, Black's king is still in a lot of danger.  9.h3  Chasing away the knight to a worse square.  9...Nh6   9...Nb4  The most popular move at the 1600-level  10.Qe4   White has a winning position. The game could continue with  10...Nh6  11.Bxh6  destroying Black's pawn structure in front of the king  11...gxh6  12.O-O-O  Getting a strong rook on the d-file, the computer gives  +5.  10.Bxh6  Weakening Black's pawn structure in front of the king.  10...gxh6  11.Qe4  Threatening Bd3 and Qxh7 mate! White has a winning position.   4...d6   This prevents the e5 push we always play when Black develops with ...Nf6! Usually, we keep our knight on f3 to play e5. For example, after  4...Nf6  5.e5  our knight on f3 is defending the e5-pawn. Since our knight is no longer needed on f3, we recapture the d4-pawn.  5.Nxd4  White has a great version of the Scotch opening! Bc4 was much more useful than ...d6 since we developed the bishop and are ready to castle while instead, Black just played ...d6, blocking its dark-squared bishop!  5...Nxd4  6.Qxd4  Nf6  7.Nc3  Be7  8.Bf4  O-O  9.O-O-O  c5  10.Qd2  . }
5. O-O
{ Isn't it lovely to watch our opponent's king in the middle of the board knowing that we have just castled! Our idea is that Black isn't ready to develop their knight and bishop on the kingside. }
5... Bc5
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level, and a very logical one! Black tries to hold on to the d4-pawn to compensate for the lack of development.   5...Nf6  6.e5  Our signature knight-hunting move. The ideas are similar to the mainline; however, with castle and ...h6 included, it is a much better version for White. Also, we see the advantage of keeping our knight on f3, allowing us to play e5 since the pawn is protected.  6...d5   6...Ng4  From the mainline, we already know that the knight cannot capture on e5, so let's force the knight to do that!  7.h3  Ngxe5   After  7...h5  8.hxg4  hxg4  Black wants to play ...Qh4 and ...Qh1 mate after we move our knight! We play  9.Ng5!  Blocking the queen and White has a winning position.  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.Re1  Pinning the knight.  9...d6  10.f4  Adding another attacker to make sure we will win the knight.  7.Bb5  Our plans don't change here compared to the mainline! White has a fantastic position due to the inclusion of ...h6 and O-O. }
6. c3
{ Preparing to regain the d4-pawn, attack the bishop and get a massive center! }
6... dxc3 7. Bxf7+
{ Black's strategy failed! Black played ...h6 with the idea to prevent any tactics on the f7-square. }
7... Kxf7 8. Qd5+
{ Forking the king and the bishop! This pattern with a sacrifice on f7 followed up with a fork on the king and bishop we frequently see in the Scotch Gambit. }
8... Ke8
{ By far the most popular move at the 1600-level, however, not it is not the best. }
9. Qxc5 d6
{ Black attacks the queen and opens the diagonal for the bishop.   9...cxb2  Black is greedy and captures another pawn.  10.Bxb2  We threaten Bxg7 with a devastating attack.  10...Nf6   10...d6  Black attacks the queen and opens the diagonal for the bishop.  11.Qh5+  With this powerful check, we make Black's king move for the third time.  11...Kf8  Black defends the g7-pawn.  12.Nh4   We threaten Ng6+ forking the king and the rook. After  12...Nf6  13.Ng6+  Kg8  14.Qb5  We threaten to capture the rook as well as Qb3+ to continue harassing the king.  11.e5  Again we go for the signature knight-hunting move.  11...d6  Black attacks the queen and opens the diagonal for the bishop.  12.Qb5  Pinning the knight and maintaining the pressure on the other knight. Black is in big trouble, and the computer evaluates this as +6. }
10. Qh5+
{ With this powerful check we make Black's king move for the third time. }
10... Kf8 11. Nh4
{ This position arises once Black plays 11 times the most popular move at the 1600-level. So we likely get this position on the board. We are threatening Ng6+ forking the king and the rook. White has a winning position. The game could continue with  11...Nf6  12.Ng6+  Kg8  13.Qb5  Black's king and rook are in an awful position crammed in the corned.   We threaten to capture the rook as well as to continue harassing the king with Qb3+ If Black defends against the fork with  11...Ne5  we play  12.f4  chasing the knight with a winning position. }
*

