{ 9.a3 is stronger than the more natural  9.Qd5  threatening the knight and mate since after  9...Ng5  10.Nxg5  Qxg5  11.Qxf7+  Kd8  12.e6  Rf8  Black forces a trade of queens and reaches an equal position.   After  9.a3  we first chase the bishop to a worse square to play Qd5 after. The game continues with  9...Ba5  10.Qd5  Ng5  11.Nxg5  Qxg5  12.Qxf7+  Kd8  13.e6  and White has a crushing attack and winning position. }
9... Ba5 10. Qd5
{ Threatening Qxf7 mate as well as to capture the knight. If Black plays  10...Ng5  we play  11.Nxg5  .  White has a winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scotch Gambit: Sidelines"]
[Black "Scotch Gambit: 4...Bb4+ #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Gambit has similarities to the Italian opening. Instead of playing the Italian with  3.Bc4  we first play the @@StartBracket@@usually@@EndBracket@@ temporary pawn sacrifice  3.d4  and only after  3...exd4  do we go for  4.Bc4  . }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started. We play  4.Bc4  instead of  4.Nxd4  because we are going for quick development and castling.  Our bishop is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle; however, Black still needs to develop the knight and the bishop on the kingside to prepare to castle. }
4... Bb4+
{ Objectively the best sideline for Black! Black is developing and immediately giving a check. }
5. c3
{ We directly counterattack the bishop, not giving our opponent any time to stabilize. }
5... dxc3 6. O-O { We know the importance of lightning-fast development. } 6...
d6 7. a3
{ Setting up a little trick, since the intermediate move  7...cxb2  8.Bxb2  Ba5  9.Bxg7  wins for White. We threaten to capture the bishop and the g7-pawn to trap the rook. }
7... Ba5 { 8...Bc5  9.b4  Bb6  would transpose to the same position. } 8. b4
{ We want to regain the c3-pawn without getting a weak pawn structure. After  8.Nxc3  Bxc3  9.bxc3  our pawn structure would be broken. }
8... Bb6 9. Qb3
{ Increasing the pressure on the f7-pawn! There is no need to recapture the pawn immediately as will we win the pawn anyway. }
9... Be6 { This is the best move for Black, a very difficult move to find. }
10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Qxe6+ { Capturing the pawn with a check! } 11... Qe7 12. Qb3
{ Black cannot play  12...Qxe4  since  13.Re1  wins the queen!  White is ready to play Nxc3 next and has a nice position. }
*

