[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scotch Gambit: Sidelines"]
[Black "Scotch gambit: 4...d6#1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started. We play Bc4 instead of Nxd4 because we are going for quick development and castling. Our bishop is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle, however, Black still needs to develop the knight and the bishop on the kingside to prepare castling. }
4... d6
{ This prevents the e5-push, which we always play when Black develops with Nf6! Usually, we keep our knight on f3 to play e5.   For example, if  4...Nf6  5.e5!  our knight on f3 is defending the e5-pawn. Since our knight is no longer needed on f3, we recapture the d4-pawn. Check out how I achieved a dominating position in this variation in this model game. }
5. Nxd4
{ White has a great version of the Scotch opening! Bc4 was much more useful than ...d6 since we developed the bishop and are ready to castle while instead Black just blocked their dark-squared bishop with d6. }
5... Nxd4
{ At the 1600-level, Black's most popular move is to trade the knights. } 6.
Qxd4 { Our queen is nicely placed! } 6... Qf6
{ Black proposes a trade of queens. } 7. Qd3
{ We decline the queen trade! White is ready to castle and play Nc3-Nd5 attacking the queen and c7-pawn. Black's queen is misplaced, blocking the natural square for the knight.   7.Qxf6  would be a mistake since it would help Black develop with  7...Nxf6  . }
*

