{ The Scotch Gambit has started. We play Bc4 instead of Nxd4 because we are going for quick development and castling. Our bishop is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle, however, Black still needs to develop the knight and the bishop on the kingside to prepare castling. }
4... h6
{ The most popular move in the 1600 rating-database! At the 1600-level  4...h6  ,  4...Bc5  and  4...Nf6  are all about equally popular. The move h6 shows that Black is struggling under the pressure of the Scotch Gambit and plays a prophylactic move to prevent Ng5.   4...h6  is a significant mistake since Black is ignoring their development! The f7-square is never fully safeguarded until Black has managed to castle. The most popular move for White is  5.Nxd4  , which gives White an advantage. This is very logical as now we have a normal Scotch Opening where we played an extra development move with Bc4 while Black wasted time with h6. I suggest to castle instead, gaining a massive lead in development! }
5. O-O
{ Isn't it lovely to watch our opponent's king in the middle of the board knowing that we have just castled! Our idea is that Black isn't ready to develop their knight and bishop on the kingside. }
5... d6 6. Nxd4
{ Why do we recapture the d4-pawn now and not in other variations? We kept our knight on f3 for two reasons:  1@@EndBracket@@ To go for the Ng5 and Nxf7 plan. In this variation, Black prevented that by playing h6.  2@@EndBracket@@ Whenever Black plays Nf6, we attack with e5. We need the knight on f3 to support the e5-pawn!  Black also prevented this idea by playing d6; that's why our knight doesn't belong on f3 anymore. }
6... Nxd4
{ Black's most popular move at the 1600-level. We are happy to develop the queen. }
7. Qxd4 Nf6 { Black prepares to castle. } 8. e5
{ Our signature knight-hunting move. In this position, we can play it even though the d6-pawn can capture it. }
8... dxe5 9. Bxf7+
{ A powerful strike. Black cannot capture the bishop as the king needs to protect the queen. }
9... Ke7 10. Qc4
{ We don't trade the queens since Black's king is in danger. We plan to play Re1 and Nc3, increasing the pressure on Black's king. White has a winning position. }
*

