[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Scotch Gambit: Sidelines"]
[Black "Scotch gambit: 4...h6 with 5...Bc5#1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ The Scotch Gambit has similarities to the Italian opening. Instead of playing the Italian with  3.Bc4  we first play the @@StartBracket@@usually@@EndBracket@@ temporary pawn sacrifice  3.d4  and only after  3...exd4  do we go for  4.Bc4  . }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch Gambit has started, we play  4.Bc4  instead of  4.Nxd4  because we are going for quick development and castling.  Our light-squared bishop on c4 is already looking at the f7-square. White is now ready to castle; however, Black still needs to develop the knight on g8 and the bishop on f8 to prepare to castle. }
4... h6
{ The most popular move in the 1600 rating-database! At the 1600-level  4...h6  ,  4...Bc5  and  4...Nf6  are all about equally popular. The move h6 shows that Black is struggling under the pressure of the Scotch Gambit and plays a prophylactic move to prevent Ng5.   4...h6  is a significant mistake since Black is ignoring their development! The f7-square is never fully safeguarded until Black has managed to castle. The most popular move for White is  5.Nxd4  , which gives White an advantage. This is very logical as now we have a normal Scotch Opening where we played an extra development move with Bc4 while Black wasted time with h6. I suggest to castle instead, gaining a massive lead in development! }
5. O-O
{ Isn't it lovely to watch our opponent's king in the middle of the board, knowing that we have just castled? Our idea is that Black isn't ready to develop their knight and bishop on the kingside. }
5... Bc5
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level, and a very logical one. Black tries to hold on to the d4-pawn to compensate for the lack of development. }
6. c3
{ Preparing to regain the d4-pawn, attack the bishop and get a massive center! }
6... dxc3 7. Bxf7+
{ Black's strategy failed! Black played h6 with the idea to prevent any tactics on the f7-square. }
7... Kxf7 8. Qd5+
{ Forking the king and the bishop! We see this pattern with a sacrifice on f7 followed by a fork on the king and bishop frequently in the Scotch Gambit. }
8... Kf8
{ This is five times less popular than  8...Ke8  at the 1600-level, even though it is objectively the best move for Black. We can capture the bishop with a check. }
9. Qxc5+ d6 10. Qxc3
{ We regained our pawn, restoring the material balance! Black's king is weak and lost the right to castle. Consequently, Black's rook on h8 has difficulty getting active. White has a great position. }
