[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Petrov Defense"]
[Black "Chapter Summary: Petrov Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nf6
{ The Petrov defense has started, this is usually a solid opening for Black. The Petrov has gained more popularity recently since Ian Nepomniatchi used it as the main repertoire in the 2021 World Championship match against Magnus Carlsen. }
3. d4
{ We play in a similar style as in the Scotch Gambit and start the fight in the center directly! I like this move a lot because it puts pressure on Black, and they have to make an important decision right away. }
3... Nxe4
{ 3...exd4  As we already learned from the Scotch Gambit, we don't have to recapture the d4 pawn immediately. Instead, we go for our signature knight-hunting move.  4.e5  Our signature move, hunting Black's knight.  4...Ne4  This is the only good square for the knight, nevertheless, on the 1600-level, this is only the fourth most popular move.   4...Qe7  The move popular move on 1600-level pinning the e-pawn.  5.Be2  We develop, prepare to castle, and also break the pin on the e5-pawn.  5...Ng4   After  5...Ne4  we play  6.O-O  Both Black's queen and knight are misplaced, and White has a significant advantage in development. Also, we will slowly regain the pawn on the  d4  to restore the material balance.  6.O-O  Development is super important. Our e5-pawn is in danger; we want to castle quickly to counter-attack with the rook to e1.  6...Nxe5  7.Nxd4  In exchange for the pawn, White has a big lead in development and more active pieces. We can continue with Nc3 and Re1. The queen on e7 and king on e8 are very poorly placed.   4...Bb4+  5.c3  And both the knight and bishop are under attack we are winning a piece.  5...dxc3  6.bxc3   It is essential to recapture with the pawn and maintain the attack on the bishop. Instead,  6.exf6  would end badly for us since Black plays  6...cxb2+  with a discovered check and subsequently captures our rook and promotes to a queen.   4...Ng4  This is another bad square for the knight.  5.h3  We immediately kick the knight away to an even worse square.  5...Nh6   A knight on the rim is dim. After  5...Nxe5  6.Nxe5  wins the knight. Here it is essential that when Black plays  6...Qe7  pinning the knight, we play  7.Qe2!  Unpinning and protecting the knight, and we remain a piece up.  6.Bg5  Before taking the knight, we force Black's dark-squared bishop to go to e7.  6...Be7  7.Bxh6  gxh6  We are happy that we forced Black's dark-squared bishop to go to e7. The bishop would be better placed on f8 since it could go to g7 to replace the missing pawn.  8.Qxd4   Black's king cannot castle kingside safely and is very far away from castling queenside. In case our queen gets attacked with  8...Nc6  we go  9.Qe3  to attack the h6-pawn.   4...Nd5  The knight is misplaced on d5, let's hunt it again.  5.Qxd4  We capture the pawn and immediately put pressure on the knight.  5...c6  6.Bc4  We develop and put more pressure on the knight. Also, we are ready to castle on the next move.  6...Nb6  7.O-O  At this point, we have gained a massive lead in development, and Black is in trouble. We can also quickly play Nc3 and Bg5 and bring our rooks to the center.  5.Qxd4  This is an excellent move to regain the pawn and immediately attack the knight.  5...d5   5...Nc5  The knight move for the third time already while all the other pieces from Black are still in the starting position.  6.Nc3  Nc6  7.Qd5  This is an active position for the queen.  7...d6  8.Bb5  We are threatening to capture the knight on c6.  8...Bd7  9.Bg5  Developing and attacking the queen. We would love to reach a position where we castle and get the rooks to e1 and d1 where they have powerful open files.  6.exd6  We put more pressure on the knight, forcing it to move for the third time.  6...Nxd6  7.Nc3  Nc6  8.Qf4  On f4, the queen put pressure on the f7 and, in some cases, also on c7. We plan to quickly bring the rooks to the d-file and e-file and control both open files on the board. Therefore we go for a queenside castle which immediately places the rook on the d-file.  8...g6   8...Be7  9.Bd2  Developing and preparing to castle long  9...O-O  10.O-O-O  Be6  11.Bd3  The bishop is keeping an eye on the h7 square nearby Black's king, and our other rook is now ready to go to e1. White has a significant advantage.   8...Bf5  9.Bb5   Pinning the knight! After  9...Nxb5  10.Nxb5  we are threatening both Nxc7 with a fork and Qxf5 winning the bishop.   If Black plays  9...Qe7+  we develop the dark-squared bishop with  10.Be3  and prepare for a long castle. }
4. dxe5
{ Making it impossible for the knight on e4 to go back to the safe f6 square. We can put pressure on Black's knight on e4. }
4... Bc5
{ This is a very principled and exciting move, Black is putting pressure on the f2 pawn; however, this is a risky way to play for Black.   4...d5  5.Nbd2  We attack the knight and try to make it move for the third time.  5...Nxd2   5...Nc5  6.Be2  Developing and getting ready to castle.  6...Be7  7.O-O  White wants to continue with by bringing the rook to the center with Re1. Also, we would like to play Nb3 and subsequently develop the dark-squared bishop.  6.Bxd2  We recapture and are ready to develop the light-squared bishop and castle  6...Be7  7.Bd3  On d3, we keep an eye on the h7 pawn.  7...O-O  8.O-O  c5  9.c3   It is crucial not to play  9.Qe2  since  9...c4  traps our bishop. With 9.c3 we create more space for the light-squared bishop and are ready to continue with Qe2, Rfe1 and Rde1. }
5. Bc4
{ Attack is the best defense, and we put pressure on the f7 pawn. And create a big threat with Qd5. }
5... Nxf2
{ This is the best move for Black, again we go for the counter-attack and also capture on f7.   5...Bxf2+  Even though it looks pretty logical to capture a pawn and give a check, this is a big blunder. After we sidestep with the king both the Black's knight and bishop are very vulnerable, and Black will lose a piece.  6.Kf1  Next move, we want to play Qd5 and go for checkmate and attack the knight on e4.  6...O-O  Black can try to castle and put his king to safety.  7.Qd5  We attack the knight on e4; also, the bishop on f2 is still under hanging. We pin the f7 pawn, which means that Black cannot defend with f5! Next move, we will win a piece. }
6. Bxf7+
{ This is a move we play more often in our repertoire. When the bishop is on c5, we immediately win back the piece. }
6... Kxf7 7. Qd5+ { Forking the king and bishop } 7... Kg6
{ It looks like Black has become crazy; nevertheless, this is the only good move for Black, running with his king towards the middle of the board.   7...Ke8  At the 1600-level, almost everyone played this move which is a significant mistake.  8.Bg5   We are going after the queen. The attractive-looking  8.Qxc5  runs into  8...Nxh1  and  9.Bg5  doesn't win the queen since Black counter-attacks with  9...d6  This will lead to an unclear equal position, whereas  8.Bg5  ensures White a comfortable advantage.  8...Be7  9.Bxe7  Qxe7  10.Kxf2  We are a clean pawn up. With White, we can still make an artificial castle by playing Rf1 and Kg1. }
8. Qxc5 Nxh1
{ We shouldn't worry much about our rook in the corner. Black captures the rook, which was entirely out of play, and now the knight on h1 is in an awful position as well. }
9. Nc3
{ White wants to create an attack against the King, develop the bishop, go for the castle and pick up the knight on h1. }
