1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nf6
{ The Petrov Defense is on the board. This is usually a solid opening for Black. The Petrov has recently gained more popularity since Ian Nepomniatchi used it as the main repertoire in the 2021 World Championship Match against Magnus Carlsen. }
3. d4
{ We play in a similar style as in theScotch Gambit and start the fight in the center directly! I like this move a lot because it is putting pressure on Black and they have to make an important decision right away. }
3... exd4
{ As we already learned from playing the Scotch Gambit, we don't have to recapture the d4-pawn immediately. Instead, we go for our signature knight-hunting move. }
4. e5 { Our signature move, hunting Black's knight. } 4... Qe7
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level, pinning the e-pawn. } 5. Be2
{ We develop, prepare to castle, and also unpin on the e5-pawn. } 5... Ng4
{ After  5...Ne4  we play  6.O-O  .  Both Black's queen and knight are misplaced and White has a big lead in development. Also, we will slowly regain the d4-pawn to restore the material balance. }
6. O-O
{ Development is super important. Our e5-pawn is in danger, so we want to castle quickly to counter-attack with the rook on e1. }
6... Nxe5 7. Nxd4
{ In exchange for the pawn, White has a big lead in development and more active pieces. We can continue with Nc3 and Re1. Black's queen and king are very poorly placed.     Our common plan in other variations with  7.Nxe5  Qxe5  8.Re1  doesn't work since our bishop blocks the e-file and Black can play  8...Be7  further closing the e-file and preparing to castle. }
