[Black "Petrov Defense: 3...Nxe4 with 4...Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nf6
{ The Petrov Defense is on the board. This is usually a solid opening for Black. The Petrov has recently gained more popularity since Ian Nepomniatchi used it as the main repertoire in the 2021 World Championship Match against Magnus Carlsen. }
3. d4
{ We play in a similar style as in theScotch Gambit and start the fight in the center directly! I like this move a lot because it is putting pressure on Black and they have to make an important decision right away. }
3... Nxe4 4. dxe5
{ Making it impossible for the knight to go back to the safe f6-square. We can put pressure on Black's knight. }
4... Bc5
{ This is a very principled and exciting move. Black is putting pressure on the f2-pawn. However, this is a risky way to play for Black. }
5. Bc4
{ Attack is the best defense. We put pressure on the f7-pawn and create a big threat with Qd5. }
5... Bxf2+
{ Even though it seems very logical to capture a pawn and give a check, this is a big blunder. After we sidestep with the king, both the black knight and bishop are very vulnerable, and Black will lose a piece. }
6. Kf1
{ Next, we want to play Qd5 and threaten checkmate while attacking the knight on e4. }
6... O-O { Black can try to castle and put his king to safety. } 7. Qd5
{ We attack the knight, and also the bishop is still under attack. We pin the f7-pawn, which means that Black cannot defend with f5! In the next move, we will win a piece. }
