[White "8. Philidor Defense"]
[Black "Chapter Summary: Philidor Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ This move is not so popular since it blocks Black's dark-squared bishop. } 3.
d4 exd4
{ 3...Nd7  4.Bc4  We develop the bishop, which is looking at the f7-square.  4...h6  Black's most popular move at the 1600-level, however, it is a big mistake.  5.dxe5  dxe5   After  5...Nxe5  6.Nxe5  dxe5  We have the powerful  7.Bxf7+  winning a pawn and destroying Black's king safety.  6.Bxf7+  We strike, and White has a winning position! Usually, a piece sacrifice on f7 is not strong enough once we don't have a follow-up tactic to win back more material. In this position, we have a lovely tactic on the next move.  6...Kxf7  7.Nxe5+   A deadly strike! Black's knight is pinned, so cannot capture. At the 1600-level, the most popular move is  7...Ke8  when  8.Qh5+  already leads to a forced mate. When Black plays  7...Kf6  White wins after  8.Nc3  Kxe5  9.Qd5+  Kf6  10.Qf5+  Ke7  11.Nd5+  Kd6  12.Bf4+  White has a devasting attack hunting Black's king with all forces, and mate should follow soon.   3...Bg4  Pinning the knight.  4.dxe5  Bxf3   After  4...dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Breaks Black's right to castle.  5...Kxd8  6.Nxe5  wins the pawn and attacks Black's light-squared bishop and f7-pawn.  5.Qxf3  dxe5  6.Bc4  Threatening Qxf7 mate.  6...Qf6   6...Nf6  The most popular move at the 1600-level and another mistake.  7.Qb3  White threatens Bxf7+ and Qxb7 and has a winning position.  7.Qb3  Attacking the b7-pawn.  7...b6  8.Nc3  The knight is coming to d5 and White has a winning position.   After  8...Bc5  Black has the threat of Qxf2 mate, and we play the brilliant  9.Be3  preparing to castle long, which is stronger than castling short since the rook immediately dominates the open d-file after  9...Bxe3  10.fxe3  , the threat of Rf1 attacking the queen and adding another attacker to the f7-pawn is deadly. }
4. Nxd4
{ Our typical Scotch Gambit move  4.Bc4  makes less sense now. Black can continue with  4...Nf6  , and our typical attacking idea with  5.e5  isn't possible anymore since Black plays  5...xe5  . }
4... Nf6 { Developing and attacking the pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ Developing and defending the pawn. } 5... Be7
{ Black prepares to castle, we are playing for a long castle. Our rook is immediately well-placed on the semi-open d-file.   5...c5  A positional mistake since Black weakens the d6 pawn and the d5 and b5 squares. This is the second most popular move at the 1600-level.  6.Bb5+   An important intermediate check. We want to free the f5-square for our knight. After  6.Nf5  Black was able to play  6...Bxf5  .  6...Bd7  We are pinning Black's light-squared bishop, which makes the f5-square available for our knight. We don't want to trade on the bishops since this helps Black develop.   6...Nbd7  7.Nf5  White is threatening to capture the d6-pawn and has a great position.  7.Nf5   We are attacking the d-pawn. White has a winning position. After  7...Bxb5  8.Nxb5  Nxe4  9.Qe2  pins the knight and wins a piece after  9...d5  10.f3  .   If Black plays  8...Qa5  forking the king and the knight, we can defend with  9.Nc3  and after  9...Nxe4  10.Qe2  wins the knight. }
6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2
{ We prepare to castle queenside. White has a lead in development, and Black's dark-squared bishop isn't doing much. }
7... c5
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level, which is a significant mistake. } 8.
Ndb5
{ White has many attackers on the d6-pawn and will soon gain the pawn. Also, after castling queenside, our rook is placed perfectly on the d-file. White has a huge advantage. }
