1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ This move is not so popular at the top level since it blocks Black's dark-squared bishop. At the 1600-level, the Petrov has been played more frequently. Against the three main openings  2...Nc6  ,  2...Nf6  , and  2...d6  we always reply with  3.d4  , opening the center.   The Philidor Defense can also occur starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d6  and these variations will be discussed in a later chapter. This chapter will cover the Philidor Defense from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  move order. }
3. d4 Nd7
{ Black develops and protects the e5-pawn. After  3...Nf6  we will play  4.dxe5  Nxe4  5.Qd5  developing and attacking the knight when after  5...Nc5  6.Bg5  Be7  7.exd6  cxd6  8.Nc3  White has a better position. }
4. Bc4 { We develop the bishop, which is looking at the f7-square. } 4... h6
{ Black's most popular move at the 1600-level, however, it is a big mistake. }
5. dxe5 { By trading pawns, we open the d-file for our queen! } 5... dxe5
{ After  5...Nxe5  6.Nxe5  dxe5  ee have the powerful  7.Bxf7+  winning a pawn and destroying Black's king safety. Black cannot capture the bishop with  7...Kxf7  since  8.Qxd8  wins the queen. }
6. Bxf7+
{ We strike, and White has a winning position! Usually, a piece sacrifice on f7 is not strong enough once we don't have a follow-up tactic to win back material. In this position, we have a powerful tactic on the next move. }
6... Kxf7 7. Nxe5+
{ A deadly strike! Black's knight is pinned, so cannot capture. At the 1600-level, the most popular move is  7...Ke8  when  8.Qh5+  already leads to a forced mate.   If Black plays  7...Kf6  White wins after  8.Nc3  Kxe5  9.Qd5+  Kf6  10.Qf5+  Ke7  11.Nd5+  Kd6  12.Bf4+  and White has a devasting attack on Black's king with all forces, and mate should follow soon. }
