1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5
{ The Latvian Gambit   2...d5  The Elephant Gambit, as the opening name already indicates it is not a dubious opening. Still, we should be precise to punish Black for playing this move.  3.exd5  Forcing Black to bring out the queen.  3...e4  Black tries to go knight-hunting. It's funny that Black is trying to fight us with our repertoire weapon. The knight-hunting idea doesn't work in this case, and we can win the e4-pawn.   3...Qxd5  4.Nc3   Developing with tempo and White has a lead in development. After  4...Qc5  , we can play  5.d4  and open all the diagonals.   If Black plays  4...Qe6  , then we go  5.Bb5+  c6  6.Ba4  White has a big lead in development, and after Black's knight hunting idea with  6...e4  we play  7.O-O  when after  7...xf3  8.Re1  is pinning and winning the queen.  4.Qe2  Pinning the e4-pawn.  4...Nf6   4...Qxd5  5.Nc3  Developing with tempo and winning the e4-pawn.  5.d3  Attacking the pinned e4-pawn again and opening the diagonal for the bishop.  5...Qxd5  6.Nc3  Developing and attacking the queen and the e4-pawn.  6...Bb4  Developing and pinning the knight.  7.Nd2  A brilliant move, unpinning the knight to reinforce the threat to capture the queen and adding another attacker to the e4-pawn. White is winning the e4-pawn and has a big advantage. }
3. Nxe5 { We are threatening Qxh5+. } 3... Nf6
{ 3...Qf6  4.d4   Putting the pawn in the center and supporting the knight.  4.Qh5+  didn't work since Black would play  4...g6  . }
4. Bc4
{ Developing, preparing to castle, and threatening Nf7 with a fork on the queen and the rook. }
4... Qe7 5. d4
{ After  5...d6  6.Nf7  Attacking the rook  6...Qxe4+  Giving check and attack the g2-pawn  7.Kf1!  defending the g2-pawn  7...Rg8  8.Ng5!  Discovered attack on the queen and the rook. White has a winning position, and the computer gives  +6. }
