[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Petrov, Philidor, Elephant & Latvian gambit Tactics"]
[Black "Exercise 1: Petrov Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/2b1P3/2B5/5N2/PPP2nPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find the strongest move for White. } 1. Bxf7+
{ We weaken Black's king and try to set up a double attack.  1.Qd5  wouldn't work even though this move would be threatening mate and the bishop on c5, as  1...Qe7  defends against both threats. }
1... Kxf7 2. Qd5+ { Forking the king and the bishop! } 2... Ke8
{ At the 1600-level, almost everyone played this move which is a significant mistake. The best move for Black is the crazy-looking  2...Kg6  when we play  3.Qxc5  Nxh1  4.Nc3  . White wants to create an attack against the king, develop the bishop, castle and pick up the knight on h1. }
3. Bg5
{ We are attacking the queen! Black has only one good defensive move.   3.Qxc5  looks strong at first sight because after  3...Nxh1  , we can play  4.Bg5  trapping the queen, but now Black has the counterattack  4...d6  . This move attacks our queen and creates an escape square on d7 for the queen. After  5.Qe3  Qd7  Black is doing fine. The discovered attack with  4.exd6+  is not dangerous since Black defends with  6...Qe6  trading the queens. }
3... Be7 { Should we capture the knight or the bishop? } 4. Bxe7
{ After trading the bishops, we will win the knight!  4.Kxf2  wouldn't work since after  4...Bxg5  Black is still a piece up. }
4... Qxe7 5. Kxf2
{ White is significantly better because of the lead in development. We can go for an artificial castle with Rf1 and Kg1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Petrov, Philidor, Elephant & Latvian gambit Tactics"]
[Black "Exercise 2: Petrov Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/8/3pP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find the best continuation for White. } 1. e5
{ Our signature move, hunting Black's knight. } 1... Ng4 2. h3
{ A knight on the rim is dim! So let's make the knight move to this poor square. }
2... Nh6 3. Bg5
{ Before taking the knight, we force Black's dark-squared bishop to go to e7. }
3... Be7 4. Bxh6
{ Weakening Black's pawn structure, and also Black's king safety as Black planned to castle kingside. }
4... gxh6
{ We are happy that we forced Black's dark-squared bishop to go to e7. The bishop would be stronger on f8 since then it could go to g7 to replace the missing pawn. }
5. Qxd4
{ Developing the queen. Keeping firm control in the center and preparing to castle long. After  5...Nc6  we play  6.Qe3  attacking the h6-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Petrov, Philidor, Elephant & Latvian gambit Tactics"]
[Black "Exercise 3: Petrov Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/8/3pP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. e5 { Our signature move, hunting Black's knight. } 1... Bb4+
{ How should we cope with the check? } 2. c3
{ We are attacking both the bishop and the knight. } 2... dxc3
{ Please don't fall for the trap by playing  3.exf6  . Because then after  3...cxb2+  4.Bd2  bxa1Q we have lost the rook and Black has promoted to a queen. }
3. bxc3 { White wins a piece. We are attacking the bishop and the knight. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Petrov, Philidor, Elephant & Latvian gambit Tactics"]
[Black "Exercise 4: Petrov Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/2b1P3/4n3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Counterattack is the best defense! With that in mind, what is the best continuation? }
1. Bc4 { We are attacking the f7-pawn. } 1... Nxf2 2. Bxf7+
{ Going for the counter-attack. } 2... Kf8 3. Qd5
{ Saving our queen, attacking the dark-squared bishop, and preparing a mate threat! }
3... Nxh1 4. Bh5 { Threatening Qf7 mate! } 4... Qe7
{ Defending against the mate and protecting the bishop. } 5. Bg5
{ Attacking the queen. The queen doesn't have a safe square from where it can keep protecting the bishop. }
5... Bf2+ { Where should we go with the king? } 6. Ke2
{ We want to open the first rank for our rook to pick up the knight. Also, we want to keep on attacking the bishop. }
6... Qe6 7. Nc3
{ Double attack. This move is beautiful! We are playing chess like a true master, using all our pieces on the board. Our rook attacks the knight, which is doomed. Also, we defended the queen. Soon we will collect the material, and White has a significant advantage. }
*

