[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Alapin Sicilian: 1600-Level Main Line  2...Nc6 "]
[Black "Chapter Summary: Alapin 2...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian opening 1.e4 c5 is the second most popular choice at the 1600-level }
2. c3
{ The Alapin variation starts, we prepare to play d4 next and make it possible to recapture with the pawn to create a strong center. It's our goal to get our pawns on e4 and d4! }
2... Nc6
{ This is by far the most popular move on 1600-level, whereas  2.Nf6  and  2.d5  are the most popular on top and high amateur level. It turns out that the most frequently played moves on the 1600-level completely differ from high-amateur/ top-level chess. Less than 20% of the games at the 1600-level Black played  2.d5  or  2.Nf6  .  The start of the Alapin chapter teaches you how to destroy your opponents when they make these frequent 1600-level mistakes. }
3. d4
{ We continue our Alapin idea and get a strong center with pawns on e4 and d4. Also, we prepare to play d5 and immediately punish our opponent for placing the knight on c6. }
3... cxd4 4. cxd4
{ We managed to get both our pawns in the center. This makes it easy to develop and castle since we opened the diagonals for the bishops and the queen. Furthermore, our pawns in the center prevent our opponent from developing, castling, and getting their pawn in the center! Rule of thumb: Next move, we play d5 kicking the knight, regardless of what Black plays. }
4... e6
{ The most popular at the 1600-level, let's punish them immediately.   4...d6  A weak move, which nevertheless has been played very frequently at 1600-level! We punish our opponent in a similar style as in the Scotch Gambit. Black's knights are best on c6 and f6, and in our repertoire, we mercilessly kick these knights away from their comfortable squares.  5.d5   Immediately attacking the knight!  5...Nb4  6.Qa4+  wins the knight with a fork, and  5...Na5  6.b4  traps the knight.  5...Ne5  6.f4  Strengthening our center and attacking the knight again.  6...Ng6  7.Nf3  White is ready to develop the light-squared bishop and castle. Black's dark-squared bishop is stuck, and castling will be an almost impossible task. White has a huge advantage.   4...d5  Black strikes back in the center and prevents us from playing d5.  5.exd5   We capture the pawn, forcing Black to bring the queen out! This transposes after  3.exd5  Qxd5  to the Barmen's Defense. }
5. d5 { We kick away the knight from its comfortable square on c6. } 5... exd5
6. exd5 Ne5
{ 6...Bb4+  7.Nc3  Ne5   7...Qe7+  8.Be2   Blocking the check with the bishop and developing. After  8...Ne5  we will play  9.Nf3  Nxf3+  10.gxf3  The doubled pawns shouldn't bother us since we can activate our rook on the g-file and play for a long castle. White has a big advantage.  8.Nf3   The game can continue with  8...Qe7  9.Nxe5  Qxe5+  10.Be2  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Qxc3  12.Bd2  Qd4  13.Bf3  White is much better even though we are down a pawn. Our pieces can develop easily while Black's rook on a8 and bishop on c8 are stuck.  8...Nxf3+  9.Qxf3  This trade is good for White since we develop the queen. Here we have a lead in development and a better position. We plan to develop the light-squared bishop and castle.   6...Nb4  A bad square for the knight, White has a winning advantage already  7.Nf3  We would like to play a3 and force the knight to the weak a6-square. Subsequently, we would like to develop our light-squared bishop and castle. The computer already evaluates this position as +3.5   6...Nce7  This move is played very often on the 1600-level and immediately loses the game.  7.d6  Attacking the knight  7...Nc6  8.Qe2+   Check! Black has to place a piece on e7 to cover the check, and we take it and are a piece up.  8...Nge7  9.dxe7  . }
7. Nf3
{ We develop and keep on attacking Black's knight. A trade benefits us since we can develop the queen when we recapture it. }
7... Nxf3+ 8. Qxf3
{ White is ready to develop the light-squared bishop and castle and has a nice lead in development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Alapin Sicilian: 1600-Level Main Line  2...Nc6 "]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian: 2...Nc6 with 4...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian opening 1.e4 c5 is the second most popular choice at the 1600-level. }
2. c3
{ The Alapin variation starts. We prepare to play d4 next and make it possible to recapture with the pawn to create a strong center. It's our goal to get our pawns on e4 and d4! }
2... Nc6
{ At the 1600-level, the three most popular moves are 2...Nc6,  2...d6  , and  2...e6  , whereas  2...Nf6  and  2...d5  are the most popular at the top and high amateur levels. The most frequently played moves at the 1600-level completely differ from high-amateur/ top-level chess. These differences show that Black has difficulties facing the Alapin at the 1600-level. }
3. d4
{ We continue our Alapin idea and get a strong center with pawns on e4 and d4. Also, we prepare to play d5 and immediately punish our opponent for placing the knight on c6. }
3... cxd4 4. cxd4
{ We managed to get both our pawns in the center. This makes it easy to develop and castle since we opened the diagonals for both the bishops and the queen.   Furthermore, our pawns in the center prevent our opponent from developing, castling, and getting their own pawns in the center! Rule of thumb: In the next move, we play d5 kicking the knight, regardless of what Black plays. }
4... g6 5. d5 { Our signature move, hunting the knight! } 5... Ne5
{ If  5...Na5  we shouldn't play  6.b4  trapping the knight since after  6...Bg7  suddenly our rook is trapped, too. So after  5...Na5  we first play  6.Qd4  attacking the rook and White will soon win a piece by playing b4. }
6. f4 { Trapping the knight! } *

