{ The Alapin variation starts. We prepare to play d4 next and make it possible to recapture with the pawn to create a strong center. It's our goal to get our pawns on e4 and d4! }
2... Nc6
{ At the 1600-level, the three most popular moves are 2...Nc6,  2...d6  , and  2...e6  , whereas  2...Nf6  and  2...d5  are the most popular at the top and high amateur levels. The most frequently played moves at the 1600-level completely differ from high-amateur/ top-level chess. These differences show that Black has difficulties facing the Alapin at the 1600-level. }
3. d4
{ We continue our Alapin idea and get a strong center with pawns on e4 and d4. Also, we prepare to play d5 and immediately punish our opponent for placing the knight on c6. }
3... cxd4 4. cxd4
{ We managed to get both our pawns in the center. This makes it easy to develop and castle since we opened the diagonals for both the bishops and the queen.   Furthermore, our pawns in the center prevent our opponent from developing, castling, and getting their own pawns in the center! Rule of thumb: In the next move, we play d5 kicking the knight, regardless of what Black plays. }
4... d6
{ A very weak move, which nevertheless has been played very frequently at the 1600-level! We punish our opponent in a similar style as in the Scotch Gambit. Black's knights are best placed on c6 and f6, and in our repertoire, we mercilessly kick these knights away from their favorite squares. }
5. d5 { Immediately attacking the knight! } 5... Ne5
{ 5...Nb4  6.Qa4+  wins the knight with a fork and  5...Na5  6.b4  traps the knight. }
6. f4
{ Strengthening our center and attacking the knight again. Check out this model game where Black never managed to catch up in development. }
6... Ng6 7. Nf3
{ White is ready to develop the light-squared bishop and castle. Black's dark-squared bishop is stuck and castling will be an almost impossible task. White has a huge advantage. }
