[White "12. Alapin Sicilian: 1600-Level - Other Main Moves"]
[Black "Chapter Summary: Alapin Other Main Moves at 1600-level"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin variation starts, we prepare to play d4 next and make it possible to recapture with the pawn to create a strong center. It's our goal to get our pawns on e4 and d4! }
2... d6
{ Black's second most popular move at the 1600-level, which allows us to get a strong center.   2...e5  This move is positionally speaking dubious as Black has difficulties controlling the d5-square with a pawn.  3.Nf3  Nc6   3...d6  4.d4   Getting control in the center and also opening up the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop! After Black plays  3...d6  the bishop on f8 is permanently blocked! That's why it is the perfect moment to play  4.d4  .  We don't play this in the  3...Nc6  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  exd4  5.Nxd4  variation because now  5...Bb4+  is possible, and since we traded the c5-pawn, Black's dark-squared bishop is no longer weak.  4...cxd4  5.cxd4  exd4  6.Nxd4  White has an advantage because of the lead in development. Also, the pawn on d6 is weak and blocking Black's dark-squared bishop.  4.Bc4  Developing and preparing to castle. Also, our bishop is looking at the f7 square already. This is a prophylactic move! The idea is that when Black develops with Nf6, we can play Ng5 increasing the pressure on f7.  4...Nf6  5.Ng5  Attacking the f7-pawn and threatening a fork on the queen and rook.  5...d5  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.Qh5  We are going for checkmate Qxf7 is the threat.  7...g6  8.Qf3  We create a double attack on f7 threatening mate, and we attack the knight on d5 twice.  8...Qxg5  9.Bxd5  Again, we threaten to capture on f7 and also on c6.  9...Nd8  A cunning move by Black defending against both threats.  10.O-O  Black found all the defensive moves. White still has a very nice position.   2...g6  We know our plan!  3.d4  cxd4   3...Bg7  4.dxc5  When we can capture a free pawn, we should do that.  4...Qc7  5.Be3  Developing and defending the pawn  5...Nf6  6.Bd3  Developing and defending the pawn.  4.cxd4  Bg7   After  4...d5  , we play  5.e5  , and closing the center gives White an excellent position. Black has trouble developing their knight on the kingside since we have taken away the f6-square.  5.Nc3  Developing and making Black's ...d5 break impossible.  5...d6  6.Nf3   After  6...Nf6  we get a transposition to the variation  2...d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.cxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  6.Nf3  Bg7  and we will cover later in this chapter!   2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  This capture is the most popular move at the 1600-level, even though it is a mistake   3...d5  Black tries to fight back in the center  4.e5  Now we tricked Black into the advanced French opening.  4.cxd4  d5  5.e5  The chapter on the French defense covers these variations! White already has an improved version of the French.   2...a6  Whenever Black plays a useless move, we continue with d4 and create a strong center.  3.d4 }
3. d4 cxd4
{ At the 1600-level this move is the overwhelming favorite. After the trade we can develop our knight to the most natural c3 square.   3...Nf6  Developing and attacking the e4-pawn  4.Bd3  Developing defending the e4-pawn and preparing to castle  4...g6  5.Nf3  Developing and preparing to castle  5...Bg7  6.O-O  White has a strong center, which gives White an advantage. We are ready to play Re1 and bring the rook to the center. }
4. cxd4
{ We are thrilled with White as we have a strong center with our pawns on e4 and d4. }
4... Nf6 { Black develops and attacks the pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ The knight-hunting idea with  5.e5  wouldn't have worked since after  5...dxe5  6.dxe5  Qxd1+  Trading queens and breaking our right to castle  7.Kxd1  Ng4!  Attacks both the e5 and f2-pawns. Still, we keep in mind that later in the variation, we will hunt the knight on f6 with e5! }
5... g6 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. Bb5+
{ Developing with a check. Black has to block with a piece on d7, which means that subsequently, our knight-hunting idea becomes possible! }
7... Bd7
{ It seems like Black is just playing their normal development moves, but now we strike with our signature knight-hunting move.   7...Nc6  8.d5  Attacking the pinned knight and we win material.  8...a6  Black counterattacks on the bishop.  9.Ba4   We keep the pin on the knight, preparing to capture the next move.  9.Bxc6  bxc6  10.dxc6  would also have been strong, but this is even better  9...b5  10.dxc6  bxa4  11.Qxa4  White has a winning position! Next, we want to castle, develop the dark-squared bishop, and bring the rooks to the center.   7...Nbd7  8.e5  We attack the knight on f6 and Black is in big trouble. }
8. e5
{ In our entire repertoire, we are merciless for knights placed on f6 and c6. }
8... Bxb5
{ A big blunder, we are winning a piece! Yet this is the most popular move at the 1600-level.   8...dxe5  9.dxe5  Reinforcing the threat on the knight  9...Ng4  10.Bf4  Developing and defending the e5-pawn  10...O-O   10...Bxb5  11.Qxd8+  Kxd8  12.Nxb5  White has a much better position, and the Black's king in the center is weak. Next move, we can play Rd1+ developing with tempo!  11.h3  Kicking the knight back, and the knight has no good squares. White has a big advantage. }
9. exf6 { Attacking both bishops! } 9... Bxf6 10. Nxb5
{ White has a winning position after just ten moves.  10...Qa5  wouldn't win back the knight for Black since we can play  11.Nc3  . }
