3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bc4
{ Developing and preparing to castle. Also, our bishop is looking at the f7-square already. The idea is that when Black develops with Nf6, we can play Ng5 increasing the pressure on f7. Check this model game where I won from this position during my Banter Blitz show. }
4... Nf6 5. Ng5
{ Attacking the f7-pawn and threatening a fork on the queen and rook. } 5... d5
6. exd5 Nxd5 7. Qh5 { We are going for checkmate. Qxf7 is the threat. } 7... g6
8. Qf3
{ We create a double attack on f7, threatening mate, and attack the knight twice. }
8... Qxg5 9. Bxd5
{ Again, we threaten to capture on f7 and also to capture the knight. } 9...
Nd8 { A cunning move by Black, defending against both threats. } 10. O-O
{ Black found all the defensive moves. White still has a very nice position. }
*

