1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin variation starts. We prepare to play d4 next and make it possible to recapture with the pawn to create a strong center. It's our goal to get our pawns on e4 and d4! }
2... d6
{ Black's second most popular move at the 1600-level, which allows us to get a strong center. }
3. d4 cxd4
{ At the 1600-level this move is the overwhelming favorite. After the trade we can develop our knight to the most natural c3-square. }
4. cxd4
{ We are thrilled with White, as we have a strong center with our pawns on e4 and d4. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ Here, the knight-hunting idea with  5.e5  wouldn't have worked since after  5...dxe5  6.dxe5  Qxd1+  trading queens and breaking our right to castle  7.Kxd1  Ng4!  attacks both the e5- and f2-pawns. Still, we keep in mind that later in the variation we will hunt the knight on f6 with e5! }
5... e6 6. Nf3
{ Since our pawns are on e4 and d4, we can develop both our bishops. Instead, Black's position with the pawns on e6 and d6 makes sure that both bishops are blocked. That's why White has a significant advantage. }
