[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Alapin Sicilian: Barmen Defense 2...d5"]
[Black "Chapter Summary: Alapin Barmen's Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5
{ This is one of the main variations for Black on the top-level called the Barmen's Defence. Black aims to strike back in the center immediately. At the 1600-level, the Barmen's Defense is way less popular and played in less than 10% of the Alapin games. }
3. exd5
{ We want to capture in the center, forcing Black to bring the queen out. }
3... Qxd5 4. d4
{ This position perfectly illustrates why the Alapin is my recommendation. The bishops and the queen are free to develop quickly. We have set up an excellent base for our future development by throwing the center pawns forward. We will ensure that if Black makes one mistake, all our pieces are crushing through the opponent's position with lightning-fast development. }
4... cxd4
{ On top-level, this is a sideline however, at the 1600-level, 4...cxd4 is by far the most played move. Trading the pawns is dangerous for Black since our knight can come to c3 attacking the queen.   4...Nf6  Black wants to develop and prepare to go for a short castle.  5.Nf3  Developing and preparing to castle.  5...Bg4  Black is pinning our knight and threatening to capture and give us doubled pawns.  6.Be2  Prepares to castle and defends the knight.  6...e6  7.h3   Provoking the bishop to make a favorable trade for us. Black shouldn't accept the trade and play  7...Bh5  , the game could continue with  8.O-O  Nc6  9.Be3  White threatens to capture on c5 and after  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  White is ready to develop the knight to c3 with tempo.   4...Nc6  Black immediately attacks the d4-pawn.  5.Nf3  We develop and defend the d4-pawn.  5...Bg4  Black is pinning the knight.  6.Be2  We unpin the knight and prepare to castle.  6...cxd4  The most popular move at the 1600-level. We are happy to trade and free the c3-square for our knight.  7.cxd4  We plan to play Nc3 developing with tempo, and subsequently, we are ready to start the knight-hunt with d5!   @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3q4/3P2b1/5N2/PP2BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bxf3  8.Bxf3  Qxd4  wouldn't win a pawn for Black since we play  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  10.Qxd4  winning the queen and the game! }
5. cxd4 { White is thrilled that the c3-square is free! } 5... Nc6 6. Nf3
{ Developing and defending our d4-pawn. } 6... Bg4
{ Black develops and pins the knight!   6...Nf6  7.Nc3  Developing with tempo and attacking the queen! Also, we are preparing to continue with our other signature knight-hunting move.  7...Qd8  8.d5  This move should no longer be a surprise.  8...Nb8  9.Bb5+  We continue with quick development.  9...Bd7  10.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  11.O-O  It's nice to see that Black's king is still in the middle.  11...g6  12.d6   After  12...exd6  13.Re1+  Be7  14.Bh6  Black will never castle. If Black decides to keep the pawn alive on ...d6, then Nb5-Nc7 will come soon with a devastating attack! The strongest computers evaluate this as  +5. }
7. Nc3
{ Ones again going for development with tempo! We plan to continue with our signature knight-hunting move regardless of where the queen moves. }
7... Bxf3
{ White wins after every other move. When Black queens moves, we continue with d5 hunting the knight, and subsequently, Black's king is weak, and we can continue the attack with Bb5+   7...Qd8  A popular move on the 1600-level but a bad one.  8.d5  Kicking the knight as always.  8...Ne5  This is the most played move on the 1600-level. We win immediately with a brilliant trick, the big queen sacrifice trick. As a kid, I won many games with this trick. We go for this trick in the Alapin, Scandinavian, and Caro-Kann.  9.Nxe5  We don't care about our queen.  9...Bxd1  10.Bb5+  Auwchhhh, this check is very painful for Black.  10...Qd7  11.Bxd7+   After  11...Kd8  12.Nxf7  Kxd7  13.Kxd1!  We are a piece up and will also gain the rook on h8 next move. The computer gives  +11. }
8. Nxd5 { We capture the queen and will also gain the rook soon! } 8... Bxd1 9.
Nc7+ { Forking the king and the rook. } 9... Kd7 10. Nxa8
{ We are an exchange up. Black has only one good move here. } 10... Bh5
{ Black's only good move.   10...Bg4  11.f3  Attacking the bishop and creating a safe square for our king on f2.  11...Bf5  12.d5  Hunting the knight! We will place the king on f2 and attack with Bb5, Bf4, and g4. White has a winning position. }
11. d5
{ We continue with our signature knight-hunting move. Again Black has only one move not to be lost. }
11... Nd4 { 11...Nb4  12.Bf4  Nc2+  13.Kd2  transposes to the same position. }
12. Bf4 { We kindly invite Black to win our rook in the corner. } 12... Nc2+
{ Black accepts the challenge and forks the king and rook. } 13. Kd2 Nxa1 14.
Bb5+
{ We are a rook down; however, White will play for a mate, and has a winning position. }
14... Kd8 15. Bc7+
{ After  15...Kc8  16.Rc1  White plans to play Be5+ and after ...Kd8 go Rc7-Rxb7-Rb8 mate! Black pieces are too underdeveloped to defend well against this plan, and White has a winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
