[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5
{ This is one of the main variations for Black on the top-level called the Barmen's Defence. Black aims to strike back in the center immediately. At the 1600-level, the Barmen's Defense is way less popular and played in less than 10% of the Alapin games. }
3. exd5
{ We want to capture in the center, forcing Black to bring the queen out. }
3... Qxd5 4. d4
{ This position is a perfect illustration of why the Alapin is my recommendation. The bishops and the queen are free to develop quickly. We have set up an excellent base for our future development by throwing the center pawns forward. We will ensure that if Black makes one mistake, all our pieces are crushing through the opponent's position with lightning-fast development. }
4... Nc6 { Black immediately attacks the d4-pawn. } 5. Nf3
{ We develop and defend the d4-pawn. } 5... Bg4
{ Black is pinning the knight. } 6. Be2
{ We unpin the knight and prepare to castle. } 6... cxd4
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level. We are happy to trade and free the c3-square for our knight. }
7. cxd4
{ We plan to play Nc3 developing with tempo, and subsequently, we are ready to start the knight-hunt with d5!  7...Bxf3  8.Bxf3  Qxd4  wouldn't win a pawn for Black since we play  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  10.Qxd4  winning the queen and the game. }
