[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5
{ This is one of the main variations for Black on the top-level called the Barmen's Defence. Black aims to strike back in the center immediately. At the 1600-level, the Barmen's Defense is way less popular and played in less than 10% of the Alapin games. }
3. exd5
{ We want to capture in the center, forcing Black to bring the queen out. }
3... Qxd5 4. d4
{ This position is a perfect illustration of why the Alapin is my recommendation. The bishops and the queen are free to develop quickly. We have set up an excellent base for our future development by throwing the center pawns forward. We will ensure that if Black makes one mistake, all our pieces are crushing through the opponent's position with lightning-fast development. }
4... cxd4
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level. This move is extremely dangerous for Black since our knight can develop with tempo after the trade of pawns, attacking the queen. }
5. cxd4 { White is thrilled that the c3-square is free! } 5... Nc6 6. Nf3
{ Developing and defending our d4-pawn. } 6... Nf6 7. Nc3
{ Developing with tempo and attacking the queen. Also, we are preparing to continue with our other signature knight-hunting move. }
7... Qd8 8. d5 { This move should not come as a surprise anymore. } 8... Nb8 9.
Bb5+ { We continue with quick development. } 9... Bd7
{ Check out the model game, where White won this position with a beautiful smothered mate. }
10. Bxd7+ { We trade bishops to subsequently castle. } 10... Nbxd7 11. O-O
{ It's nice to see that Black's king is still in the middle. After  11...Nb6  we can go  12.Ne5  here  12...Nfxd5  is too dangerous for Black when we attack with  13.Qb3  followed by Qb5+.   When Black plays  11...Nb6  12.Ne5  g6  we go for the same plan with  13.Re1  Bg7  14.d6  and we have a crushing attack. }
11... g6 12. d6
{ After  12...exd6  13.Re1+  Be7  14.Bh6  Black will never castle. If Black decides to keep the d6-pawn alive, then Nb5-Nc7 will come soon with a devastating attack. The strongest computers evaluate this as  +5. }
