1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5
{ This is one of the main variations for Black on the top-level called the Barmen's Defence. Black aims to strike back in the center immediately. At the 1600-level, the Barmen's Defense is way less popular and played in less than 10% of the Alapin games. }
3. exd5
{ We want to capture in the center, forcing Black to bring the queen out. }
3... Qxd5 4. d4
{ This position is a perfect illustration of why the Alapin is my recommendation. The bishops and the queen are free to develop quickly. We have set up an excellent base for our future development by throwing the center pawns forward. We will ensure that if Black makes one mistake, all our pieces are crushing through the opponent's position with lightning-fast development. }
4... cxd4
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level. This move is extremely dangerous for Black since our knight can develop with tempo after the trade of pawns, attacking the queen. }
5. cxd4 { White is thrilled that the c3-square is free! } 5... Nc6 6. Nf3
{ Developing and defending our d4-pawn. } 6... Bg4
{ Black develops and pins the knight. } 7. Nc3
{ Once again going for development with tempo. Regardless of where the queen moves, we plan to continue with our signature knight-hunting move. }
7... Bxf3
{ White wins after every other move. When Black's queen moves, we continue with d5 hunting the knight, and subsequently, Black's king is weak, and we can continue the attack with Bb5+. }
8. Nxd5 { We capture the queen and will also gain the rook soon! } 8... Bxd1 9.
Nc7+ { Forking the king and the rook. } 9... Kd7 10. Nxa8
{ We are an exchange up. Black has only one good move here. } 10... Bh5
{ Black's only good move. } 11. d5
{ We continue with our signature knight-hunting move. Again Black has only one move not to be lost. }
11... Nd4 { 11...Nb4  12.Bf4  Nc2+  13.Kd2  transposes. } 12. Bf4
{ We kindly invite Black to win our rook in the corner. } 12... Nc2+
{ Black is greedy and goes for the rook. This has been played in all of the games at the 1600-level in my database. Instead Black's best move  12...e5  when after  13.dxe6+  fxe6  14.f3  White plans to continue with  Rd1  pinning the knight. }
13. Kd2 Nxa1 14. Bb5+
{ We are a rook down; however, White will play for a mate, and has a winning position. }
14... Kd8 15. Bc7+
{ After  15...Kc8  16.Rc1  White  plans to play Be5+ and after Kd8 go Rc7-Rxb7-Rb8 mate! Black's pieces are too underdeveloped to defend well against this plan, and White has a winning position. }
