[White "14. Alapin Sicilian: 2...Nf6"]
[Black "Chapter Summary: Alapin 2...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6
{ Black attacks in the center, which temporarily stops us from playing d4. } 3.
e5 { We counterattack the knight, forcing it to move again! } 3... Nd5 4. d4
{ We set up a perfect basis to be able to develop all the pieces. Our bishops and queen are free to develop. }
4... cxd4 5. Nf3
{ We don't recapture the pawn yet, and kindly invite Black to capture on c3. Like in the Scotch Gambit, we plan to play for Bc4 next, developing and putting pressure on the knight. }
5... Nc6
{ 5...dxc3  A big blunder, which Black played in more than 10% of the games at the 1600-level.  6.Qxd5  We win the knight and have a winning position.   5...d6  6.Bc4  We attack the knight again!  6...dxe5  7.Nxe5  We threaten Qf3 to go for Qxf7 mate and attack the knight.  7...e6  8.O-O   We continue our lightning-fast development. Black has to be careful here and would already be losing after  8...dxc3  9.Nxc3  Nxc3  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8  11.Nxf7  Ke8  12.Nxh8  winning the rook.   5...e6  6.Bc4  We go for quick development and attack the knight!  6...dxc3  7.Bxd5  We capture the knight and break Black's pawn structure!  7...cxb2  Black plays greedily and first captures the pawn.   7...exd5  8.Nxc3  We plan to play Bg5, Nxd5, and O-O. White has a lead in development and a better position.  8.Bxb2  exd5  9.O-O  White has a big lead in development, and Black has to be very careful here. After   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/8/3pP3/8/5N2/PB3PPP/RN1Q1RK1 b kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Be7  10.Nc3  White already has a winning position. We plan to play Nc3-Nd5, regaining the pawn and placing our knight on a powerful central square. }
6. Bc4 { We develop and attack! } 6... Nb6
{ Black counter-attacks the bishop. } 7. Bb3
{ We sidestep the attack and keep an eye on the f7-pawn. } 7... dxc3
{ This greedy capture is Black's most popular move at the 1600-level and a big mistake.   7...d5  8.exd6  We capture en-passant and open our bishop's diagonal towards f7 again.  8...Qxd6  9.O-O   We continue the fast development. Black cannot pin the knight with  9...Bg4  because we play  10.Bxf7+  Kxf7  11.Ng5  Ke8  12.Qxg4  regaining the bishop with a winning position.   After  9...dxc3  , we attack with  10.Ng5  e6  11.Qh5  White threatens Qxf7 and has nice attacking chances.   Black's best move is  9...Be6  when  10.Na3  dxc3  11.Qe2  gives White great compensation for the two sacrificed pawns. We are threatening Nb5 attacking the queen and keeping an eye on the c7-square to fork the king and rook in the future. }
8. Nxc3 e6 9. Bf4
{ A prophylactic development move that prevents Black from playing  9...d5  because we capture with  10.exd6  White has a fantastic position. We plan to castle when Black castled we attack with Qd3-Bc2 threatening mate on h7. }
