[White "14. Alapin Sicilian: 2...Nf6"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian 2...Nf6 with 5...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6
{ Black attacks in the center, which temporarily stops us from playing d4. } 3.
e5 { We counterattack the knight, forcing it to move again! } 3... Nd5 4. d4
{ We set up a perfect basis to be able to develop all the pieces. Our bishops and queen are free to develop. }
4... cxd4 5. Nf3
{ We don't recapture the pawn yet and kindly invite Black to capture on c3. Like in the Scotch Gambit, we plan to play for Bc4 next, developing and putting pressure on the knight. }
5... d6 6. Bc4 { We attack the knight again! } 6... dxe5
{ After  6...e6  I recommend playing  7.O-O  delaying the capture on  d4  . After  7...dxe5  8.Nxe5  dxc3?  9.Nxc3  White pieces are developing at lightning-fast speed and the position is significantly better for us.   Instead Black should play  8...Be7  when we can attack with  9.Qg4  targeting the g7-pawn. }
7. Nxe5 { We threaten Qf3 to go for Qxf7 mate and attack the knight. } 7... e6
8. O-O
{ We continue our lightning-fast development. Black has to be careful here and would already be losing after  8...dxc3  9.Nxc3  Nxc3  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8  11.Nxf7  Ke8  12.Nxh8  winning the rook. }
