[White "14. Alapin Sicilian: 2...Nf6"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian 2...Nf6 with 5...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6
{ Black attacks in the center, which temporarily stops us from playing d4. } 3.
e5 { We counterattack the knight, forcing it to move again! } 3... Nd5 4. d4
{ We set up a perfect basis to be able to develop all the pieces. Our bishops and queen are free to develop. }
4... cxd4 5. Nf3
{ We don't recapture the pawn yet and kindly invite Black to capture on c3. Like in the Scotch Gambit, we plan to play for Bc4 next, developing and putting pressure on the knight. }
5... e6 6. Bc4
{ We go for quick development and attack the knight! After  6...Nb6  7.Bb3  dxc3  8.Nxc3  Black has to be careful and play  8...d5  when after  9.exd6  Bxd6  10.O-O  White keeps a nice initiative. }
6... dxc3 { After  6...d6  we will transpose to the previous variation. } 7.
Bxd5 { We capture the knight and break Black's pawn structure! } 7... cxb2
{ Black plays greedily and first captures the pawn. After  7...exd5  8.Nxc3  White plans to play  Bg5  ,  Nxd5  , and castle. }
8. Bxb2
{ In classical games  8...Qa5+  has been played by many strong players. This move is a mistake since after  9.Nc3  exd5  10.O-O  White has a massive lead in development, and Nxd5 is coming soon. }
8... exd5 9. O-O
{ White has a big lead in development, and Black has to be very careful here. After  9...Be7  Nc3  White already has a winning position. We plan to play Nc3-Nd5 regaining a pawn and placing our knight on a powerful central square. }
*

