[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. French Defense"]
[Black "Chapter Summary: French Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French 1.e4 e6 is the third most popular move at the 1600-level. } 2. d4
{ Just like in the Alapin we love to get our pawns on e4 and d4. } 2... d5
{ The idea of the French opening is to strike back in the center. } 3. e5
{ We go for the advanced variation in the French. When we play e5, Black's light-squared bishop is locked in by Black's pawn chain. Also, Black's knight can no longer develop to the most natural f6 square. }
3... c5
{ Black wants to attack and exchange the d4 pawn. If that happens, our e5-pawn will become weak. That's why we should defend this pawn. }
4. c3 { Supporting our pawn on d4 } 4... Nc6
{ 4...Qb6  5.Nf3  Developing, supporting the d4-pawn and preparing to castle  5...Bd7   5...Nc6  transposes to the French mainline.  6.Bd3  We develop and prepare to castle.  6...Bb5   6...Nc6  will transpose to the mainline, which is covered later in this chapter.  7.Bxb5+  Qxb5  The queen prevents us from castling.  8.Na3   We attack the queen and develop with tempo. When Black plays  8...Qa6  , we can go for  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.b4  Be7  11.Nd4  Next move, we can play  Nab5  and try to threaten  Nc7+  forking the king and queen.   4...Bd7  Black will play for a strategy to play Qb6 and exchange the light-squared bishop with Bb5.  5.Nf3  .   4...cxd4  We are happy to see this pawn trade.  5.cxd4  Nc6  Developing and attacking d4  6.Nf3  Developing and defending d4  6...Bb4+   6...Nge7  Black wants to play Nf5 and attack the d4 pawn more often.  7.Bd3  Nf5  8.Bxf5  Giving Black doubled pawns and ensuring that only one of knight is attacking our d4-pawn  8...exf5  9.Nc3  White is ready to castle and has a good position  7.Nc3  Nge7  8.Bd3  The light-squared bishop on d3 is well-placed looking at the h7-square.  8...O-O  The most popular move on the 1600-level and a horrible mistake  9.Bxh7+  This idea is known as the Greek gift. When Black captures the bishop, we have a famous checkmating idea  9...Kxh7  10.Ng5+  Kg8   After  10...Kg6  many moves are winning, most convincing is  11.h4  which threatens h5+, and subsequently when Black has to play ...Kh6, we can win the queen with a discovered check by play Nxf7+.  11.Qh5   The idea is to play Qh7 mate on the next move After  11...Re8  12.Qh7+  Kf8  13.Qh8+  Ng8  14.Nh7+  Ke7  15.Bg5+  White is completely winning. Black doesn't have any good moves; after  15...Nf6  , we play  16.Qxg7  , we will win the knight on f6 next and have a devastating attack. }
5. Nf3 { Developing and providing more protection to the d4-pawn. } 5... Qb6 6.
Bd3 { Setting up a trick for our opponent } 6... Bd7
{ 6...cxd4  7.cxd4  Bd7  This is a cunning move from Black, with this move, Black prepares to capture the pawn on d4.   7...Nxd4  Are we just giving up a pawn for free???  8.Nxd4  Qxd4  Of course, we didn't give the pawn for free, the discovered attack ensures we are winning the queen now.  9.Bb5+   Discovered check winning the queen! After  9...Bd7  , we first play  10.Bxd7+  and only after  10...Kxd7  we capture the queen with  11.Qxd4  .  8.O-O  We sacrifice the pawn for piece activity.  8...Nxd4  9.Nbd2  We want to develop the knight to get a lead in development in exchange for the pawn.  9...Nxf3+   9...Bc5  10.Nxd4  When we trade knights, we are ready to play Qh5 and bring the queen into the attack.  10...Bxd4  11.Qh5   The variation could continue with  11...Ne7  12.Nf3  Ng6  13.Bd2  For Black, it will be dangerous to capture on  b2  because our rook will get very active on the b file.   If Black instead plays  11...Bb5  we can play  12.Bxb5+  Qxb5  and  13.Qg5  attacking the g7-pawn.   9...Ne7  10.Nxd4  Qxd4  11.Nf3  Attacking the queen, defending the e5-pawn, and opening the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop!  11...Qb6  12.Be3   When Black plays  12...Qxb2  with  13.Rb1  Qxa2  14.Rxb7  , our rook becomes very active.   9...Nc6  10.Nb3  We prepare to develop the dark-squared bishop with tempo.  10...Nge7  11.Be3  Developing with tempo  11...Qc7  12.Rc1  Activating the rook and pinning the knight. We are planning to play Nc5 on the next move  10.Nxf3  Bb5   10...Ne7  11.Be3   Attacking the queen and developing with tempo.  11...Qxb2  would be dangerous for Black. We play  12.Rb1  and capture the b7-pawn next with a great position.  11...Qd8  12.Rc1  It is a typical plan to play h4, h5, and h6 to weaken the Black's king.  11.Be3  Developing and attacking the queen with tempo }
7. dxc5
{ At first, it may seem like we are helping Black's development, nevertheless, the Black's dark-squared bishop can be in a lot of danger on c5. }
7... Bxc5 8. O-O
{ By castling, we safeguard the f2 pawn. What should make us very happy is that the by far most popular move in 1600-level is a big blunder. }
8... a5
{ The best move for Black preventing us from playing b4.   8...Nge7  This move looks very logical, just developing the knight and preparing to castle.  9.b4  The bishop is trapped, White has a winning position.   8...f6  9.b4  We chase the bishop away to e7 where it is blocking the development of the g8 knight.  9...Be7  10.Re1  Next, we are ready to develop the dark-squared bishop with tempo and develop the knight on b1. }
9. Qe2
{ The game could continue with  9...Nge7  10.Nbd2  O-O  11.Nb3  And we would be able to trade the powerful dark-squared bishop for our knight. }
