[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French 1.e4 e6 is the third most popular move at the 1600-level. } 2. d4
{ Just like in the Alapin, we love to get our pawn on e4 and d4. With both pawns in the center, we can develop both the bishops and the queen whenever we want, as well as go for our knight-hunting ideas. }
2... d5 { The idea of the French opening is to strike back in the center. } 3.
e5
{ We go for the Advance Variation in the French. When we play e5, Black's light-squared bishop is locked in by Black's pawn chain. Also, Black's knight can no longer develop to the most natural f6-square. }
3... c5
{ Black wants to attack and exchange the d4-pawn. If that happens, our e5-pawn would become weak. That's why we should defend this pawn. }
4. c3 { Supporting our d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6 5. Nf3
{ Developing and providing more protection to the d4-pawn. } 5... Qb6 6. Bd3
{ Setting up a trick for our opponent. } 6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Bd7
{ This is a cunning move that prepares to capture the d4-pawn. } 8. O-O
{ We sacrifice the pawn for piece activity. } 8... Nxd4 9. Nbd2
{ We want to develop the knight and get a lead in development in exchange for the pawn. }
9... Nxf3+ 10. Nxf3 Bb5
{ After  10...Bc5  we will play  11.Rb1  the idea is that after  11...Ne7  12.b4  White already has a winning position. Black cannot capture the pawn as their bishop will be in a deadly pin and lost soon. So after  12...Bd4  we can play  13.Qd2  preventing Black bishop from running away with ...Bc3. Now Black is unable to castle since after  13...O-O  14.Nxd4  wins the bishop and  14...Qxd4?  15.Bxh7+  wins the queen.   When Black responds with  10...Bc5  11.Rb1  a5  we will play  12.a3  reinforcing the threat of b4. }
11. Be3 { Developing and attacking the queen with tempo. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. French Defense"]
[Black "French Defense: 3...c5 with 4...Nc6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French 1.e4 e6 is the third most popular move at the 1600-level. } 2. d4
{ Just like in the Alapin, we love to get our pawn on e4 and d4. With both pawns in the center, we can develop both the bishops and the queen whenever we want, as well as go for our knight-hunting ideas. }
2... d5 { The idea of the French opening is to strike back in the center. } 3.
e5
{ We go for the Advance Variation in the French. When we play e5, Black's light-squared bishop is locked in by Black's pawn chain. Also, Black's knight can no longer develop to the most natural f6-square. }
3... c5
{ Black wants to attack and exchange the d4-pawn. If that happens, our e5-pawn would become weak. That's why we should defend this pawn. }
4. c3 { Supporting our d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6 5. Nf3
{ Developing and providing more protection to the d4-pawn. Black usually continues with  5...Qb6  6.Bd3  Bd7  this position can also be reached from the  5...Bd7  6.Bd3  Qb6  move order. }
5... Qb6 6. Bd3 { Setting up a trick for our opponent. } 6... Bd7 7. dxc5
{ At first, it may seem like we are helping Black's development; nevertheless, Black's dark-squared bishop can be in a lot of danger on c5. }
7... Bxc5 8. O-O
{ By castling, we safeguard the f2-square. What should make us very happy is that the by far most popular move at the 1600-level is a big blunder. }
8... Nge7
{ This move looks very logical, just developing the knight and preparing to castle . }
9. b4
{ The bishop is trapped and White has a winning position. Check out how GM Ivic converted this winning position in the model game. }
*

