[White "17. French Defense: Tactics "]
[Black "Exercise 3: French Defense "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/2n1p3/3pP3/1b1P4/2NB1N2/PP3PPP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Do you know the famous Greek gift tactic? } 9. Bxh7+
{ This idea is known as the Greek gift. When Black captures the bishop, we have a famous checkmating idea }
9... Kxh7 10. Ng5+ Kg8
{ After  10...Kg6  many moves are winning, the most convincing is  11.h4  which threatens h5+ and subsequently when Black has to play Kh6, we can win the queen with a discovered check by playing Nxf7+. }
11. Qh5
{ The idea is to play Qh7 mate on the next move. After  11...Re8  12.Qh7+  Kf8  13.Qh8+  Ng8  14.Nh7+  Ke7  15.Bg5+  White is winning. Black doesn't have any good moves; after  15...Nf6  we play  16.Qxg7  we will win the knight next and have a devastating attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Chapter Summary: Caro-Kann"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann is closely related to the French opening, and Black prepares to strike back in the center on the second move by playing d5. }
2. d4
{ We love to get our pawns on e4 and d4 when Black doesn't prevent us from doing so. }
2... d5 3. e5
{ Just like in the French defense, we are going for the advanced variation. The idea is to prevent Black from developing without concerns. With e5, we take away the natural f6 square for Black's knight. }
3... Bf5
{ Black's main idea of playing the Caro-Kann compared to the French is to make sure that the light-squared can develop. In the advanced French variation after   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  , Black's bishop is stuck behind the e6-pawn.   3...c5  Black attacks the d4-pawn.  4.dxc5  We capture the pawn and challenge Black to win it back.  4...Nc6   Developing and attacking  e5  . Instead,  4...Qa5  wouldn't win the pawn back after  5.Nc3  Qxc5  we play  6.Qxd5!   4...e6  5.Nf3   It would be a mistake to play  5.b4  defending the pawn since after  5...a5  undermining our b4-pawn  6.c3  axb4  7.cxb4  b6  threatening to win the  c5  pawn  8.cxb6  Bxb4+  9.Bd2  Qxb6  Black has a better position.  5...Bxc5  6.Bd3  We are ready to castle! Also, we can play a3, b4, and Bb2, gaining a tempo on Black's dark-squared bishop and developing.  5.Nf3  We develop and defend the e5-pawn.  5...Bg4  6.c3  We want to keep our extra pawn on c5 and prepare to play b4.  6...Bxf3   6...Nxe5  A big blunder from Black! And also the second-most-popular move at 1600-level. We saw the same tactic in the Alapin.  7.Nxe5  Bxd1  8.Bb5+  This deadly check ensures that we will regain the queen.  8...Qd7  9.Bxd7+  We will be two pieces up, and the computer gives +10.   6...e6  7.Be3  7.b4 would also be fine. I like 7.Be3 more since we prepare a nasty trick.  7...Bxf3   7...Nxe5  By far the most popular move on 1600-level. This time we have a different trick.  8.Qa4+  This check is deadly! We are unpinning the knight and attacking the king, knight, and bishop simultaneously. White is winning a piece, and the computer gives +7.  8.Qxf3  Nxe5  9.Bb5+  The knight has to retreat to c6 to block the check, and White is ready to castle.  7.Qxf3  Nxe5  Black regained the pawn  8.Bb5+  Developing with a check! The knight has to go back to c6. White has better development and a better position. We are ready to castle next move. }
4. h4
{ This move requires some explanation. Why do we push a pawn instead of playing a standard developing move like  4.Nf3?  The idea behind this move is prophylactic. It is just as essential to prevent our opponent from developing as it is for us to develop our pieces.  4.h4  prevents Black from playing  4...e6  and subsequently developing all the pieces on the kingside and castling. }
4... h5
{ The main move at the top level! At the 1600-level only the third most popular move.   4...e6  Black falls for our trap! This is the second most popular move at the 1600-level.  5.g4  Planning to trap the bishop.  5...Be4   After  5...Bg6  6.h5  Be4  7.f3  , the bishop is also trapped.  6.f3  Bg6  7.h5  White wins the bishop and has a winning position.   4...h6  Black is making space for the light-squared bishop on h7 to avoid getting trapped.  5.g4   What are we doing? Pushing our pawns? Pay attention; this is important. Again our play is prophylactic. Black needs to play e6 to develop the dark-squared bishop and eventually castle. With  5.g4  we force Black to move the bishop either with  5...Bh7  @@StartBracket@@  5...Be4  6.f3  Bh7  is more or less the same@@EndBracket@@ or with  5...Bd7  .   After  5...Bh7  , we play  6.e6  , which ensures Black's e7-pawn will not move forward, which means that Black's dark-squared bishop on  f8  will remain completely stuck.   Whereas after  5...Bd7  Black moves the bishop to a passive square and surrenders the whole Caro-Kann dream that it would be possible to get a position where Black's light-squared bishop was out of the pawn chain.  5...Bd7  The most popular move on the top level, but a rarely played move at the 1600-level.   5...Bh7  6.e6  A brilliant idea! We prevent Black forever from playing e6 and ensure the Black's dark-squared bishop on f8 is completely stuck.  6...fxe6  7.Bd3  Exchanging Black's strong bishop and gaining control of the light squares.  7...Bxd3  By far the most popular move at the 1600-level and again a significant mistake.   7...Nf6  8.Bxh7  Rxh7  9.Qd3  Next three moves, you want to bring the knight to e5 and play Qg6 mate!  8.Qxd3  Our knight would be a monster on e5! If we could make three more moves, Nf3, Ne5, and Qg6 would-be mate. White has a winning position already.  8...Nf6   8...Nd7  This is played a lot at 1600-level and accelerates our victory.  9.Qg6  Mate!  9.Qg6+  Kd7  10.Nf3  The threat is Ne5+ and subsequently Nf7 forking the queen and the rook. White is winning   5...Be4  6.f3  Bh7  7.e6  A brilliant idea! We prevent Black forever from playing e6 and ensure the Black's dark-squared bishop on f8 is completely stuck.  7...Qd6  The strongest move for Black. I played this myself in France in 2018 in a classical game as Black against international master Shkapenko; the game finished in a draw Black threatens to capture on e6 with the queen and to give a check on g3.   7...fxe6  8.Bd3  Let's exchange Black's good light-squared bishop and gain control on the light-squares.  8.exf7+  Kxf7  9.f4  Defending against Qg3+ and preparing to get our knight on a beautiful outpost on e5. Also, we would like to trade Black's strong light-squared bishop with Bd3. White has a nice position.  6.Be3  As we have pushed our pawns forward on the kingside, we plan to castle queenside. We can do that by playing Nc3, Qd2, and O-O-O. At this point, we cannot play Qd2 yet, since Black is attacking the g4 pawn with their light-squared bishop, but once Black plays e6, we can safely play Qd2. }
5. Bd3
{ Black did so much effort to get a beautiful light-squared bishop. So let's be mean and exchange it. }
5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6
{ 6...Qa5+  7.Nd2  If Black doesn't play e6, we will play e6, which forever locks in the Black's dark-squared bishop on f8. We can continue development with Ne2 and O-O. We will keep the f3-square open for our knight on d2. The model games will show a fanatic win from Caruana against Firouzja with this opening. }
7. Bg5 { Developing and attacking the queen } 7... Qb6
{ 7...Be7  8.Nf3   Developing and defending the bishop.  8...Bxg5  would benefit us since after  9.hxg5  our rook on  h1  is activated.  8...Nd7  9.Nbd2   White has a lead in development and is ready to castle. Black is still struggling to develop the knight on g8. After  9...Nh6  we play  10.Bxh6  and force Black to either move the rook and give up on the idea of a short castle or break the pawn structure.   After  9...Qb6  we play  10.O-O  when after  10...Qxb2  11.Bxe7  Nxe7  12.Rfb1!  Traps the queen. }
8. Nd2
{ We kindly invite Black to play  8...Qxb2  when after  9.Rb1!  9...Qxa2  10.Rxb7  White has a huge advantage. }
*

