1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann is closely related to the French opening, and Black prepares to strike back in the center on the second move by playing d5. }
2. d4
{ We love to get our pawns on e4 and d4 when Black doesn't prevent us from doing so. }
2... d5 3. e5
{ Just like in the French Defense, we are going for the Advance Variation. The idea is to prevent Black from developing freely and with e5 we take away the natural f6-square for Black's knight. }
3... c5 { Black attacks the d4-pawn. } 4. dxc5
{ We capture the pawn and challenge Black to win it back. } 4... Nc6
{ Developing and attacking e5.  4...Qa5  wouldn't win the pawn back since after  5.Nc3  Qxc5  we play  6.Qxd5! }
5. Nf3 { We develop and defend the e5-pawn. } 5... Bg4 6. c3
{ We want to keep our extra pawn on c5 and prepare to play b4. } 6... e6 7. Be3
{ 7.b4  would also be fine. I like  7.Be3  more since we prepare a nasty trick. }
7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nxe5 9. Bb5+
{ The knight has to retreat to c6 to block the check, and White is ready to castle. }
