[Black "Caro-Kann: 3... Bf5 with 4...e6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann is closely related to the French opening, and Black prepares to strike back in the center on the second move by playing d5. }
2. d4
{ We love to get our pawns on e4 and d4 when Black doesn't prevent us from doing so. }
2... d5 3. e5
{ Just like in the French Defense, we are going for the Advance Variation. The idea is to prevent Black from developing freely and with e5 we take away the natural f6-square for Black's knight. }
3... Bf5
{ Black's main idea of playing the Caro-Kann compared to the French is to make sure that the light-squared bishop can develop. In the French Advance Variation after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  we saw that the light-squared bishop was stuck behind the e6-pawn. }
4. h4
{ This move requires some explanation. Why do we push a pawn when we also can play a normal developing move like  4.Nf3  ?   The idea behind this move is prophylactic. It is just as important that we prevent our opponent from developing as it is for us to develop our pieces.  4.h4  prevents Black from playing  4...e6  and developing the dark-squared bishop. }
4... e6
{ Black falls for our trap! This is the second most popular move at the 1600-level. }
5. g4 { Planning to trap the bishop. } 5... Be4
{ After  5...Bg6  6.h5  Be4  7.f3  the bishop is also trapped. } 6. f3 Bg6 7.
h5 { White wins the bishop and has a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Caro-Kann: 3...Bf5 with 4...h6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ The Caro-Kann is closely related to the French opening, and Black prepares to strike back in the center on the second move by playing d5. }
2. d4
{ We love to get our pawns on e4 and d4 when Black doesn't prevent us from doing so. }
2... d5 3. e5
{ Just like in the French Defense, we are going for the Advance Variation. The idea is to prevent Black from developing freely and with e5 we take away the natural f6-square for Black's knight. }
3... Bf5
{ Black's main idea of playing the Caro-Kann compared to the French is to make sure that the light-squared bishop can develop. In the French Advance Variation after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  we saw that the light-squared bishop was stuck behind the e6-pawn. }
4. h4
{ This move requires some explanation. Why do we push a pawn when we also can play a normal developing move like  4.Nf3  ?  The idea behind this move is prophylactic. It is just as important that we prevent our opponent from developing as it is for us to develop our pieces.  4.h4  prevents Black from playing  4...e6  and developing the dark-squared bishop. }
4... h6
{ Black is making space to avoid getting the light-squared bishop trapped. } 5.
g4
{ What are we doing? Pushing our pawns? Pay attention, this is important. Again our play is prophylactic. Black needs to play e6 to develop the dark-squared bishop and eventually castle.   With 5.g4 we force Black to move the bishop either with 5... Bh7 @@StartBracket@@  5...Be4  6.f3  Bh7  is more or less the same@@EndBracket@@ or with 5...Bd7  .   After  5...Bh7  we play  6.e6  which ensures Black's pawn on e7 will not move forward, which means that Black's dark-squared bishop on f8 will remain completely stuck.   Whereas after  5...Bd7  Black moves the bishop to a passive square and surrenders the whole Caro-Kann dream of getting a position in which Black's light-squared bishop is out of the pawn chain. }
5... Bh7 6. e6
{ A brilliant idea! We prevent Black forever from playing e6 and ensure Black's dark-squared bishop on f8 is completely stuck. }
6... fxe6 7. Bd3
{ Exchanging Black's strong bishop and gaining control over the light squares. }
7... Bxd3
{ By far the most popular move at the 1600-level and it, once again, is a significant mistake. }
8. Qxd3
{ Our knight would be a monster on e5! If we could make three more moves, then Nf3, Ne5 and Qg6 would be mate. White already has a winning position. }
8... Nd7
{ This is played a lot at the 1600-level and accelerates our victory. } 9. Qg6#
{ Checkmate! } *

