{ Black's main idea of playing the Caro-Kann compared to the French is to make sure that the light-squared bishop can develop. In the French Advance Variation after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.e5  we saw that the light-squared bishop was stuck behind the e6-pawn. }
4. h4
{ This move requires some explanation. Why do we push a pawn when we also can play a normal developing move like  4.Nf3  ?  The idea behind this move is prophylactic. It is just as important that we prevent our opponent from developing as it is for us to develop our pieces.  4.h4  prevents Black from playing  4...e6  and developing the dark-squared bishop. }
4... h5
{ The main move at the top level! At the 1600-level, it is only the third most popular move as more opponents would allow you to trap the bishop :@@EndBracket@@ or play 4...h6. Black is more or less forced to move the h-pawn since our idea of playing 4.h4 was trapping the light-squared bishop. Therefore, Black needs to free the h7-square to safeguard the bishop. }
5. Bd3
{ Black made a lot of effort to get a beautiful light-squared bishop. So let's be mean and exchange it. }
5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 { Developing and attacking the queen. } 7... Qb6 8.
Nd2
{ We kindly invite Black to play  8...Qxb2  when after  9.Rb1!  Qxa2  10.Rxb7  White has a huge advantage. }
