[White "20. Scandinavian"]
[Black "Chapter Summary: Scandinavian"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ In the Scandinavian opening, Black immediately attacks our e4-pawn. } 2. exd5
{ We capture the pawn, forcing Black's queen to recapture it. } 2... Qxd5
{ 2...Nf6  Black is scared to bring out the queen early and tries to recapture the pawn with the knight. We don't protect the pawn and play d4.  3.d4   Protecting the pawn with  3.Nc3  didn't help since Black would still play  3...Nxd5  .   After  3.c4  Black will play  3...c6  When after  4.dxc6  Nxc6  , Black's lead in development fully compensates for the pawn.  3...Nxd5  4.Nf3   We delayed  4.c4  to wait for the moment when Black plays ...Nc6 because now after  4.Nf3  Nc6  when we play  5.c4  attacking the knight after Black's knight moves  5...Nf6  , we can also hunt the other knight with  6.d5  . }
3. d4
{ This move is not so popular. Nevertheless, it is, in my opinion, the most tricky way to play against the Scandinavian. We develop with tempo after the main move 3.Nc3; however, the downside is that Black's queen moves to a safer square. With  3.d4  , we put our pawn in the center, and we wait for a perfect moment to target Black's queen on d5. After  3...c6  or  3...Qd8  , we continue with  4.Nf3  and plan to continue development with Be2, O-O, c4, Nc3. }
3... Nc6
{ Black's main move and most logical move. Black is targetting our d4-pawn. We are happy to see the knight on c6 because what we already learned in the Alapin is that we can go knight-hunting and play d5 after we have managed to chase away Black's queen on d5. First, we should develop and defend the d4 pawn.   3...e5  Black wants to strike immediately in the center.  4.Nc3   Developing and attacking the queen. We shouldn't play  4.dxe5  since after  4...Qxd1  5.Kxd1  We lost our right to castle and after  5...Nc6  6.Nf3  Bg4  Black will also regain the e5-pawn.  4...Qxd4   After  4...Bb4  , we play  5.Nge2  supporting our knight. The game could continue with  5...exd4  6.Qxd4  Qxd4  7.Nxd4  Bxc3  8.bxc3  White has an excellent position and plans Ba3, Bc4, and bringing the rooks to the open e and d-files.  5.Qxd4  exd4  6.Nb5  Double attack on c7 and d4.  6...Na6  7.Nf3   There is no need to play  7.Nxd4  on the previous move, we want to develop as quickly as possible.  7...c5  Defending the d4-pawn.  8.Bc4  We are ready to castle, bring the rook to the open e-file and develop the dark-squared bishop. Black's king is still in the middle of the board and is in danger.   3...Nf6  4.Nf3  Developing and preparing to castle. We want to wait with attacking the queen on d5 until Black has played Nc6.  4...Bg4   Pinning the knight.  4...Nc6  5.c4  transposes to the mainline that will be covered later.  5.Be2  Defending on f3 and preparing to castle.  5...Nc6   The knight is on c6 now, so we want to chase the queen and subsequently hunt the knight! There is one issue: after  6.c4  Qd7  7.d5  , Black can still play  7...Bxf3  8.Bxf3  Ne5  and Black knight still find a nice square in the center. That's why we first chase the bishop to g6 and subsequently go for our plan to attack the queen and hunt the knight.  6.h3  Aiming to chase the bishop to c6!  6...Bxf3   6...Bh5  The most popular move at the 1600-level, but this is a significant mistake.  7.g4  We attack the bishop again and chase it to g6 so that the bishop no longer can capture the knight.  7...Bg6  8.c4   Attacking the queen and strengthening the control over the d5-square. As a rule of thumb, when Black plays with ...Nf6, we will go for c4 and d5 hunting the knight on c6! Whereas when Black plays without the ...Nf6, we go for Nc3 followed by d5. We should avoid  8.Nc3  Qa5  9.d5  O-O-O  When Black counters our knight-hunt with a strong pin and will win the d5-pawn.  8...Qd7  9.d5  We timed the knight-hunt to perfection! Our knight on f3 controls both center squares Black's knight could jump to, so Black's knight doesn't have any good squares. The game could continue with   @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pppqpppp/2n2nb1/3P4/2P3P1/5N1P/PP2BP2/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nb4  10.Ne5  Qd6  11.Nxg6  hxg6  12.Qa4+  c6  13.a3  Black's knight will have to retreat to the weak a6. White has a significant advantage.  7.Bxf3  Qe6+   Slightly better for Black would be  7...Qd7  , which has rarely been played at the 1600-level. Then we play  8.O-O  O-O-O  9.c3  White keeps a nice advantage and a strong light-squared bishop.   7...Qxd4  Black's most popular move at the 1600-level, and a big blunder.  8.Bxc6+  We eliminate the knight to win the queen.  8...bxc6  9.Qxd4  Winning the queen:@@EndBracket@@  8.Be3  Developing the bishop! We threaten d5, forking the queen and knight. }
4. Nf3
{ We develop and defend in the center. We are ready for our knight-hunting plan to attack the queen with either c4 or Nc3 and subsequently, after the queen moves, play d5 hunting the knight on c6. At this point, Black is in a tough spot, and they have to play multiple good moves to get a playable position. }
4... Bg4
{ Developing and counterattacking by pinning our knight. After  4...e5  , We play the strong  5.Nc3  developing and attacking the queen and after  5...Bb4  6.Bd2  Bxc3  7.Bxc3  White threatens to capture on  e5  and has a better position.   4...Nf6  5.c4   Attacking the queen and strengthening our center. After  5...Qe4  we play  6.Be2  preparing to castle.   After  5...Qa5+  we play  6.Bd2  developing and attacking the queen with tempo. White has a great position. }
5. Nc3
{ Developing and attacking the queen. This position is the same as the Alapin Barmen's Defense, but the c-pawns are still on the board. When Black's queens moves, we plan to continue with d5, hunting the knight! }
5... Qh5
{ The only good move for Black and also the sixth most popular move at the 1600-level.  5...Qa5  would not be so strong from Black. Here is the strongest to delay the knight-hunt for one move and first play  6.Bb5  pinning the knight and threatening d5.   5...Bxf3  This is the second most popular move at the 1600-level, it is a big mistake.  6.Nxd5  We had the same position as the Alapin, with the only difference that the c-pawns are still on the board. We play in the same fashion, and after the trade of queens, we will win the rook! This is even stronger than in the Alapin since we will also capture the c-pawn.  6...Bxd1  7.Nxc7+  A nice fork, and we are winning the rook on a8.  7...Kd8  8.Nxa8  Bxc2  9.d5  We finish the variation with our signature knight-hunting move. We kick away the knight from the comfortable c6 square, and the knight will be misplaced regardless of where it moves. White has a winning position.   5...Qe6+  The most popular move at the 1600-level and a big mistake. The queen is misplaced here, blocking the e7 pawn, which makes Black unable to develop the dark-squared bishop.  6.Be3   We don't play  6.Be2  since after  6...Bxf3  Black weakens our pawn structure, and we must recapture with  7.gxf3  .  6...O-O-O   6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  Nxd4  The most popular move on 1600-level, White is winning now.  8.Qxb7   An essential attacking move and the only good move. After  8...Nxc2  9.Kd2  , we are attacking the rook and the knight. Also, Bb5+ is a threat. The computer gives  +10.   After  8...Rd8  9.O-O-O  bringing our king to safety and attacking the knight. White is also winning the computer gives  +9.  7.d5  Qf6   7...Qf5  8.Bd3  Attacking the queen and also breaking the pin of Black's rook on the d5 pawn. That's why we are also threatening to capture the knight next move. White is winning a piece.  8.Be2   White has a beautiful position. After  8...Bxf3  9.Bxf3  Ne5  , we retreat the bishop with  10.Be2  White has a much safer king and a winning position.   5...Qd7  6.d5  Going for the knight-hunt.  6...Nb4  7.a3  Bxf3  8.gxf3   8.Qxf3  doesn't work since  8...Nxc2+  forks the king and the rook, giving Black a winning position. After Black plays the forced  8...Na6  retreating to the edge of the board, we can continue with Bf4, Qd4, and O-O-O. The computer already gives +7 as White has a much safer king and a lead in development.   5...Qd8  6.d5  Our signature knight-hunting move.  6...Ne5  7.Nxe5  The big queen sacrifice trick ones again!!!  7...Bxd1  8.Bb5+  This check is deadly.  8...c6  9.dxc6  With c7+, we threaten mate and the queen with a discovered attack.  9...a6  10.c7+  Discovered check! We will regain the queen.  10...axb5  11.cxd8=Q+  Rxd8  12.Nxd1  White remains with a piece up, the computer gives +7. }
6. d5 { Going for another knight-hunt. } 6... O-O-O
{ Black is pinning the d5-pawn and castling.   6...Ne5  7.Be2  Developing and defending on f3.  7...Nxf3+  8.gxf3  Gaining a tempo on the bishop. Since our pawn structure on the kingside is weak, we plan to castle on the queenside.  8...Bd7  9.Bf4  Attacking the c7 pawn. We are ready to play Qd2 and O-O-O. }
7. Be2 { Defending the knight and preparing to castle. } 7... e6
{ After  7...Bxf3  8.Bxf3  Qe5+  9.Be3  e6  10.O-O  White has a nice lead in development. }
8. Ng5
{ A brilliant move! Forcing and exchange of bishops and putting pressure on f7. }
8... Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2
{ The queens are traded, so; it is safe to capture with the king. We are attacking the pawn on f7 and the knight on c6. Black only has one move to survive. }
10... Ne5 { Black's only move to save the knight and defend on f7. } 11. f4
{ Attacking the knight and threatening to capture on f7 when the knight moves. }
11... h6
{ Again, the only good move Black can play, counterattacking our knight on g5. }
12. fxe5 hxg5 13. Bxg5
{ Black found all the defensive moves, nevertheless White still has a better position, and we are attacking the rook. }
