1. e4 d5
{ In the Scandinavian opening, Black immediately attacks our e4-pawn. } 2. exd5
{ We capture the pawn, forcing Black's queen to recapture. } 2... Nf6
{ Black is scared to bring out the queen early and tries to recapture the pawn with the knight. We don't protect the pawn and play d4. }
3. d4
{ Protecting the pawn with  3.Nc3  doesn't help since Black would still play  3...Nxd5  .   After  3.c4  Black plays  3...c6  when after  4.dxc6  Nxc6  Black's lead in development fully compensates for the pawn. }
3... Nxd5
{ 3...Qxd5  4.Nf3  transposes to the mainline, covered later.   After  3...Bg4  we reply with  4.Bb5+  when after  4...c6  5.dxc6  Nxc6  6.Bxc6+  bxc6  7.Nf3  White is a pawn up and has a significant advantage.   At the 1600-level is it more popular to capture the queen on move 6 which doesn't work  3...Bg4  4.Bb5+  c6  5.dxc6  Bxd1  would lose for Black after  7.c7+  When White wins the queen with a discovered check and remains a piece up.   After  3...Bg4  4.Bb5+  c6  5.dxc6  bxc6  6.Be2  White has a significant advantage.   If Black instead plays  3...Bg4  4.Bb5+  Nbd7  we also retreat with  5.Be2  Bxe2  6.Qxe2  Nxd5  7.Nf3  White is ready to castle and play  c4  and has a better position. }
4. Nf3 Bg4 { Black develops and pins the knight. } 5. Be2
{ We develop and unpin the knight. After  5...Nc6  we will go for the knight-hunt with  6.c4  Nf6  7.d5  and after  7...Bxf3  8.Bxf3  Ne5  9.O-O  White has a big lead in development and Black cannot play  9...Nxc4  since  10.Qa4+  wins the knight. }
5... e6 6. O-O Bd6 { Black develops and prepares to castle. } 7. h3
{ We chase away the bishop as  7...Bxf3  8.Bxf3  would be a favorable trade for us.   Our point is that after  7...Bh5  8.c4  Nf4  9.Bxf4  Bxf4  10.Qb3  is cunning as we threaten Qxb7 and Qb5+ forking the king and bishop. }
