[Black "Scandinavian: 3...Nf6#1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ In the Scandinavian opening, Black immediately attacks our e4-pawn. } 2. exd5
{ We capture the pawn, forcing Black's queen to recapture. } 2... Qxd5 3. d4
{ This move is not so popular. Nevertheless, it is, in my opinion, the most tricky way to play against the Scandinavian. We develop with tempo after the main move  3.Nc3  ;  (however, the downside is that Black's queen moves to a safer square.)   With  3.d4  , we put our pawn in the center and wait for the perfect moment to target Black's queen. After  3...c6  or  3...Qd8  , we continue with  4.Nf3  and plan to continue development with Be2, O-O, c4, Nc3. }
3... Nf6 4. Nf3
{ Developing and preparing to castle. We want to wait with attacking the queen on d5 until Black has played Nc6. }
4... Bg4
{ Pinning the knight.  4...Nc6  5.c4  transposes to the mainline that will be covered later. }
5. Be2
{ Defending the knight and preparing to castle. Check out how the 5-time World Championship Anand won against the 2021 World Cup Winner Duda from this position in the model game. }
5... Nc6
{ The knight came out now, so we want to chase the queen and subsequently hunt the knight! There is one issue: after  6.c4  Qd7  7.d5  Black can still play  7...Bxf3  8.Bxf3  Ne5  and Black's knight still finds a nice square in the center. That's why we first chase the bishop to g6 and subsequently go for our plan to attack the queen and hunt the knight. }
6. h3 { Aiming to chase the bishop to g6! } 6... Bh5
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level, but this is a significant mistake. }
7. g4
{ We attack the bishop again and chase it to g6, so that the bishop no longer can capture the knight. }
7... Bg6 8. c4
{ Attacking the queen and strengthening the control over the d5-square. As a rule of thumb, when Black plays Nf6, we will go for c4 and d5, hunting the knight on c6. Whereas when Black plays without Nf6, we go for Nc3 followed by d5.   We should avoid  8.Nc3  Qa5  9.d5  O-O-O  when Black counters our knight-hunt with a strong pin  and wins the d5-pawn. }
8... Qd7 9. d5
{ We timed the knight hunt to perfection! Our knight on f3 controls both central squares Black's knight could jump to, so it doesn't have any good squares. The game could continue with  9...Nb4  10.Ne5  Qd6  11.Nxg6  hxg6  12.Qa4+  c6  13.a3  when Black's knight will have to retreat, and White has a significant advantage. }
