[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Scandinavian: Tactics "]
[Black "Exercise 1: Scandinavian "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3kbnr/ppp1pppp/2n5/3q4/3P4/2N2b2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find the strongest continuation for White. } 6. Nxd5
{ We should always consider the captures first.  6.gxf3  is not good since Black wins a pawn with  6...Qxd4  .   Even worse is  6.Qxf3  Qxf3  7.gxf3  Nxd4  when Black is  also a pawn up and threatening the c2- and f3-pawns. }
6... Bxd1 7. Nxc7+ { And we are winning material! } 7... Kd8 8. Nxa8 Bxc2
{ We have seen positions before where the knight ends up capturing a rook in the corner. Often this knight could be vulnerable or lost since it is in the opponent's territory! We still need to play accurately here to maintain our advantage. }
9. d5
{ Our signature knight-hunting move. There aren't any good squares. After  9...Nb8  or  9...Ne5  , we could develop the bishop with tempo by  10.Bf4  . The bishop on f4 also supports our knight in escaping to safety with Nc7.   After  9...Nd4  we play  10.Be3  developing with tempo. Therefore,  9...Nb4  would be Black's best bet. We can play  10.Bc4  defending the d5-pawn, and subsequently, we can quickly activate the c1-bishop and a1-rook. }
