1. e4 g6 { The Modern opening. } 2. d4 { We grab the center! } 2... Bg7 3. Nc3
{ Against this set-up, we are playing for a queenside castle. That's why we first develop the pieces on the queenside. }
3... d6 4. Be3 { Developing the bishop and preparing for a queenside castle. }
4... a6 5. Qd2 { We are ready to castle queenside next! } 5... b5 6. O-O-O
{ We plan to play f3, supporting our center, and subsequently, we can go for the attack with h4 and h5, also activating our rook on h1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Pirc, Modern, Alekhine and Owen's Defense "]
[Black "Pirc Defense: 1...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 { Grabbing the center. } 2... Nf6
{ Black develops and attacks the e4-pawn. } 3. Nc3
{ We develop and defend the e4-pawn. Our signature knight-hunting move  3.e5  wouldn't work since  3...dxe5  4.dxe5  Qxd1+  breaks our right to castle and after  5.Kxd1  Ng4  Black has a double-attack on the f2- and e5-pawns. }
3... g6 { The Pirc Defense. } 4. Be3
{ Developing the bishop and defending the center. In this position, we can both play for queenside or kingside castle. }
4... c6 5. Qd2
{ We are ready to castle queenside. Only if Black plays  5...b5  ignoring development to attack on the queenside, we will change our strategy and go for a kingside castle. }
5... b5 { Black threatens to chase away the knight and win the e4-pawn. } 6.
Bd3
{ It's essential to defend the e4-pawn, as Black was threatening to play b4 attacking our knight, which was defending the e4-pawn. }
6... Nbd7 7. Nf3
{ Here it is safer to castle kingside, as Black has some attacking chances on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Pirc, Modern, Alekhine and Owen's Defense "]
[Black "Pirc Defense: 1...d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 { Grabbing the center. } 2... Nf6
{ Black develops and attacks the e4-pawn. } 3. Nc3
{ We develop and defend the e4-pawn. Our signature knight-hunting move  3.e5  wouldn't work since  3...dxe5  4.dxe5  Qxd1+  breaks our right to castle and after  5.Kxd1  Ng4  Black has a double-attack on the f2- and e5-pawns. }
3... g6 4. Be3
{ Developing the bishop and defending the center. In this position, we can both play for queenside or kingside castle. }
4... Bg7 5. Qd2
{ We use this set-up with the bishop and queen to play Bh6 and trade Black's strong-dark squared bishop. Black's fianchettoed dark-squared bishop is their best defending piece and trading it helps to start a mating attack. }
5... c6 6. Bh6
{ We target Black's strong dark-squared bishop. After  6...Bxh6  7.Qxh6  Black is unable to castle. }
6... O-O 7. h4
{ Let's attack and go for checkmate. The threat of h5 is dangerous for Black. A sample variation where Black plays carelessly is  7...Nbd7  8.h5  Nxh5  9.Rxh5  gxh5  10.Qg5  when Qxg7 mate is unavoidable on the next move! }
*

