{ The Philidor Defense can also be reached through a different move order. } 2.
d4 { Grabbing the center. } 2... Nf6
{ Black develops and attacks the e4-pawn. } 3. Nc3
{ We develop and defend the e4-pawn. Our signature knight-hunting move  3.e5  wouldn't work since  3...dxe5  4.dxe5  Qxd1+  breaks our right to castle and after  5.Kxd1  Ng4  Black has a double-attack on the f2- and e5-pawns. }
3... e5
{ The difference to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  is that we developed the c3-knight first. }
4. Nf3
{ We develop and put extra pressure on e5.  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Breaking Black's right to castle is a possible alternative. Here Black still has the plan to play ...c6 to prepare ...Kc7 and create a safe square for the king. In other variations where we went for the early queen trade like here in the Scotch, Black already played ...Nc6 and cannot go for this plan to place the king on c7. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4
{ We transpose to the variations we have seen in the Philidor chapter here. } *

