[Black "Exercise 10: Petrov Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/2b1P3/2B5/5N2/PPP2nPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find the strongest move for White. } 1. Bxf7+
{ We weaken Black's king and try to set up a double attack.  1.Qd5  wouldn't work even though this move would be threatening mate and the bishop, as  1...Qe7  defends against both threats. }
1... Kxf7 2. Qd5+ { Forking the king and the bishop! } 2... Ke8
{ At the 1600-level, almost everyone played this move which is a significant mistake. The best move for Black is the crazy-looking  2...Kg6  when we play  3.Qxc5  Nxh1  4.Nc3  . White wants to create an attack against the king, develop the bishop, castle and pick up the knight on h1. }
3. Bg5
{ We are attacking the queen! Black has only one good defensive move.   3.Qxc5  looks strong at first sight because after  3...Nxh1  , we can play  4.Bg5  trapping the queen, but now Black has the counterattack  4...d6  . This move attacks our queen and creates an escape square on d7 for the queen. After  5.Qe3  Qd7  Black is doing fine. The discovered attack with  6.exd6+  is not dangerous since Black defends with  6...Qe6  trading the queens. }
3... Be7 { Should we capture the knight or the bishop? } 4. Bxe7
{ After trading the bishops, we will win the knight!  4.Kxf2  wouldn't work since after  4...Bxg5  Black is still a piece up. }
4... Qxe7 5. Kxf2
{ White has a significant advantage because of the lead in development. We can go for an artificial castle with Rf1 and Kg1. }
*

