{ How can we put a lot of pressure on Black? } 8. e5
{ Our signature knight-hunting move. In this position, we can play it even though the d6-pawn can capture us. }
8... dxe5 9. Bxf7+
{ A powerful strike. Black cannot capture the bishop as the king needs to protect the queen. }
9... Ke7 10. Qc4
{ We don't trade the queens since Black's king is in danger. We plan to play Re1 and Nc3, increasing the pressure on Black's king. White has a winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Theme-based Tactic Drills "]
[Black "Exercise 12: Petrov Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/2b1P3/4n3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Counterattack is the best defense! With that in mind, what is the best continuation? }
1. Bc4 { We are attacking the f7-pawn. } 1... Nxf2 2. Bxf7+
{ Going for the counter-attack. } 2... Kf8 3. Qd5
{ Saving our queen, attacking the dark-squared bishop, and preparing a mate threat! }
3... Nxh1 4. Bh5 { Threatening Qf7 mate! } 4... Qe7
{ Defending against the mate and protecting the dark-squared bishop. } 5. Bg5
{ Attacking the queen. The queen doesn't have a safe square from where it can keep protecting the dark-squared bishop. }
5... Bf2+ { Where should we go with the king? } 6. Ke2
{ We want to open the first rank for our rook to pick up the knight. Also, we want to keep on attacking the bishop. }
6... Qe6 7. Nc3
{ Double attack. This move is beautiful! We are playing chess like a true master, using all our pieces on the board. Our rook attacks the knight, which is doomed. Also, we defended the queen. Soon we will collect the material, and White has a significant advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Theme-based Tactic Drills "]
[Black "Exercise 13: Scotch gambit 4...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/8/2b1n1N1/2BpP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How do we punish Black for their opening mistake? } 6. Nxf7
{ We shouldn't let your opponent recover from the big shock that we just gave them! We continue with our plan, even though Black just defended the pawn! }
6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+
{ Our tactical justification, we fork the king and the bishop and win back the piece. White is in a much better position because Black's king is in a lot of trouble. }
8... g6 9. Qd5+
{ Before taking the bishop, we give one more check to force the king to a worse square. }
9... Kg7 10. Qxc5
{ White is ready to go Qxd4+ next move and has a great position! This position is a much better version than we will get in the mainline, where we will have a similar position, but in that case, Black's knight is on c6 instead of g8! }
*

