[SetUp "1"]

{ What is the strongest continuation here? } 1. Bb5+
{ Developing with check. Black is forced to block with a piece on d7, which means that subsequently, our knight-hunting idea becomes possible! It's important to note that the signature knight-hunting move  1.e5  is too early here, since after  1...dxe5  2.dxe5  Qxd1+  White either has to retreat the knight to a passive position or break the right to castle. }
1... Bd7
{ Black's light-squared bishop blocks the d-file, which makes it possible to go for the knight-hunt immediately. }
2. e5 { Going for our signature knight-hunting move. } 2... Bxb5
{ A big blunder. We are winning a piece! Yet, this is the most popular move at the 1600-level. }
3. exf6 { A double attack and White wins a piece. } 3... Bxf6 4. Nxb5 Qa5+
{ Black tries to strike back with a double attack. } 5. Nc3
{ We save our knight and have a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Theme-based Tactic Drills "]
[Black "Exercise 21: Scandinavian "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3kbnr/ppp1pppp/2n5/3q4/3P4/2N2b2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find the strongest continuation for White. } 6. Nxd5
{ We should always consider the captures first.  6.gxf3  is not good since Black wins a pawn with  6...Qxd4  .   Even worse is  6.Qxf3  Qxf3  7.gxf3  Nxd4  when Black is  also a pawn up and threatening the c2- and f3-pawns. }
6... Bxd1 7. Nxc7+ { And we are winning material! } 7... Kd8 8. Nxa8 Bxc2
{ We have seen positions before where the knight ends up capturing a rook in the corner. Often this knight could be vulnerable or lost since it is in the opponent's territory! We still need to play accurately here to maintain our advantage. }
9. d5
{ Our signature knight-hunting move. There aren't any good squares. After  9...Nb8  or  9...Ne5  , we could develop the bishop with tempo by  10.Bf4  . The bishop on f4 also supports our knight in escaping to safety with Nc7.   After  9...Nd4  we play  10.Be3  developing with tempo. Therefore,  9...Nb4  would be Black's best bet. We can play  10.Bc4  defending the d5-pawn, and subsequently, we can quickly activate the c1-bishop and a1-rook. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Theme-based Tactic Drills "]
[Black "Exercise 22: Alapin Barmen's Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3kbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/3q4/3P4/2N2b2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The game heated up, how will you continue? } 8. Nxd5
{ We capture the queen and will also gain the rook soon! } 8... Bxd1 9. Nc7+
{ Forking the king and the rook. } 9... Kd7 10. Nxa8
{ We are an exchange up. Black has only one good move here. } 10... Bh5
{ Black's only good move. } 11. d5
{ We continue with our signature knight-hunting move. Again Black has only one move not to be lost. }
11... Nd4 { 11...Nb4  12.Bf4  Nc2+  13.Kd2  transposes. } 12. Bf4
{ We kindly invite Black to win our rook in the corner. } 12... Nc2+
{ Black is greedy and goes for the rook. This has been played in all of the games at the 1600-level in my database. Instead Black's best move  12...e5  when after  13.dxe6+  fxe6  14.f3  White plans to continue with  Rd1  pinning the knight. }
13. Kd2 Nxa1 14. Bb5+
{ We are a rook down; however, White will play for a mate, and has a winning position. }
14... Kd8 15. Bc7+
{ After  15...Kc8  16.Rc1  White plans to play Be5+ and after ...Kd8 go Rc7-Rxb7-Rb8 mate! Black pieces are too underdeveloped to defend well against this plan, and White has a winning position. }
*

