[SetUp "1"]

{ Black just gave an annoying check! Are there any tactical ideas in this position? }
1. Kd1
{ This move surely requires some explanation! We give up on our right to castle and keep the king in the middle, but why? The reason is tactical! We just want to win the knight on e4 and capture it on the next move.   That's why we didn't want to play  1.Nbd2  or  1.Bd2  because it allows Black to trade the knight and solve this problem!   1.c3  may look logical because you are attacking the knight and the bishop but it doesn't work tactically after  1...dxc3  2.Qxe4  there is  2...cxb2+  and Black will capture our rook on a1 and promote.   So if we play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n5/4P3/1bB1n3/2p2N2/PP2QPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.bxc3  instead, the knight escapes after  2...Nxc3  and we are in trouble.   1.Kf1  would also have been possible. }
1... Nc5 2. a3 { Forcing the bishop to a5, we are ready to go for a fork. }
2... Ba5 3. Bg5
{ Even stronger than  3.b4  .  We are developing with tempo and attacking the queen. }
3... Ne7
{ Black is forced to retreat with the knight, since after  3...f6  attacking the bishop  4.exf6+  would be a deadly discovered check. }
4. b4 { Forking the bishop and the knight. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Theme-based Tactic Drills "]
[Black "Exercise 29: Scotch Gambit 4...Nf6 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n5/4P3/1bBpn3/5N2/PPP1QPPP/RNB1K2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What would you play here? } 1. Kd1 f5
{ This is the best move for Black since  1...Nc5  doesn't work, as shown in the previous tactic. }
2. exf6
{ We should make use of the en-passant rule! Now we are attacking the knight and the g7-pawn.  The game could continue with  2...d5  3.fxg7  Rg8  4.Nbd2  dxc4  5.Qxe4  with a large opening advantage for White.   In case of @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n5/4P3/1bBpn3/5N2/PPP1QPPP/RNBK3R b kq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  we should also capture en-passant with  2.exd6  winning the pawn and reinforcing the threat on the knight. }
*

