[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "FinchEye(Marieke)  vs. Edumcmates, Chess.com 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ For the model games, I picked games at different levels of play. I share crushing victories of my chess students rated under 1600 as well as games from top grandmasters. Also, I will show how the talented 18-year old world number 2 Firouzja and the 2021 World Cup winner Duda lost after getting a difficult position against our repertoire. Two of the model games are mine and show a nice victory as well as a painful loss, which contains a powerful learning message for you on how to study chess openings. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5
{ Our signature knight-hunting move. } 5... Ng4 6. O-O Be7 7. Re1 O-O
{ Here Black makes the first big mistake, even though Black is playing a very logical move.   7...d6  8.exd6  Qxd6  was better.  As we know from the course this is stronger for Black. Now the knight on g4 can jump back to f6. We learned in the course that White has the strong  9.b3  preparing to attack the queen with Ba3 and we will regain the d4-pawn. }
8. h3
{ We hunt the knight again! It's thematic in our repertoire that we mercilessly keep on hunting these knights. }
8... Nh6 9. Bxh6
{ By capturing the knight we give Black doubled pawn and weaken their king. }
9... gxh6 10. Nxd4
{ Until this point we studied the variation in the course. My student Marieke @@StartBracket@@FinchEye@@EndBracket@@ managed to win the game in only three more moves. Black's king is very weak due to the doubled h-pawns. }
10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 b6
{ A logical move that develops the bishop. However, it is a big mistake. My student found the best way to punish this mistake. }
12. Qe4 { Attacking the rook and also preparing mate. } 12... c6 13. Bd3
{ Black already resigned because Qxh7 mate is coming.   Black could have played  13...f5  to avoid getting mated immediately; however, after  14.exf6  the position is hopeless. A great and quick victory by my chess student Marieke! It's incredible that Black only made two mistakes which seemed like logical moves, and still lost the game so quickly. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Tsroth93(Tom) vs. azazel46, Chess.com 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's now have a look at a game from my student Tom @@StartBracket@@Tsroth93@@EndBracket@@, who faced the 4...Bc5 variation in the Scotch Gambit. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Bc5 5. Ng5 Nh6 6. Nxf7 Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7
8. Qh5+ g6 9. Qxc5
{ So far, Black found all the only moves. We know our dangerous preparation didn't finish yet. }
9... Re8 10. Qd5+
{ Tom knows how to punish Black for the first mistake, checking the king and protecting the e4-pawn. }
10... Kg7 11. Bg5 Ne7
{ By far the most popular move at the 1600-level and White is winning now. As covered in the course Black's best bet would have been  11...Rxe4+  12.Qxe4  Qxg5  13.O-O  when White would also have a big advantage. }
12. Qxd4+ Kg8 13. Nc3
{ We studied until this point in the course. Tom remembered that we shouldn't play  13.Bh6  going for Qg7 mate immediately since  13...Nf5  forks the queen and the bishop and defends against the mate. }
13... c6
{ Black defends against the threat of Nd5! Having a winning position doesn't automatically mean that you won the game. Now Tom was out of book and he misplayed the position a bit. Tom has three active pieces: the queen, bishop, and knight.  The best move would be  14.O-O-O  safeguarding the king and also activating the rook. After that,  Tom would be ready to go for the plan of Bh6 and Qg7 mate since castling prevents Black's ...Nf5 defensive idea. }
14. Qc4+ Kg7
{ 14...d5  is the strongest move, attacking the queen and activating the bishop. After  15.Qb3  the d-pawn is pinned and White still has a great position. }
15. e5
{ 15.O-O-O  would have been the strongest move again, safeguarding the king and activating the rook on the d-file. }
15... Qa5 16. Bf6+ { Giving a check and protecting the e5-pawn. } 16... Kf8 17.
O-O { White's king is super safe, while Black's king remains in big trouble. }
17... Ng8 18. Qf4 { Threatening discovered check with Bd8 to win the queen. }
18... Nxf6 19. exf6 { Black's position is collapsing. } 19... Qe5 20. Qh6+ Kf7
21. Qg7+ Ke6 22. Rfe1
{ Pinning and winning the queen. Tom's opponent resigned the game here. A crushing victory by Tom. Move 14 was a key moment where he could have improved, when he decided to move his well-placed queen again instead of castling, safeguarding his king, and activating his rooks. Regardless of that, the advantage after the opening was so big that Black couldn't recover from that. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black " Juan Carlos Leon vs. Martín Leonardo De la Cruz Navarro, Villa Ballester 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now, we will see four games where the white player was a big favorite with at least 300 points higher rating than Black.   This game is in the Alapin, where we will have the 1600-mainline 2.Nc6 and the key knight-hunting idea. The games show how an 1800-player loses control from the opening onward and is unable to recover from that during the game. }
1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 d6 5. d5
{ Our signature knight-hunting move. } 5... Ne5 6. f4
{ Hunting the knight again. This was covered in the course. } 6... Nd7
{ Black's knight already moved for the third time, and now it is in a position where it is blocking Black's light-squared bishop. }
7. Nf3 Nc5
{ Black's knight already move for the fourth time and all other major pieces are still in the starting position. }
8. Nc3 Bg4 { Pinning the knight. } 9. h3
{ Forcing Black to capture the knight. } 9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 g6 11. Be3 Bg7 12.
e5
{ A prophylactic move. White prevents Black from developing the knight on the kingside. Because of that, Black also is unable to castle. Even stronger would be  12.Bxc5  dxc5  13.Bb5+  Giving a powerful check to prevent Black from castling  13...Kf8  14.e5  Blocking the dark-squared bishop.   When we directly play  12.Bb5+  Black can still block with  12...Nd7  . }
12... a6 { Preventing Bb5+. } 13. Bxc5 dxc5 14. d6 Qd7 15. Rd1 Rd8 16. g4
{ The idea is to prevent Black from developing with Nh6 and Nf5. Also, White can play Bg2 next, putting pressure on the b7-pawn. }
16... exd6
{ Even if Black would play  16...Nh6  preparing to castle White would strike with  17.Ne4  attacking the c5-pawn. Black is unable to castle without losing material. }
17. Ne4 { A lovely move bringing the knight into the attack. } 17... Qc6 18.
Rxd6 Rxd6 19. Nxd6+ Kf8 20. Qxc6
{ Preferably, you don't want to trade queens when you are the one who is attacking. In this case, though, it completely breaks the pawn structure on Black's queenside. }
20... bxc6
{ Please take a look at Black's pieces. Imagine you are playing with Black. What are you going to do? How will you ever activate your rook? White has a completely winning position. Prophylaxis was key to reaching this victory. }
21. Bc4
{ This is much stronger than  21.Bxa6  . White is threatening to capture the f7-pawn and after Nxf7 also the rook is trapped. }
21... Nh6 22. g5 Nf5 23. Nxf7 Rg8 24. Nd6 Nxd6 25. Bxg8 Kxg8 26. exd6
{ The remaining endgame is easily winning for White. } 26... Kf7 27. Ke2 Ke6
28. Rd1 Bd4 29. Kf3 Kxd6 30. Ke4 Ke6 31. b3 a5 32. h4 Bg7 33. Rd8 Bc3 34. Rc8
Kd7 35. Ra8 Kc7 36. Ra7+ Kb6 37. Rxh7 Kb5 38. Rb7+ Ka6 39. Rb8 Be1 40. f5 gxf5+
41. Kxf5 Bxh4 42. g6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Mauricio Ramirez Gonzalez vs. Alexander Roose, Aruba 2017 "]
[Result "*"]

{ This next game is also in the Alapin and shows that the knight-hunting idea also works in the Barmen Defense. This game was played between Gonzalez  (2188)  and Roose  (1935)  with classical time control in Aruba 2017. }
1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4 Nc6 6. Nf3 Nf6
{ A logical move, but it is a big mistake. } 7. Nc3
{ As we learned, we attack the queen first and then hunt the knight. } 7... Qd8
8. d5 { Our signature knight-hunting move. } 8... Nb8 9. Bb5+ Bd7
{ So far all was covered in the course, and here the recommendation was  10.Bxd7+  when after  10...Nbxd7  11.O-O  g6  12.d6  we are destroying our opponent! After  12...exd6  13.Re1+  Be7  14.Bh6  Black will never castle.  If Black decides to keep the d6-pawn alive, then Nb5-Nc7 will come soon with a devastating attack! The strongest computers evaluate this as +5. }
10. O-O
{ Even though this is not the best move and not the course recommendation, White maintains a big lead in development and has a large advantage. }
10... Bxb5 11. Nxb5 Na6
{ 11...Nxd5  doesn't work tactically due to  12.Qxd5  Qxd5  13.Nc7+  with a royal fork winning back the queen, and White remains a piece up. }
12. Qa4 { Setting up a big discovered attack. } 12... Nd7
{ 12...Qd7  wouldn't help  when  13.Ne5  @@StartBracket@@chasing away the queen and after the queen moves a deadly discovered attack is coming@@EndBracket@@  13...Qd8  14.Nc7#  is checkmate. }
13. Re1 { Preparing for a beautiful smothered mate. } 13... Nac5 14. Nd6#
{ And this is how a 1935-rated chess player got mated in 14 moves in a classical game. I don't think that Black missed the smothered mate. My guess is that it was a respectful way to resign and allow a beautiful mate. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Velimir Ivic vs. Velimir Tokarev, Chess.com 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is the game with the biggest rating difference. It is interesting to see the battle between grandmaster Ivic @@StartBracket@@rated 2548@@EndBracket@@ and amateur player Tokarev @@StartBracket@@rated 1438@@EndBracket@@. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bd7 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O
Nge7 9. b4
{ And the bishop is trapped. This was all covered here Even a couple of 2200+ players have fallen for this trick. Objectively, White has a winning position, but it still is instructive to watch how Ivic converts this position. }
9... Bxb4 10. cxb4 Nxb4 11. Be3 { Developing with tempo. } 11... Qd8 12. Bc5
{ Ivic is forcing some exchanges now that he is a piece up. } 12... Nxd3 13.
Qxd3 Rc8 14. Ba3
{ Ivic doesn't play  14.Bxe7  because the bishop is stronger than the knight in this position. White's dark-squared bishop is strong since it is attacking the knight and also makes sure that Black's knight is pinned once Black castled. It is also interesting to note that Ivic didn't grab the pawn with  14.Bxa7  , since the bishop would not be so active there. }
14... Qb6 15. Nd4 Rc4 16. Bxe7
{ The situation has changed; Black would need to recapture with  16...Kxe7  and that's why Ivic captures the knight now. }
16... Rxd4 17. Qa3
{ Defending the bishop! Black's king is stuck in the middle. } 17... Bb5 18.
Bc5 { Double attack on the queen and the rook! } 18... Qc6 19. Bxd4 Bxf1 20.
Nd2
{ 20.Kxf1  would be the first move to consider, however, Black can win the bishop on d4 and the pawn on e5. Therefore, Nd2 is a safer choice for White. After  20...Qc4+  @@StartBracket@@forking the king and the bishop@@EndBracket@@  21.Kg1  Qxd4  Black threatens mate as well as to capture the rook in the corner, but White can still defend against both threats:  22.Nc3  Qxe5  White remains with a winning advantage, though it was not necessary to allow such complications. }
20... Bc4 21. Bxa7 Kd7 22. Bd4 Rc8 23. Rc1 b5 24. Qg3
{ When we have a big advantage, trades are usually good. Ivic still doesn't play  24.Nxc4  .  The reason is that the bishop is pinned and cannot run away anyway. Ivic could also decide to trade later if he wants. }
24... g6 25. a3 Ra8 26. h3 { Avoiding a potential back rank mate. } 26... Qa6
27. Nxc4
{ Black's last move unpins the light-squared bishop, so that's why Ivic decided to trade now. }
27... bxc4 28. Rc3 Ke8 29. Qf4
{ Ivic did a very nice job of blocking the pawns and is now completely winning with a piece up. }
29... Qb5 30. Kh2 h5 31. Rf3 Qb7 32. Qf6 Rc8 33. Qh8+ Ke7 34. Qf6+ Ke8 35. Qh8+
Ke7 36. Rxf7+ { A tactical combination to finish the game. } 36... Kxf7 37.
Qh7+ { Winning the queen and Black resigned the game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Evgeny Alekseev vs. Iskander Nasibullin, St. Petersburg 2016"]
[Result "*"]

{ Alekseev shows in this game how easy it is to win a seemingly innocent advantage out of the Scandinavian opening. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4 Nc6 4. Nf3 { This was covered in the course. } 4...
e5
{ Black deviates from the main variations and immediately puts pressure in the center. }
5. Nc3
{ Developing and attacking the queen. Black doesn't have time to retreat with  5...Qd8  as we go for our signature knight-hunting move with  6.d5  and get a big lead in development. }
5... Bb4 { Black develops and pins the knight to safeguard the queen. } 6. Bd2
{ Developing and unpinning the knight to reinforce the threat to capture the queen. }
6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3
{ White recaptures with the bishop to protect the d4-pawn and threatens to win the e5-pawn. }
7... e4 8. Ne5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Be6
{ A logical development move. However, White keeps the initiative here. Black should have played  9...Ne7  with the idea that after  10.Qxd5  Nxd5  Black is threatening to capture the dark-squared bishop on c3 and give White doubled pawns. }
10. Qxd5 Bxd5 11. O-O-O { Castling and attacking! } 11... Bc6 12. Bc4
{ This is simply an excellent position for White, the bishops and rook on d1 are powerful. And the h1-rook is ready to join the game quickly. }
12... a5 13. Bd5
{ After trading Black's light-squared bishop, White can pick up the e4-pawn.  The strongest move is  13.e6  when our dark-squared  bishop is attacking the g7-pawn.  13...f6  is the only move to defend against both threats  14.Bd5  @@StartBracket@@White wants to exchange bishop and win the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@  14...Bxd5  15.Rxd5  and White is ready to play Re1 and Rxe4, with a winning position. }
13... Ne7 14. Bxc6+ Nxc6 15. Rhe1 O-O
{ 15...Ke7  would have been better. Since we are playing an endgame, it is important to have an active king. After castling, Black's king is out of play,  while on e7 it could have prevented White from entering the seventh rank with the rook. }
16. Rd7
{ A very nice move. White will win the e4-pawn anyway and also wants to enter the seventh rank and attack. There was no need to rush with  16.Rxe4  . }
16... Rfe8 17. Rxc7 Nxe5 18. Rxe4 Nc6 19. Rxe8+ Rxe8 20. Rxb7
{ White is gobbling up pawn after pawn after pawn. It is a matter of technique for grandmaster Alekseev. The endgame is completely winning. }
20... f6 21. Rb6 Ne5 22. b3 Ng4 23. a4 Re2 24. Bxa5 Rxf2 25. Bd2 Rxg2 26. a5
Ne5 27. a6 Nd7 28. Rd6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
