[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Fabiano Caruana vs. Alireza Firouzja, Riga 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ The current world number two Firouzja had an impressive year in 2021, winning the FIDE Grand Swiss and surpassing the 2800-rating barrier. The only game he did lose in the Grand Swiss, though, was his game against Caruana, mentioned by many as the world's best-prepared chess player. So what opening did Caruana choose to beat Firouzja? He playedour recommendation against the Caro-Kann. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ 7. Nd2
{ All moves that we covered in the course are on the board. } 7... e6 8. Ne2
{ Keeping the f3-square free for the other knight! } 8... Ne7 9. b4
{ A spectacular pawn sacrifice, breaking the pin on the knight. } 9... Qa6
{ Capturing the pawn with  9...Qxb4  would be too risky due to  10.Rb1  Qa5  11.Rxb7  when White's rook is strong on the seventh rank. }
10. Qb3 Nf5 11. Nf3
{ The idea of 8.Ne2 was to get the other knight to f3 which Caruana has just accomplished. Both knights are supporting the d4-pawn. }
11... Nd7 12. a4
{ White cannot castle yet, since Black's queen attacks the knight on e2. That's why Caruana plays against the queen on a6 and prepares a later b5 which would close the diagonal. }
12... Qc4 13. Bd2 { Developing and defending the d4-pawn. } 13... Qxb3 14. cxb3
f6 15. O-O Be7 16. g3 Kf7 17. Rfe1 fxe5 18. dxe5 Rac8 19. Nf4
{ White has a very nice position out of the opening. Black's king is stuck defending the e6-pawn. Still, Firouzja is by no means losing, and at the top-level, it is almost impossible to beat someone out of the opening in a classical game. }
19... d4 20. Rac1 c5 21. Nd5
{ A spectacular move. After  21...exd5  22.e6!  White wins back the knight on d7 and has an open file for the rook. }
21... cxb4 22. Nxe7 Nxe7 23. Ng5+
{ A big mistake. the rest of the game was quite complicated, but Caruana still won.   23.Bxb4  would have given Caruana a big advantage.  White plans to play Bd6 protecting the e5-pawn and subsequently can play Ng5+, attacking the king and the e6-pawn. }
23... Kg6 24. Rxc8 Rxc8 25. Nxe6 Nc6 26. f4 Kf5 27. Nxg7+ Kg6 28. Ne6 Kf5 29.
Ng5 Nc5 30. Nf7 Ke6 31. Nd6 Rg8 32. Kg2 Kd5 33. Rb1 Ne4 34. Nxe4 Kxe4 35. Rc1
