[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Midas Ratsma vs. Mikhail Tobak, Skalica 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ The last two model games I played myself, one quite nice victory and one very embarrassing loss. Both games were played in Slovakia, this one in 2021. I played Tobak, a thirteen-year-old talent from Ukraine rated 2087. }
1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6 7. Be3
{ This is a key move in the Alekhine. We don't want to play  7.Nf3  to avoid getting pinned with  7...Bg4  . }
7... Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Be2
{ Up to this point, we followed the theory in the course and have a fantastic position!! My preparation for the game went a little deeper. }
9... Qd7 10. Nf3 O-O-O 11. O-O Bg4
{ Black has three attackers on the d4-pawn and is threatening to eliminate my knight first and then win the pawn! }
12. c5 Nd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. b4
{ A lovely move which was still part of my preparation. The idea is to support the c5-pawn. }
14... Qe4
{ It looks logical to capture the pawn with  14...Nxb4  but this opens up the b-file and is very dangerous:  15.Rb1  a5  16.Rxb4  @@StartBracket@@this strong exchange sacrifice was still part of my preparation@@EndBracket@@  16...axb4  17.Qa4  and White has a massive attack and a winning position. }
15. Qd2
{ This shows the idea why 14.b4 was so strong: it is preventing Black from playing Bxc5. My d4-pawn is pinned and therefore unable to protect the c5-pawn. Black's dark-squared bishop is now completely out of play and the strongest cloud engines show that White already has a +4 advantage.   I will not go into detail about the rest of the game, in which I gave my opponent some counter-chances and still needed good endgame technique to convert the game into a full point. }
15... f6 16. h3 Bf5 17. Qc3 fxe5 18. Rad1 Nxb4 19. Ng5 Qc2 20. Qxb4 Qxe2 21.
Rde1 Qc2 22. Rf2 Qd3 23. Nf7 exd4 24. Rd2 Qe4 25. Bf2 Qd5 26. Re5 Qd7 27. Nxd8
Qxd8 28. Rxd4 Qe8 29. g4 Bg6 30. Bh4 b6 31. Rd8+ Qxd8 32. Bxd8 Bxc5+ 33. Rxc5
bxc5 34. Qxc5 Rxd8 35. Qxa7 Rd1+ 36. Kf2 Rd2+ 37. Kg3 Rd3+ 38. Kh2 Rd2+ 39. Kg1
Rd3 40. Qa6+ Kb8 41. Kh2 Rd2+ 42. Kg3 Rd3+ 43. Kh4 Rd6 44. Qb5+ Rb6 45. Qe5 Ra6
46. a4 Kb7 47. Kg3 Rd6 48. Qxg7 Rd3+ 49. Kh4 Rd5 50. Qb2+ Ka7 51. Kg3 e5 52. h4
Rd3+ 53. Kf2 e4 54. h5 e3+ 55. Kf3 Be8 56. Qc2 Rd7 57. Kxe3 h6 58. Qc5+ Kb7 59.
Qb4+ Ka7 60. Qf8 Bxh5 61. Qc5+ Kb7 62. gxh5 Rd6 63. Ke4 Re6+ 64. Kf5 Rb6 65. a5
Ra6 66. Ke5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Harry Grieve vs. Midas Ratsma, Skalica 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ The last game of the course will end shockingly! I am sharing my classical game against FM Harry Grieve in 2020 in Skalica, Slovakia. It was the final round of the tournament and we had both 5 points out of 8. The winner would earn prize money. A classical game lasts usually between 2 and 6 hours. How embarrassing would it be if you lose the last and most important game within two minutes of playing! This could have happened to me. Within two minutes after the game started, I had a dead-lost position. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ Just like in the French Defense, we are going for the Advance Variation. The idea is to prevent Black from developing without concerns. With e5, we take away the natural f6-square from Black's knight. }
3... Bf5 4. h4
{ This move requires some explanation. Why do we push a pawn instead of playing a standard developing move like  4.Nf3  ?   The idea behind this move is prophylactic. It is just as important that we prevent our opponent from developing as it is for us to develop our pieces.  4.h4  prevents Black from playing  4...e6  and subsequently developing all the pieces on the kingside and castling. }
4... h6
{ Black is making space to avoid getting the light-squared bishop trapped. } 5.
g4
{ What are we doing? Pushing our pawns? Pay attention, this is important. Again our play is prophylactic. Black needs to play e6 to develop the dark-squared bishop and eventually castle.   With 5.g4 we force Black to move the bishop either with 5... Bh7 @@StartBracket@@  5...Be4  6.f3  Bh7  is more or less the same@@EndBracket@@ or with 5...Bd7  .   After  5...Bh7  we play  6.e6  which ensures Black's pawn on e7 will not be able to move forward, which means that Black's dark-squared bishop will remain completely stuck.   Whereas after  5...Bd7  Black moves the bishop to a passive square and surrenders the whole Caro-Kann dream of getting a position in which Black's light-squared bishop is out of the pawn chain. }
5... Be4 6. f3 Bh7 7. e6
{ A brilliant idea! We prevent Black forever from playing e6 and ensure the Black's dark-squared bishop is completely stuck. }
7... Qd6 8. exf7+ Kxf7 9. f4
{ We learned the theory until here.  We are defending against Qg3+ and preparing to get our knight on a beautiful outpost on e5. Also, we would like to trade Black's strong light-squared bishop with Bd3. White has a nice position.   My opponent FM Harry Grieve blitzed out all the moves and so did I! We continued blitzing a couple of moves more. }
9... Nf6 10. Nf3 Nxg4 11. h5
{ The strongest move according to the best cloud engines! We both spent a lot of time preparing. The idea is that White can play Bh3 next, attacking the knight, and Black can no longer defend with h5. }
11... Qe6+ 12. Ne5+ Nxe5 13. fxe5 g5
{ A massive blunder. We reached this position one minute after the game started. Now my position with Black is dead-lost. Can you find the win for White? }
14. hxg6+
{ It's unbelievable that both my move 13...g5 and 14.hxg6 were played within 2 seconds.  Both of us mixed up the moves from our preparation which went @@StartFEN@@rn3b1r/pp2pkpb/2p1q2p/3pP2P/3P4/8/PPP5/RNBQKB1R b KQ - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Ke8  14.Nc3  g5  15.hxg6   But now after  14.Bh3!!  Bf5  15.Bxf5  Qxf5  16.Rf1  White is pinning and winning the queen. If this happened I would have resigned the game immediately after two minutes of playing. }
14... Qxg6 15. Rh2 Ke8 16. Nc3 Na6 17. Rg2 Qe6 18. Bxa6 bxa6 19. Qh5+ Qf7 20.
Qe2 e6 21. Qxa6 Qc7 22. Na4 Be4 23. Rh2 Rg8 24. Be3 Rg3 25. Kd2 Bxc2
{ A big mistake! Capturing this pawn is too dangerous since my light-squared bishop was an important defensive piece blocking the f-file. Instead  25...Rb8  would have been much better with an equal position with chances for both sides. }
26. Kxc2 Rxe3 27. Rf1 Rb8 28. Rg2 Rb4 29. Rxf8+ Kxf8 30. Qf1+
{ White's attack is devastating and I resigned. So why do I show you my most embarrassing game as the last model game, instead of a crushing victory?   This game taught me @@StartBracket@@and hopefully also will teach you@@EndBracket@@ a super important lesson. We shouldn't remember any computer moves without understanding them. I often made this mistake too and blundered horribly or simply forgot the variations a few days later.   Do you feel like you remember all the moves? Or do you feel like you both remember and understand all the ideas? My advice is to go for the last option and slowly rewatch the videos or read again all the ideas when repeating the move trainer. I firmly believe, and the statistics of over 50 million games support it, that you can crush 80% of 1600-level opponents with our attacking repertoire. I encourage you to be a hard-working student who focuses on both understanding and remembering the moves. If you have any questions regarding the course, you can leave a comment and I will respond. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Jones, Gawain vs. Amin, Bassem, ACP ChessBase KO 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ I updated the course with ten more model games! In this game, GM Jones showed how to outplay GM Bassem in the Scotch Gambit. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian opening. Jones decides to transpose back to the Scotch gambit.   3.d4  This is the move order recommended in the course. The game reached the same position again from 5.e5  3...exd4  4.Bc4  Nf6  5.e5 }
3... Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 10.
f3 Ng5 11. Be3
{ In the course I recommend the immediate 11.f4 which is covered here. Jones transposed back to the variation in the course one move later. }
11... Bb6 12. f4 Ne4 13. Nd2 Nxd2 14. Qxd2
{ This was all covered in the course till here. } 14... c5 15. Nf3 Bf5
{ Black puts the bishop on a more active square and blocks future attacking play with f5. }
16. a4 { Jones threatens 17.a5 to trap the bishop. } 16... d4
{ A significant mistake from Black. Now that the bishop is on f5, White wants to play Bf2 and Nh4, chasing away the bishop to continue the attack.   16...a5  This would be the strongest move to prevent White from playing a5 and trapping the bishop.   16...a6  It would be a mistake for Black to allow White to play a5 and b4.  17.a5  Ba7  18.Bf2  O-O  19.b4  An amazing strategical idea. White wants to free the d4 square for the knight. There it would target the light-squared bishop and help to start an attack with f5-f6.  19...cxb4  20.Bxa7  Rxa7  21.Qxb4  White has an advantage since we can place the knight on d4 and the queen on c5. }
17. Bf2 a5 { Black prevents us from trapping the bishop. } 18. h3
{ A significant mistake. Jones wants to prepare g4 to chase away the bishop and start attacking on the kingside. This wasn't necessary since White can also attack the bishop immediately.   18.Nh4  This is much stronger attacking the bishop.  18...Qd7  Black doesn't want to give up control over the f5-square.   18...Bd7  Would give up the control over the f5-square.  19.f5  We can continue with our attack! It's the typical plan to march the f-pawn in the Scotch 4...Nf6 variations.  19...O-O  Casteling would be too dangerous for Black.  20.f6  The typical mating idea in the Scotch Gambit!  20...gxf6   20...Re8  Would be a big blunder allowing our mating idea.  21.Qg5  Threatens Qxg7 mate.  21...g6  22.Qh6  We will play Qg7 mate next, and Black cannot defend against it.  21.Nf3  We are threatening Bh4 pinning the f6-pawn when after Bxf6 we attack the queen and trap the king in a deadly mating net.  21...fxe5  22.Bh4  Attacking the queen and getting the bishop to f6 to threaten mate.  22...f6   22...Qe8  23.Bf6  The king is trapped in a deadly mate net, and Black cannot defend against Qg5 or Qh6-Qg7 mate.  23.Nxe5  We capture the pawn since the f6-pawn is pinned. White has a winning position as Black's kingside is under severe pressure.  19.Nxf5  We are happy to trade the defending bishop. Typically the queen is not a good piece to form a blockade.  19...Qxf5  20.Rae1  O-O  21.b3  Black wants to play c4 to activate the dark-squared bishop. We want to stop this. Now White is ready to start attacking with h3-g4. }
18... Qd5
{ The queen is powerful in the center and prevents Jones's idea to play  19.g4  since Black can play  19...Qxf3 }
19. Rac1 Qc4
{ A big mistake since White already wanted to play b3 and can do that now with a tempo.  19...O-O-O  or  19...Bxh3  would have been stronger. }
20. b3 { Attacking the queen and protecting the a4-pawn. } 20... Qb4 21. Qd1
{ A great decision from Jones to avoid the trade of queens. As our king is safer, we want to keep the queens on the board to keep our attacking chances alive. }
21... O-O-O 22. Be1 { Jones chases the queen to a worse square. } 22... Qa3 23.
Nd2
{ Jones reroutes the knight to the c4-square. Here it is placed perfectly as Black's pawns cannot attack the knight and prevents Black from playing ...c4. Black's position is quickly collapsing. }
23... Qa2 24. Nc4
{ The knight is placed perfectly, leaving Black's dark-squared bishop doomed behind the c5-pawn. }
24... d3 25. Qf3 Kb8
{ 25...dxc2  White has a devasting attack here.  26.Qa8+  26...Kd7  27.Nxb6+  White's knight is much stronger than the bishop. Still trading it is the best move, allowing White to continue with a devasting kingside attack on the seventh rank after the c-pawn disappeared from the seventh rank.  27...cxb6  28.Qb7+  28...Ke8  29.Bh4  Threatening Qe7 mate as well as to capture the rook. Black has almost no defenders, and its pieces are discoordinated. }
26. Bxa5
{ Grabbing a pawn and adding another attacker. White has a crushing attack and won the game comfortably. }
26... Ba7 27. Qc6 Rd7 28. Bd2 Rd4 29. Ra1 Qxc2 30. Rfc1 Rxc4 31. Rxc2 Rxc2 32.
Ba5 Rc8 33. Kh2 Re2 34. Re1 Rc2 35. Rd1 Re2 36. Qb5+ Ka8 37. Rxd3 Bxd3 38. Qxd3
Rf2 39. Qa6 Kb8 40. Kg3 Rb2 41. Qb5+ Ka8 42. Bc3 Rc2 43. Qd3 Ra2 44. Qb1
{ Black resigned as after  44...Ra3  45.Qb2  or  44...Re2  45.Kf3  the rook is trapped. }
