[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar vs. Corrales Jimenez, Fidel, chess.com Titled Tuesday 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ We will have a look at a game from Azerbaijan grandmaster Mamedyarov the current number 9 in the world. He played against grandmaster Corrales in an online blitz game in Titled Tuesday. This game shows typical plans in the Alapin Barmen's defense. }
1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 { These positions were covered here. }
4... e6
{ This is a little bit calmer move from Black, which has not been covered in the course. Memedyarov replies in a great way. }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3
{ As we cannot develop the knight to c3, Mamedyarov aims to go Nb5-Nc7 with a royal fork. }
6... cxd4 7. Nb5
{ typically, we don't have to recapture the pawn since we are threatening Nc7+ with a royal fork. }
7... Qd8 8. Qxd4
{ A sneaky move from Mamedyarov. He offers a trade of queens since he wants to eliminate Black's queen from defending the c7 square. }
8... Bd7
{ 8...Qxd4  This is the most played move and a significant mistake.  9.Nfxd4  White threatens the fork with Nc7.  9...Na6  Black is forced to develop the knight to the edge of the board where it is misplaced.  10.Bf4  White is ready to develop the bishop to f3 and castle. }
9. Bf4 { Threatening the fork with Nc7+. } 9... Nd5
{ Black defends against the fork and threatens the bishop on f4. } 10. O-O-O
Nc6
{ 10...Nxf4  Capturing the bishop would be a big mistake.  11.Qxf4  White threatens Nc7+ forcing Black to develop the knight to the edge of the board. Knights are better placed in the center as they can jump to more squares.  11...Na6  12.Ne5  Winning the pinned bishop. }
11. Qxd5
{ A cool queen sacrifice. This is unfortunately not the best move, but White keeps the advantage.   11.Qe4  This is objectively better; however less entertaining than the queen sacrifice Mamedyarov played. We threaten Rxd5 as the e6-pawn is pinned.  11...Be7  12.Nd6+  Black is in trouble since after a trade on d6 Black would be unable to castle. }
11... exd5 12. Nc7+
{ Giving Black the option to return the queen or misplace its king. } 12... Ke7
{ 12...Qxc7  Giving back the queen would have been a wise decision for Black, even though the position remains problematic with the isolated d-pawn.  13.Bxc7  Be6  White is also having all the fun here and can attack with Ng5, Bb5, and Rhe1. }
13. Nxd5+ { Capturing the pawn and forcing Black to retreat. } 13... Ke8 14.
Nc7+
{ A key move! Forcing Black's king back to e7 makes sure that Black's queen and dark-squared bishop are blocked }
14... Ke7 15. Bc4
{ A beautiful move! Even though White is a queen down, they develop the bishop. They are threatening to play Rhe1+ with a deadly check. }
15... Qc8 16. Rhe1+
{ 16.Bg5+  This would also win  16...f6  17.Rhe1+  White brings the other rook into the game with a devastating effect.  17...Kd8  18.Ne6+  The check forces Black's king back to the e-file.  18...Ke7  Now White has the windmill tactic. Black's king cannot escape from the checks, and our knight can repeatedly gain material by creating a series of unescapable checks.  19.Nxg7+  Kd8  20.Ne6+  Ke7  Now we have the same position again where we won the g7-pawn.  21.Nxf8+  Kd8   21...Kxf8  Wouldn't work  22.Bh6  Mate!  22.Ne6+  Ke7  And again White reaches the same position where White won another bishop.  23.Nc5+  Kd8  24.Bxf6+  Gaining another pawn with a check  24...Kc7  25.Rxd7+  Qxd7  Black has to give up the queen to prevent mate.  26.Nxd7  White regained the queen and is up a lot of material. White has a winning position. }
16... Kd8
{ This leads immediately to mate   16...Kf6  Would have been a better try! The king is still walking in a minefield, and White can continue the attack.  17.Nd5+  Kg6  18.Nh4+  Chasing the king further up the board.  18...Kh5  19.Ne3  White threatens Rd5 and Bg3 mate! }
17. Re8#
{ A brilliant game. The final position shows that Mamedyarov managed to active all pieces and made them cooperate nicely. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Grischuk, Alexander vs. Moskalenko, Alexander, chess.com Titled Tuesday 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this model game, the current Grischuk, the current world number 17, wins against grandmaster Moskalenko. Grischuk shows a great understanding of the opening in this structure, which we can frequently get against the French. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Bd7 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O
Qc7 9. Re1
{ Grischuk deviates from my course recommendation to play  9.b4  covered here. 9.Re1 is a sound alternative. }
9... Nge7 10. Nbd2 Ng6 11. Nb3
{ Opening up the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop. } 11... Bb6 12. Qe2
{ Supporting the e5-pawn. } 12... O-O
{ It doesn't make much sense to develop the dark-squared bishop as it isn't attacking anything after  13.Bg5  or  13.Bd2  and  13.Be3  would lose the pawn after  13...Ngxe5  14.Bxb6  Nxf3+  15.Qxf3  Qxb6  . The bishop is one of the view pieces that can be pretty strong on the starting square without development. The dark-squared bishop keeps an eye on the h6-square and can assist in an attack with the h-pawn. }
13. Nbd4 a6
{ 13...Nxd4  This trade would benefit White since the center will be stronger. White has a better position because of the space advantage and the stronger bishop. White's light-squared bishop is dangerous in the attack, whereas Black's dark-squared bishop looks at the d4-pawn. Typically Black would like to trade a light-squared bishop in this structure since Black's light-squared bishop is misplaced as it is locked in within the pawn chain.  14.cxd4  Since White controls the center, we can safely start a kingside attack. }
14. h4
{ A typical attacking move in this structure. Grischuk aims to march the pawn to h6, weakening Black's king. A trade of pawns would open Black's king, and after ... g6, White can aim to get the queen toward g7 and deliver mate. }
14... f6
{ Black doesn't want to wait quickly and counterattacks in the center. This significantly weakens the e6-pawn. }
15. Bxg6
{ Black was threatening to play ...Ngxe5. That's why Grischuk eliminated the knight to be able to protect the e5-pawn sufficiently. Grischuk doesn't want to play  15.exf6  , since after  15...Rxf6  , the rook is defending the e6-pawn. }
15... hxg6 16. Bf4
{ Grischuk supports the e5-pawn. Black's king is significantly weakened because Blacked played ...f6. }
16... Nxd4 17. Nxd4
{ 17.cxd4  Capturing with the pawn would be a sound alternative. } 17... Bxd4
18. cxd4 f5 19. Rac1
{ Grischuk develops the rook to the open c-file with tempo. } 19... Qa5 20. Qe3
{ 20.h5  Would have been the strongest to blow open Black's king's position.  20...gxh5  21.Qxh5  Qxa2  Grabbing the pawn would be too greedy for Black.  22.Re3  All White's pieces are ready for the kingside attack, and Black has not enough defenders. }
20... Rfc8
{ 20...Qxa2  Grabbing this pawn would be too greedy! White can now start attacking with the rook on the seventh rank.  21.Rc7  Bc6  The bishop shouldn't sidestep. The rook is now attacking g7. White wants to attack the g7-pawn more often, so first wants to remove the g6-pawn.  22.h5  Forcing the g6-pawn to capture us.  22...gxh5  23.Bh6  White adds the bishop to the attack. Black will get mated if they capture the bishop.  23...Rf7  24.Rxf7  Kxf7  25.Qg5  gxh6  26.Qf6+  Even though Black is a piece up, White is winning here. Black has no defender for the king. White can slowly pick up all the pawns with the queen and bring the rook into the attack to deliver mate. The next variation shows how the game could continue, however White has many ways to win here.  26...Kg8  27.Qxe6+  Kg7  28.Qf6+  Kh7  29.Qxf5+  Kh8  30.Qxh5  Qxb2  31.Qxh6+  Kg8  32.Qg6+  Kh8   32...Kf8  This wouldn't work either.  33.e6  Mate will follow soon.  33.Re3  Rh3 is coming next, and White wins the game. It's a typical motif to mate with a queen and rook. A queen and rook or two rooks can control the last two files of the board, not allowing the king any escape. }
21. Qg3 Kf7 22. Qb3 Bb5 23. a3 Qa4 24. Qe3
{ An instructive moment. Grischuk declines the trade of queens since White's king is safer. If your king is safer, you shouldn't trade queens to keep the attacking chances. }
24... Rc2 { A big blunder! } 25. Rxc2
{ 25.b3  Interposing the defense of the queen on the rook would win the game. What Grischuk played also resulted in a winning position. }
25... Qxc2 26. Rc1
{ Getting the rook with tempo on the open c-file. Black cannot avoid that White's rook will come to the seventh rank with a devastating effect. }
26... Qxb2 27. Rc7+ Kg8 28. Qg3 Be8 29. h5
{ A cunning move bringing another piece into the attack. } 29... Qb6 30. Re7
Qxd4
{ Black threatens Qd1+ to win the h5-pawn. Grischuk has to be careful and sidestep with the king. }
31. Kh2 Qc5 32. Qh4 Rc8 33. h6
{ Black's king is helpless with no defender around them. } 33... gxh6 34. Qf6
{ Mate will follow soon. Black resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Howell, David vs. Crispin Ferreras, Darvi Abraham; chess.com Titled Tuesday 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h6 5. g4 Bh7 6. e6 fxe6 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3
Nf6 9. Nf3
{ Howell deviates from the recommendation in the course to play  9.Qg6+  covered here. What Howell played also gives White a significant advantage, but it is slightly less precise. }
9... Qd6 10. Ne5
{ Planning to go for a deadly check with Qg6 followed by a fork with Nf7 }
10... Ne4 11. f3
{ Chasing away the knight. Black cannot move the knight is Qg6 is deadly. }
11... Nd7 12. fxe4 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qxe5
{ Howell is a piece up. It is instructive to see how we convert this position. The priority is to get the king to safety by castling queenside. }
14. Nc3 { Developing and defending the d4-pawn. } 14... O-O-O 15. Bd2
{ Getting ready to castle and consolidate, but Black has other plans. } 15...
dxe4 16. Qxe4
{ Howell wasn't worried about allowing ...Qg3+ as Black has not enough attackers to create serious problems.   16.Qe3  This would have been my choice. We prevent ...Qg3+ and get ready to castle safely. Later we can pick up the e4-pawn. }
16... Qg3+ 17. Ke2
{ This is better than  17.Kd1  , which wouldn't allow the a1-rook to join the game. The rest of the game is a matter of technique. It's interesting to see how Howell converts this winning position. }
17... g5 18. hxg5 Bg7 19. Rag1 Qd6 20. Bf4 e5 21. Be3 hxg5 22. Rh5
{ I like this choice from Howell. Surely you are familiar with the rule that you want to trade pieces once you are up. By trading pieces, you reduce your opponent's counter-chances. So why didn't Howell capture the rook on h8?   22.Rxh8  I think it is a good decision from Howell not to trade rooks. White would trade the strong rook on the h-file and give up control over the h-file.  22...Rxh8  White now has to worry about Black's rook entering the position on h2. Still, White would have a winning position here. However, trading the rooks made life slightly more difficult for us. It's beneficial to trade pieces once we are up in material . However, we shouldn't make trades that benefit our opponent more than us. }
22... Kb8 23. Bxg5 Bf6 24. Be3
{ Howell decides again not to trade the bishop and retreat. This is a decision I like.   24.Bxf6  Trading the bishop would improve Black's pawn structure.  24...exf6  Black got rid of the doubled pawns now and did benefit from the trade. }
24... Rxh5 25. gxh5 Qe6 26. h6 Qh3 27. Rh1
{ The rook is supporting the past pawn. } 27... Qg3 28. Qf3
{ At this point, Howell is willing to trade queens. The trade of queens would be a trade that comes without any downsides for White. That's why it would make it easier to covert the winning position into a victory as it takes away Black's counter-chances. }
28... Qg6 { Black understandably refuses the trade of queens. } 29. Ne4
{ Defending against ...Qxc2+ } 29... Bh8 30. Rg1 Qe6 31. b3
{ Defending against ...Qc4+. Howell keeps the position under control and doesn't give Black any counter-chances. }
31... Qd5 32. h7 Qb5+ 33. Kf2 Qa5 34. Rg8 Bf6 35. Nxf6 exf6 36. Qxf6
{ Black resigned. Also, here Howell didn't trade rooks on the previous move with  36.Rxd8  Qxd8  .  White's rook is stronger than Black's rook as it prevents Black from defending the last rank. Black cannot prevent us from promoting to a queen when our rook is on g8. Also Black wouldn't be able to capture the rook on g8 as we would recapture and promote to a queen. What is instructive about this game is that Howell showed that to convert a winning position to victory, we should avoid making trades that favor our opponent. When there is no downside in trading pieces, we benefit from this when we have a material advantage since it reduces our opponents' chances to fight back in the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Midas Ratsma vs. Monkeyking37, Chess24 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ On the 6th of May, Chess24 invited me to give the Banter Blitz show. The idea of Banter Blitz is to provide commentary and share all my thought while playing the games. In every game, I played the openings covered in this course. Let's have a look at the first game. }
1. e4 c5 2. c3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bc4
{ The course explains here why  4.d4  is less strong. } 4... Be7 5. O-O Nf6 6.
d4 { Putting pressure in the center before Black is ready to consolidate. }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 8. e5
{ The signature knight-hunting move. Which we see so frequently in the Scotch, Petrov, and Alapin. }
8... Ng4 9. Re1 { Supporting that e5-pawn and Black's knight is in trouble. }
9... O-O 10. h3 { Kicking that knight to the edge of the board. } 10... Nh6 11.
Bxh6 { Weakening the pawn structure near Black's king. } 11... gxh6 12. Nxd4
{ Regaining the pawn. So far I played the opening perfectly. This variation is very similar to the variation we also get in the Scotch Gambit. We use the idea to hunt the knight and keep on hunting the knight, forcing it to the edge of the board. }
12... d5 13. Nxc6
{ This trade is favorable for Black since the d5-pawn gets more protection and ...Rb8 would give Black counterplay on the b-file.   13.exd6  The en-passant capture would have been the best here.  13...Qxd6  14.Nxc6  bxc6  Black is forced to weaken the pawn structure.  15.Qf3  An instructive move. Since White's king is much safer than Black's king, we want to avoid the trade of queens. White has a significant advantage due to the safer king and better pawn structure. }
13... bxc6 14. Bd3 Kh8 15. Bc2
{ It looks like a powerful idea to build a battery with the bishop and queen and go for mate. Unfortunately, the attack is too slow as Black can place a rook on g7 and queen on g8. Therefore it would have been better to continue development instead.   15.Nc3  Developing the knight would be better. This also allows me to activate the rook on the queenside quicker. }
15... Rg8 { Pinning the g2-pawn so Black threatens ...Bxh3 } 16. Qd3
{ Threatenening mate! } 16... Rg7
{ Black defends against the mate and also prepares ...Qg8 putting pressure on the g2-pawn. }
17. Re3 { Getting the rook over to g3 to counter Black's rook on the g-file. }
17... Qg8 18. Rg3 Rxg3 19. fxg3 Be6 20. Nd2
{ Developing the knight and also getting ready to activate the rook. } 20...
Qg7 21. Kh2 Rg8 22. Rf1 Qg6 23. Qc3
{ A good decision to sidestep with the queen.   23.Qxg6  Trading queens would be a significant mistake as it allows Black to get a strong pawn structure again.  23...hxg6  This endgame would be very comfortable for Black. Black doesn't have weaknesses and can start attacking our b and e-pawns. }
23... Qg5 24. Rf3 { Getting more support for the g3-pawn. } 24... c5 25. Nf1 d4
26. Qd3 Qg7 27. b3 Bd5 28. Rf5 Bg5 29. h4
{ A big blunder in time trouble! As the g-pawn is pinned, Black can capture the pawn. }
29... Be6
{ A big blunder from Black. The two bishops are much stronger than the rook.   29...Bxh4  Black can capture the pawn for free since after  30.gxh4  Qxg2#  is mate. White cannot capture the bishop, so Black has a significant advantage. }
30. hxg5 Bxf5 31. Qxf5 hxg5 32. Nd2
{ My queen and bishop are already doing a great job putting pressure on h7. That's why I also want to bring the knight into the attack. }
32... h5 33. Ne4 h4 34. g4 Qh6 35. Qxf7
{ My opponent lost on time here, but the position is winning for White either way. You can watch the game with commentary here: @@LinkStart@@https://youtu.be/0iHazTB6l14@@LinkEnd@@. }
