[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Ratsma, Midas vs. Oopskitty, Chess24 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 d6 5. Nxd4
{ So far, we have covered this in the course here. } 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bf4
{ Our dark-squared bishop is stronger than Black's dark-squared bishop, which is locked in by the d6-pawn.   7.Nxc6  bxc6  Trading the knight would weaken Black's pawn structure slightly. It would be difficult for White to exploit this weakness, though, as we cannot attack the c6-pawn so easily. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Nxe4
{ Black relies on a tactic trick. After White captures the knight ...d5 regains the piece with a fork. }
9. Nxe4 d5 10. Nxc6
{ Now, the trade of knights is much more effective than before. As it leaves Black with weak a and c-pawns. Because the e4 pawn and d6-pawns are also traded, it is much easier for White to attack the weak c-pawns. }
10... bxc6 11. Bd3
{ An important move. The light-squared bishop is typically powerful, and we want to keep it. }
11... dxe4 12. Bxe4
{ The opening went very well for me. White has an almost decisive advantage here as the c-pawns are under enormous pressure. }
12... Bd6 13. Bxc6
{ I missed here that after  13...Bxf4  14.Bxa8  Black has  14...Ba6  attacking the bishop in the corner and the rook on f1. White still has a better position; however, it would have been much stronger to first trade the bishops before grabbing the c6-pawn.   13.Bxd6  This is much stronger! White wins the c-pawn and has a winning position.  13...cxd6  14.Bxc6  White is a pawn up. Also, Black's d6-pawn is weak and cannot be protected by any other pawns.  14...Rb8  15.b3  The last move consolidates White's pawns on the queenside. }
13... Rb8 { My opponent missed that opportunity. } 14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. b3 Be6 16.
Qd2
{ 16.c4  Would be strong to fix the weak d6-pawn. Black cannot play ...d5 to be on a safer square anymore. }
16... d5 17. Rad1 Qc7
{ This is strong for Black. Black now forces a favorable pawn trade by exchanging their d5-pawn for our c2-pawn. With this trade, Black gets rid of one pawn island. }
18. Bxd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Qxc2 20. Rd2
{ Regaining control of the second rank and defending the a2-pawn. } 20... Qg6
21. Rfd1 h5 22. Qd4
{ 22.Qa5  This is stronger as it is targetting the a7-pawn and not allowing it to move forward. }
22... a6 23. h3 Rb5 24. Rd3
{ An inaccuracy since after ...Rg5, I have to weaken the pawn structure around my king with g3.   24.Qd6  This would have been strong to propose a trade of queens. }
24... Rg5 25. g3 Re8 26. Kg2 Re4 27. Qd6 Re6 28. Qb8+ Kh7 29. Rd8
{ This threatens mate, but it ignores Black's counterplay.   29.Qa8  This would have been best! A prophylactic move to defending against ...Qe4+ }
29... Qe4+ 30. Kh2 Qf3
{ Black is threatening ... Qxf2+ and White has to allow a weak pawn structure to defend. }
31. Qf4
{ The trade weakens White's pawn structure, but it is necessary to safeguard the king. }
31... Qxf4 32. gxf4 Rf5 33. Kg3 Re4 34. R8d5 Rexf4 35. Rxf5 Rxf5 36. b4 Rb5 37.
a3 a5 38. Rb1 axb4 39. axb4 g5 40. Kf3 f5 41. Ke3 g4 42. hxg4 fxg4 43. Kd4
{ I should have realized here that White can never try to play for a win. It's safer to keep the king on the queenside to defend against the pawns. }
43... Kg6 44. Kc4 Rb8 45. b5 h4 46. Kd4
{ 46.Kd3  Would have been much safer getting the king back to f1. } 46... Kf5
47. Ke3
{ The computer claims that other moves still make a draw like  47.b6  . However, Black has better chances to play for a win here. }
47... g3
{ This immediately trades off to a drawn endgame.   47...Re8+  A cunning check forcing White's king back to the d-file. With precise play, the position would be winning for Black now.  48.Kd2  h3  Black can start running with the h-pawn now.  49.b6  Kf4  Black's king gets closer to support the h-pawn and win the f2-pawn.  50.b7  h2  51.Rh1  g3  52.fxg3+  Kxg3  53.Rb1  Kg2  White is lost here. Black's h-pawn is about to promote.  54.b8=Q  Rxb8  55.Rxb8  h1=Q  The resulting queen versus rook endgame is winning for Black. }
48. fxg3 hxg3 49. Kf3 Ke5 50. Kxg3 Kd5 51. Kf3 Kc5 52. Rc1+
{ One last trick. After  52...Kxb5?  53.Rb1+  wins the rook. } 52... Kb6 53.
Rb1 Ra8 54. Ke4 Ra5 55. Kd4 Rxb5 56. Rxb5+ Kxb5
{ Unfortunately, I couldn't convert the fantastic position after the opening. Credits to my opponent for defending well. You can watch the game with my commentary here: @@LinkStart@@https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-yKn4CeuEhA@@LinkEnd@@. }
