[White "24. Model Games"]
[Black "Ratsma, Midas vs. Fuentes, Lilia, Chess24 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was also played in my Banter Blitz session. I faced Woman Internanational Master Lilia Fuentes from Mexico. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Nf3
{ This was covered in the course here. } 8... c5
{ I can capture the pawn since the bishop is pinned. } 9. dxc5 Nc6 10. Nc3 a6
11. O-O Qc7
{ Black unpins the bishops and threatens ... Bxc5. That's why I should defend the pawn. }
12. Na4 Bxg5 13. hxg5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5
{ So far, I played the opening very well. However, I missed a big opportunity here. It was dangerous for Black to capture the e5-pawn. }
15. Nb6
{ 15.f4  Would give White a crushing attack.  15...Qe4  It's best for Black to trade queens as otherwise, the king would be in danger. After the trade of queens, the e4-pawn will be lost.  16.Qxe4  dxe4  17.Nb6  Rb8  18.Nc4  The knight is aiming to give a deadly check on d6. White will win the e4-pawn and has a winning position. }
15... Rd8
{ By playing Nc5, I lost the protection of the c5-pawn. After  16.f4  Qc7  Black  now threatens ...Qxc5, and White doesn't have time to continue the attack immediately. }
16. g6 { Aiming to weaken Black's king. } 16... Nf6 17. Rfe1 Qg5 18. gxf7+ Kxf7
19. Re3 h4 20. Rae1
{ A nice move to activate the sleeping rook and put pressure on the e6-pawn. }
20... h3 21. Rxh3 Rxh3 22. Qxh3 e5 23. c4
{ 23.Nc8  This would have been a brilliant move to reroute the knight to the strong d6-square. On d6, the knight is on a strong outpost close to Black's king, and the c5-pawn defends it. }
23... d4 24. Qf3 { Again  24.Nc8  would have been the best. } 24... d3
{ 24...e4  Black can gain a tempo on the queen and support the d-pawn to run forward safely. }
25. Nd5
{ 25.Qxb7+  It would be best to grab this pawn. I didn't play this as I was scared that the d-pawn would run forward and my queen would no longer cover the promotion square. However, Black cannot sufficiently support the pawn after  25...Kg6  26.Nd5  . }
25... d2
{ 25...e4  would have been stronger to chase the queen away from the f3-square. }
26. Rd1 e4 27. Qe3
{ Blocking Black's queen from defending the d2-pawn. White will win the d-pawn now and has a significant advantage. }
27... Nxd5 { A big blunder for Black in time trouble. } 28. Qxg5
{ Black resigned the game. You can watch the game with commentary here @@LinkStart@@https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a9KZqj3g8-s@@LinkEnd@@. }
