[Black "MrBastK(Bas) vs. fravit99, online 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this online Blitz game, my chess student Bas  (1364)  played against fravit99  (1364)  . }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c4
{ Now that the knight lands on c6, Bas starts hunting the queen. The course covered this variation here. }
5... Qd8 6. d5 { The signature knight-hunting move. } 6... Nb8 7. Nc3 Bg4 8.
Be2 c6
{ It's not advisable to capture since after  9.dxc6  Qxd1+  10.Bxd1  Nxc6  Black develops the knight to the active c6 square. }
9. O-O
{ White gained a massive lead in development. This is because White won 2 tempi with the knight hunt. Also, we won tempi on Black's queen. }
9... Qc7 10. h3
{ Bas wants to encourage Black to trade their light-squared bishop. } 10... h5
{ A tricky and spectacular move which we will also see in my upcoming Black course. Black's idea is that after  11.hxg4  hxg4  , the rook is active on the h-file and  12.Nd4?  Qh2  would lead to a mate. A similar idea where Black used this strategy and played ...h5 is covered here. }
11. Qd4
{ Bas foresaw that it would be dangerous to capture the bishop. During our chess lessons, we discussed this idea with ...h5, so Bas was aware of what Black was doing. Qd4 is cunning as it threatens to play Bf4 chasing the queen away from the dangerous diagonal, after which White can capture the bishop without any risk. }
11... Nbd7
{ Black still insisted on the plan to sacrifice the bishop, which is no longer working. It would have been better to play  11...Bxf3  and trade the bishop. Either way, White has a winning advantage. }
12. Bf4 { Bas first chases away the queen before grabbing the bishop. } 12...
Qc8 13. hxg4
{ It's completely safe to capture the bishop now as the rook on the h-file cannot pose any threats without the help of the queen. }
13... hxg4 14. Ng5 c5 15. Qe3 Nb6 16. Rad1
{ Bas also involves the other rook in the game. } 16... Qf5
{ Black still plans to bring the queen to the h-file and threaten mate. } 17.
Qe5
{ This move I don't like too much. As White is ahead a lot, it's clear that White would be happy to trade queens to reduce Black's counterplay. Unfortunately, this move doesn't force Black to trade queens, and Black can still continue with the plan to get the queen to the h-file and threaten mate. Stronger would have been  17.Nb5  threatening a rook on the king and the rook with Nc7+. }
17... Qg6 18. d6
{ Bringing the pawn into the attack. After  18...Qh5  White can still defend with  19.f3  making an escape square for the king. }
18... e6 19. Bxg4
{ A blunder as it gives up the bishop for free. White has to be precise after  19...Nxg4  20.Qxc5  as Black can threaten mate with  20...Qh5!  White should block with the knight on the h-file to defend against mate. The knight is currently pinned as the queen on  c5  is undefended. So White should first play  21.Qb5+  moving the queen to a protected square with a check, and after  21...Nd7  22.Nh3  White keeps a winning advantage. }
19... O-O-O
{ A big mistake from Black! White has a powerful tactic to win the game. } 20.
d7+ { Opening up the diagonal for the queen and bishop while giving a check. }
20... Nbxd7 21. Qc7#
{ An amazing victory from Bas. He was many tempi's up from the opening by using the signature knight-hunting plan. Bas always maintained a winning advantage after the opening, even though he made two big mistakes at the end of the game. }
