[Black "NuriRaja(Jur) vs. NIM2021, online 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played by my student Jur. } 1. e4 b6 { The Owen's defense } 2.
d4 Bb7 3. Bd3
{ As discussed in the course, this move is important. In the previous game, when Jur faced this opening, he played  3.Nc3  , and after  3...e6  4.Bd3  Bb4  he ran into this annoying pin and later lost the e4-pawn and the game. }
3... e6 4. Nf3 { So far everything is covered in the course here. } 4... Be7 5.
O-O { White has a fantastic center. } 5... a5 6. c4
{ A nice move to further strengthen the center. } 6... Nf6 7. Re1
{ The immediate knight-hunting idea with  7.e5  is best! After  7...Ne4  White can keep on hunting the knight with  8.Re1  . }
7... c5 8. e5 { Jur still goes for the knight hunt, a great move. } 8... Ng4
{ As we have seen often, we can keep on hunting this knight with  9.h3  when after  9...Nh6  10.Bxh6  gxh6  Black has a severely weakened pawn structure, decreasing their king safety.   The computer claims that  9.d5  is even stronger with the idea of shutting down Black's light-squared bishop. After  9...exd5  10.Bf5  Nh6  11.Bxh6  gxh6  12.cxd5  White has a positionally winning position. }
9. Be4
{ A mistake, but White still keeps a significant advantage. Black should try  9...Bxe4  10.Rxe4  and  10...f5  attacking the rook and defending the knight. }
9... d5 { A big blunder! Maybe Black forgot about the en-passant capture. } 10.
exd6 Bxe4 11. dxe7
{ A cunning move! Jur is still attacking the queen and bishop and will gain a piece. }
11... Qxe7 12. Rxe4 cxd4 { Black even gives up on another piece. } 13. Rxg4 O-O
14. Rxd4 Nc6 15. Rd2 Rad8 16. b3
{ A dangerous move to play as  16...Qf6  traps the rook in the corner, and White cannot defend with  17.Bb2  as  17...Qxb2  18.Rxb2?  Rxd1  leads to mate.  17.Ba3  counterattacking the rook on  f8  is better; however, Black still regains a piece after  17...Qxa1  18.Bxf8  Rxd2  19.Nfxd2  Kxf8  . }
16... g6 17. Bb2 e5 18. Nc3 f6 19. Qe2 Rfe8 20. Nd5 Qd6 21. Nxb6 Nd4 22. Nxd4
exd4
{ Double attack on the queen and knight. Black regains one piece, but White's advantage was already so big that White keeps a winning advantage either way. }
23. Qd3 Qxb6 24. Bxd4 Qc7 25. g3 Rd6 26. Rad1 h5 { This gives up the g6-pawn. }
27. Qxg6+ Qg7 28. Qxe8+
{ Black resigned. A good victory from Jur. In the opening, he managed to get an amazing center against Owen's defense, and his opponent never mentioned fighting back in the game. Congratulations you have made it to the end of the course! If you have any questions feel free to share them and I will reply as soon as possible. Also, repetition is key for learning so it's always good to refresh the variations and tactics. Lots of luck in your games! }
